INSERT INTO `Proof` VALUES (8,'','<ul>\r\n<li>\r\n\\((\\Rightarrow)\\)<br/>\r\nSuppose that \\(f\\) is continuous at \\(x\\) and let \\(\\epsilon \\lt 0\\). Then there exists \\(\\delta \\gt 0\\) such that\r\n\\[|y - x| \\lt \\delta \\Rightarrow |f(y) - f(x)| \\lt \\epsilon\\]\r\nBut for any \\(i\\) in the range \\(1 \\leq i \\leq k\\) we have \\(|f_i(y) - f_i(x)| \\leq |f(y) - f(x)|\\) showing that each \\(f_i\\) is continuous at \\(x\\).\r\n<br/><br/><br/>\r\n</li>\r\n<li>\r\n\\((\\Leftarrow)\\)<br/>\r\nSuppose that each \\(f_i\\) is continuous at \\(x\\) and let \\(epsilon \\gt 0\\). Then there exist \\(\\delta_i \\gt 0\\) such that\r\n\\[|y - x| \\delta_i \\Rightarrow |f_i(y) - f_i(x)| \\lt {\\epsilon \\over n}\\]\r\nSet \\(\\delta = \\min \\delta_i\\), and then we have\r\n\\[|y - x| \\lt \\delta \\Rightarrow |f(y) - f(x)| = \\sqrt{\\sum_{i=1}^n {|f_i(y) - f_i(x)|}^2} \\lt {\\sqrt{n} \\epsilon \\over n} \\leq \\epsilon\\]\r\n</li>\r\n</ul>',48),(9,'','<ol>\r\n<li>\r\nLet \\(z\\in B(a,\\epsilon)\\), then \\(|z-a|\\lt\\epsilon\\) so \\(\\delta={\\epsilon-|z-a|\\over 2}\\gt0\\). Therefore for any \\(w\\) s.t. \\(|z-w|\\lt\\delta\\), \\(|w-a|\\lt|w-z|+|z-a|\\lt\\epsilon\\). So \\(B(z,\\delta)\\subset B(a,\\epsilon)\\)\r\n<br/><br/><br/>\r\n</li>\r\n<li>\r\nLet \\(U_i, ..., U_m\\) be (finitely many) open subsets of \\(\\mathbb{R}^n\\). Let \\(x \\in \\bigcap_{i=1}^m U_i\\).<br/>\r\nThen for all \\(1 \\leq i \\leq m\\) there exist \\(\\epsilon_i \\gt 0\\) such that \\(B(x, \\epsilon_i) \\subset U_i\\). Let \\(\\epsilon = \\min \\{\\epsilon_1, ..., \\epsilon_m\\} \\gt 0\\) and then \\(B(x, \\epsilon) \\subset \\bigcap_{i=1}^m U_i\\).\r\n<br/><br/><br/>\r\n</li>\r\n<li>\r\nFor \\(i \\in I\\) (a not-necessarily finite indexing set), let \\(U_i\\) be an open subset of \\(\\mathbb{R}^n\\). Let \\(x \\in \\bigcup_{i \\in I} U_i\\)<br/>\r\nThen there exists \\(i \\in I\\) such that \\(x \\in U_i\\) and \\(\\epsilon_i \\gt 0\\) such that \\(B(x, \\epsilon_i) \\subset U_i\\).\r\nThen \\(B(x, \\epsilon_i) \\subset U_i \\subset \\bigcup_{i \\in I} U_i\\)\r\n</li>\r\n</ol>',52),(10,'','Note that \\(x\\) is an interior point of \\(\\mathbb{R}^n \\setminus S\\) if and only if \\(x\\) is not a limit point of \\(S\\).<br/>\r\nSo...<br/>\r\n<br/>\r\n\\(S\\) is closed<br/>\r\n\\(\\Leftrightarrow \\mathbb{R}^n \\setminus S\\) is open<br/>\r\n\\(\\Leftrightarrow\\) every point of \\(\\mathbb{R}^n \\setminus S\\) is an interior point<br/>\r\n\\(\\Leftrightarrow\\) no point of \\(\\mathbb{R}^n \\setminus S\\) is a limit point of \\(S\\)<br/>\r\n\\(\\Leftrightarrow S\\) contains all its limit points',55),(11,'','Suppose \\(x\\) is a limit point of \\(S\\) and suppose for a contradiction that \\(x\\) is an interior point of \\(\\mathbb{R}^n \\setminus S\\).<br/>\r\nThen\r\n\\[\\forall \\delta \\gt 0, \\exists y \\in S&nbsp;s.t.&nbsp;0 \\lt |x - y| \\lt \\delta\\]\r\nand\r\n\\[\\exists \\delta \\gt 0&nbsp;s.t.&nbsp;B(x, \\delta) \\subset \\mathbb{R}^n \\setminus S\\]\r\nThis is the contradiction as there is a point in \\(S\\) that is arbitrarily close to \\(x\\), so there cannot be a ball around \\(x\\) not in \\(S\\).',56),(12,'','<ul>\r\n<li>\r\n\\((\\Rightarrow)\\)<br/>\r\nSay \\(f\\) is continuous at \\(x \\in \\mathbb{R}^n\\) and \\(x_k \\to x\\).<br/>\r\nLet \\(\\epsilon \\to 0\\), by continuity of \\(f\\) at \\(x\\),\r\n\\[\\exists \\delta :s.t. |y - x| \\lt \\delta \\Rightarrow |f(y) - f(x)| \\lt \\epsilon\\]\r\nby convergence of \\(x_k\\)\r\n\\[\\exists K \\in \\mathbb{N} s.t. k \\geq K \\Rightarrow |x_k - x| \\lt \\delta\\]\r\n\\[then \\forall k \\geq K, |f(x_k) - f(x)| \\lt \\epsilon\\]\r\n<br/><br/><br/>\r\n</li>\r\n<li>\r\n\\((\\Leftarrow)\\)<br/>\r\nSuppose \\(f(x_k) \\to f(x)\\) whenever \\(x_k \\to x\\) but \\(f\\) is not continuous\r\n\\[\\exists \\epsilon \\gt 0 s.t. \\forall \\delta \\gt 0, \\exists y \\in \\mathbb{R}^n s.t. |y - x| \\lt \\delta but |f(y) - f(x)| \\geq \\epsilon\\]\r\nTake \\(\\delta = {1 \\over k}\\) to get \\(x_k\\) s.t. \\(|x_k - x| \\lt \\delta\\) and \\(|f(x_k) - f(x)| \\geq \\epsilon\\)<br/>\r\nso \\(x_k \\to x\\) but \\(f(x_k) \\not\\to f(x)\\)<br/>\r\nThis is a contradiction to a supposition at the start.\r\n</li>\r\n</ul>',57),(13,'','<ul>\r\n<li>\r\n\\((\\Rightarrow)\\)<br/>\r\nSuppose, firstly that \\(f\\) is continuous.<br/>\r\nSay \\(U \\subset Y\\) is open in \\(Y\\) and take \\(x \\in f^{-1}(U)\\),<br/>\r\nthen \\(f(x)\\) is interior to \\(U\\) so there is \\(\\epsilon \\gt 0\\) s.t. \\(B_Y(f(x), \\epsilon) \\subset U\\).<br/>\r\nBy continuity of \\(f\\), \\(\\exists \\delta \\gt 0\\) s.t. \\(f(B_X(x, \\delta)) \\subset B_Y(f(x), \\epsilon) \\subset U\\).<br/>\r\nSo \\(B_X(x, \\delta) \\subset f^{-1}(U)\\) showing \\(x\\) is interior.<br/>\r\nSo \\(f^{-1}(U)\\) is open.\r\n<br/><br/><br/>\r\n</li>\r\n<li>\r\n\\((\\Leftarrow)\\)<br/>\r\nSuppose the preimage of all open sets is open.<br/>\r\nThen take \\(x \\in X\\), so \\(B_Y(f(x), \\epsilon)\\) is open in \\(Y\\).<br/>\r\nSo \\(x \\in f^{-1}(B_Y(f(x), \\epsilon))\\) which is open in \\(X\\),<br/>\r\nso \\(x\\) is interior to it.<br/>\r\nSo \\(\\exists \\delta \\gt 0\\) s.t. \\(B_X(x, \\delta) \\subset f^{-1}(B_Y(f(x), \\epsilon))\\),<br/>\r\nso \\(f\\) is continuous at \\(x\\)\r\n</li>\r\n</ul>',58),(14,'','Suppose \\(ab = 0\\) and \\(ac = 1\\),<br/>\r\nthen \\(0 = ab = (ab)c = (ac)b = 1b = b\\)<br/>\r\nso if \\(a \\neq 0\\) then \\(a\\) is not a zero-divisor.',64),(15,'','\\(ab = ac\\)<br/>\r\n\\(\\Rightarrow ab - ac = 0\\)<br/>\r\n\\(\\Rightarrow a(b - c) = 0\\)<br/>\r\n\\(\\Rightarrow b - c = 0\\)<br/>\r\n\\(\\Rightarrow b = c\\)',66),(16,'','<ol>\r\n<li>Proof is trivial</li>\r\n<li>The function \\(b \\mapsto ab\\) is one-to-one for any \\(a \\in R \\setminus \\{0\\}\\).<br/>\r\nIf \\(R\\) is finite then the functinos is also onto and hence invertible.<br/>\r\nSo \\(\\forall a \\in R \\setminus \\{0\\}, \\exists b\\) s.t. \\(ab = 1\\) so \\(R\\) is a field.</li>\r\n</ol>',67),(17,'','Suppose \\(a\\) is prime and \\(a = bc\\), then \\(a|bc\\) so \\(a|b\\) or \\(a|c\\).<br/>\r\nWithout loss of generality say \\(a|b\\) and \\(b = ad\\), then \\(a = bc = adc\\) so \\(dc = 1\\) so \\(c\\) is a unit and \\(a\\) is irreducible.',69),(18,'','<ol>\r\n<li>\r\n\\((1 \\Rightarrow 2)\\)<br/>\r\nIf \\(a = bc\\) and \\(c\\) is not a unit, suppose \\(cd = 1\\).<br/>\r\nthen \\(ad = bcd = b1 = b\\) so \\(a|b\\) and \\(b|a\\)\r\n<br/>\r\n<br/>\r\n<br/>\r\n</li>\r\n<li>\r\n\\((2 \\Rightarrow 1)\\)<br/>\r\nIf \\(a|b\\) and \\(b|a\\), then \\(\\exists c,d \\in R\\) s.t. \\(a = bd\\), \\(b = ac\\),<br/>\r\nso \\(a = bd = acd\\) so \\(cd = a\\) so \\(a\\) is a unit multiple of \\(b\\)\r\n</li>\r\n</ol>',70),(19,'','Suppose \\(X,Y \\leq V\\), \\(V = X \\oplus Y\\), \\(u \\in X\\), \\(v \\in Y\\),\r\n\\[P_{X,Y}(P_{X,Y}(u+v)) = P_{X,Y}(u) = u = P_{X,Y}(u+v)\\]',98),(20,'Preimage of continous functions','Say \\(U\\) is an open subset of \\(Z\\), then \\((g \\circ f)^{-1}(U) = f^{-1}(g^{-1}(U))\\) which is open as \\(f,g\\) are continuous.<br/>\r\nTherefore \\(f \\circ g\\) is continuous.',101),(21,'','<ol>\r\n<li>\r\n<ul>\r\n<li>\r\n\\((\\Rightarrow)\\)<br/>\r\nSay \\(S\\) is open in \\(T\\), then \\(\\forall s \\in S, \\exists \\epsilon_s \\gt 0\\) s.t. \\(B_T(s, \\epsilon_s) \\subset S\\),<br/>\r\nso \\(\\bigcup_{s \\in S} B_T(s, \\epsilon_s) = S\\) so set \\(U = \\bigcup_{s \\in S} B(s, \\epsilon_s)\\)\r\n<br/><br/><br/>\r\n</li>\r\n<li>\r\n\\((\\Leftarrow)\\)<br/>\r\nConversely, say \\(S = U \\cap T\\), \\(U\\) is open,<br/>\r\ntake \\(s \\in S \\subset U\\), so \\(\\exists \\epsilon \\gt 0\\) s.t. \\(B(s, \\epsilon) \\subset U\\),<br/>\r\n\\(B(s, \\epsilon) \\cap T \\subset U \\cap T = S\\)\r\n</li>\r\n</ul>\r\n<br/><br/><br/>\r\n</li>\r\n<li>\r\nFollows from the above\r\n</li>\r\n</ol>',102),(22,'Intervals are connected','Any interval is connected by the previous proof.<br/><br/>\r\nSuppose \\(S \\subset \\mathbb{R}\\) with \\(x \\lt y \\lt z\\) and \\(x,z \\in S\\) but \\(y \\not\\in S\\), then \\((-\\infty, y) \\cap S\\) and \\((y, \\infty) \\cap S\\) are non-empty open sets that partition \\(S\\), so \\(S\\) is not connected.',105),(23,'Intervals are connected','If not, then \\(f^{-1}(-\\infty, 0)\\) and \\(f^{-1}(0, \\infty)\\) are open and disjoint and partition \\([a, b]\\), contradiction as \\([a, b]\\) is connected.',107),(24,'','Let \\(C\\) be an open and closed subset of \\([a, b]\\) containing \\(a\\).<br/>\r\nWe aim to show that \\(C = [a, b]\\).<br/>\r\n<br/>\r\nLet \\(W = \\{x \\in [a,b] : [a,x] \\subset C\\}\\), firstly \\(a \\in W \\neq 0\\) and \\(W\\) is bounded above by \\(b\\) so that we can set \\(c = sup(W)\\).<br/>\r\nSo there are points \\(x \\in C\\) arbitrarily close to \\(c\\) s.t. \\([a,x] \\subset C\\).<br/>\r\nTaking the union of these, we see that \\([a,c) \\subset C\\).<br/>\r\nHence as \\(C\\) is closed, \\(c \\in C\\) as \\(c\\) is a limit point, so \\(c \\in W\\).<br/>\r\nSay \\(x \\in W\\), \\(x \\lt b\\), but \\(C\\) is open so there is \\((x - \\epsilon, x + \\epsilon) \\subset C\\).<br/>\r\nHence \\([a, x + {\\epsilon \\over 2}] \\subset C\\) so \\(x + {\\epsilon \\over 2} \\in W\\).<br/>\r\nThis contradicts the supremum unless \\(c = b\\), so \\(C = [a,b]\\) and \\([a,b]\\) is connected.',106),(25,'contradtiction','Let \\(A,B\\) be non-empty open subsets of \\(f(X)\\) which partition it.<br/>\r\nAs \\(f\\) is continuous, \\(f^{-1}(A)\\), \\(f^{-1}(B)\\) are open, non-empty and\r\n\\[f^{-1}(A) \\cap f^{-1}(B) = f^{-1}(A \\cap B) = \\emptyset\\]\r\n\\[f^{-1}(A) \\cup f^{-1}(B) = f^{-1}(A \\cup B) = X\\]\r\nHence \\(f^{-1}(A)\\), \\(f^{-1}(B)\\) partition \\(X\\), contradicting its connectedness.<br/>\r\nHence \\(f(X)\\) is connected.',109),(26,'','Say \\(X\\) is path connected and \\(f : X \\to \\mathbb{Z}\\) is continuous.<br/>\r\nTake \\(x,y \\in X\\), \\(\\gamma:[0,1] \\to X\\) a path between them.<br/>\r\nThen \\(f|_{\\gamma([0,1])}\\) is constant as \\(\\gamma([0,1])\\) is connected.<br/>\r\nIn particular \\(f(x) = f(y)\\), hence \\(f\\) is constant, so \\(X\\) is connected.',111),(27,'','Let \\(X \\subset \\mathbb{R}^n\\) be open and connected, take \\(x \\in X\\).<br/>\r\nLet \\(U\\) be the path component of \\(x\\).<br/>\r\nTake \\(y \\in U\\), as \\(X\\) is open, \\(\\exists \\epsilon \\gt 0\\) s.t. \\(B(y, \\epsilon) \\subset X\\), but then we can follow a radius from \\(y\\), so \\(B(y, \\epsilon) \\subset U\\).<br/>\r\nSo \\(U\\) is open but also all other path components are open. The complement of \\(U\\) is a union of path components and hence is open.<br/>\r\nSo \\(U\\) is both open and closed and by connectedness \\(U = X\\).',112),(28,'','Let \\(U\\) be an open cover of \\([a,b]\\), let \\(W = \\{x \\in [a,b] : [a,x]&nbsp;has&nbsp;a&nbsp;finite&nbsp;subcover\\}\\).<br/>\r\nAs \\(U\\) is a cover, \\(a \\in X\\) for some \\(X \\in U\\), so \\(a \\in W\\).<br/>\r\nSo we can set \\(c = sup(W)\\). By the approximation property, \\([a, c-\\delta]\\) has a finite subcover in \\(U\\) for any \\(\\delta \\gt 0\\).<br/>\r\nAs \\(U\\) is an open cover \\(\\exists V \\in U\\) s.t. \\(c \\in V\\).<br/>\r\nAs \\(V\\) is open, \\(\\exists \\epsilon \\gt 0\\) s.t. \\((c - \\epsilon, c + \\epsilon) \\subset V\\), so \\([a,c]\\) has a finite subcover as \\([a, c - {\\epsilon \\over 2}]\\) has one.<br/><br/>\r\nBut, arguing similarly to this, if \\(x \\in W\\) and \\(x \\lt b\\), then we can see that \\(x + \\epsilon \\in W\\) for some \\(\\epsilon \\gt 0\\).<br/>\r\nTherefore the only possibility that does not contradict the supremum is that \\(c = b\\).<br/>\r\nTherefore \\([a,b]\\) is compact. ',116),(29,'','\\[(I - E)^2 = I - 2E + E^2 = I - 2E + E = I - E\\]',117),(30,'','\\[E(I-E) = EI - E^2 = E - E = 0\\]',118),(31,'','Let \\(v \\in V\\), then \\(v = Ev + (v - Ev)\\),\r\n\\[Ev \\in im(V)\\]\r\n\\[E(v - Ev) = E(I - E)v = 0 \\Rightarrow v - Ev \\in ker(E)\\]\r\n<br/>\r\nLet \\(v \\in im(E) \\cap ker(V)\\),<br/>\r\nthen \\(v = Ew\\) for some \\(w \\in V\\) and \\(Ev = 0\\),\r\n\\[so&nbsp;0 = Ev = E^2w = Ew = v \\Rightarrow im(E) \\cap ker(E) = \\{0\\}\\]\r\n<br/>\r\nFinally, if \\(v \\in im(E)\\), then \\(Ev = E^2w = Ew = v\\),\r\n\\[so&nbsp;E|_{im(E)} = id_{im(E)}\\]',119),(32,'','Let \\(E : V \\to V\\) be idenpotent, then \\(V = im(E) \\oplus ker(E)\\)<br/>\r\nThen \\(\\forall v \\in im(E) \\cup ker(E)\\), \\(E(v) = P_{im(E), ker(E)}(v)\\) and as \\(im(E) \\cup ker(E)\\) spans \\(V\\), \\(E = P_{im(E), ker(E)}\\)',120),(33,'','If \\(v \\in V\\), then write \\(v = x + y + z\\) where \\(x \\in X\\), \\(y \\in Y\\), \\(z \\in Z\\).<br/>\r\n\\[Then&nbsp;(P_{X,Y+Z} + )_{Y,X+Z})(v)\\]\r\n\\[= (P_{X,Y+Z} + P_{Y,X+Z})(x+y+z)\\]\r\n\\[= x + y\\]\r\n\\[= P_{X+Y,Z}(x+y+z)\\]\r\n\\[= P_{X+Y,Z}(v)\\]',121),(34,'','(linear independence)<br/>\r\nSuppose \\(\\alpha_1f_1 + ... + \\alpha_nf_n = 0\\), then \\((\\alpha_1f_1 + ... + \\alpha_nf_n)(e_j) = \\alpha_j \\Rightarrow \\alpha_j = 0\\). So all \\(\\alpha_1 = ... = \\alpha_n = 0\\).<br/><br/>\r\n(spanning set)<br/>\r\nIf \\(f \\in V\'\\) then \\(f\\) and \\(\\alpha_1f_1 + ... + \\alpha_nf_n\\) where \\(a_i = f(e_i)\\) agree on the basis \\(\\{e_1, ..., e_n\\}\\), so they are equal.',126),(35,'','Define \\(\\Phi : V \\to V\'\'\\) so that \\(\\forall v \\in V,&nbsp;\\forall f \\in V\',&nbsp;\\Phi(v)(f) = f(v)\\).<br/>\r\n<br/>\r\n(Want that \\(\\Phi(v) \\in V\'\'\\))<br/>\r\ndomain of \\(\\Phi(v) = V\'\\), range of \\(\\Phi(v) = \\mathbb{F}\\)<br/>\r\n\\(\\Phi(v)(\\alpha f + \\beta g) = (\\alpha f + \\beta g)(v) = \\alpha f(v) + \\beta g(v) = \\alpha \\Phi (v)(f) + \\beta \\Phi (v)(g)\\), so \\(\\Phi\\) is linear.<br/>\r\nTherefore \\(\\Phi \\in V\'\'\\)<br/>\r\n<br/>\r\n(Want that \\(\\Phi\\) itself is linear)<br/>\r\n\\(\\Phi (\\alpha u + \\beta v)(f) = f(\\alpha u + \\beta v) = \\alpha f(u) + \\beta f(v) = \\alpha \\Phi (u)(v) + \\beta \\Phi (v)(f)\\)<br/>\r\nThis is for all \\(f \\in V\'\\), so \\(\\Phi(\\alpha u + \\beta v) = \\alpha \\Phi(u) + \\beta \\Phi (v)\\)<br/>\r\n<br/>\r\n(Want that \\(\\Phi\\) is 1-1)<br/>\r\nSuppose \\(u \\in ker(\\Phi)\\), \\(u \\neq 0\\),<br/>\r\nby extending \\(\\{u\\}\\) let \\(\\{u, u_2, ..., u_n\\}\\) be a basis for \\(V\\), let \\(\\{f_1, ..., f_n\\}\\) be the corresponding dual basis.<br/>\r\nThen \\(\\Phi(u)(f_1) = f_1(u) = 1 \\neq 0\\)<br/>\r\nThis is a contradiction, therefore \\(\\ker(\\Phi) = \\{0\\}\\) so \\(\\Phi\\) is 1-1.<br/>\r\n<br/>\r\n(Want that \\(\\Phi\\) is onto)<br/>\r\n\\(dim(V\'\') = dim(V\') = dim(V)\\)<br/>\r\n\\(ker(\\Phi) = \\{0\\}\\) so \\(dim(ker(\\Phi)) = 0\\)<br/>\r\nSo by the rank-nullity formula, \\(dim(im(\\Phi)) = dim(V) = dim(V\'\')\\),<br/>\r\nso \\(\\Phi\\) is onto<br/>\r\n<br/>\r\nTherefore \\(\\Phi\\) is an isomorphism.',128),(36,'','\\(U^\\circ \\neq \\emptyset\\) as the zero map is in \\(U^\\circ\\).<br/>\r\nIf \\(f,g \\in U^\\circ\\), \\(\\alpha, \\beta \\in \\mathbb{F}\\), \\(u \\in U\\), then\r\n\\[(\\alpha f + \\beta g)(u) = \\alpha f(u) = \\beta g(u) = 0 + 0 = 0\\]',130),(37,'','If \\(f \\in W^\\circ\\), then \\(f(w) = 0\\) for all \\(w \\in W\\) and hence for all \\(w \\in U\\), so \\(f \\in U^\\circ\\)',132),(38,'','Let \\(\\{u_1, ..., u_m\\}\\) be a basis of \\(U\\), extend to \\(\\{u_1, ..., u_n\\}\\) a basis for \\(V\\).<br/>\r\nLet \\(\\{f_1, ..., f_n\\}\\) be a dual basis for \\(V^\\circ\\), then \\(\\{f_{m+1}, ..., f_n\\}\\) is a dual basis for \\(U^\\circ\\).<br/>\r\nIf \\(i \\gt m\\) and \\(j \\leq m\\) then \\(i \\neq j\\) so \\(f_i(u_j) = 0\\), \\(f_i(v) = 0\\) for all \\(v\\) in a basis of \\(U\\), so \\(f_i \\in U^\\circ\\).<br/>\r\n<br/>\r\n(Linear independence is trivial)<br/>\r\n<br/>\r\n(Spanning)<br/>\r\nSuppose \\(f \\in U^\\circ\\), say \\(f = \\alpha_1 f_1 + ... + \\alpha_n f_n\\), if \\(i \\leq m\\), \\(f(u_i) = 0\\), so \\((\\alpha_1 f_1 + ... + \\alpha_n f_n)(u_i) = 0\\), so \\(\\alpha_i = 0\\).<br/>\r\nSo \\(f = \\alpha_{m+1} f_{m+1} + ... + \\alpha_n f_n \\in span\\{f_{m+1}, ..., f_n\\}\\).<br/>\r\n<br/>\r\nSo \\(dim(U^\\circ) = n - m = dim(V) - dim(U)\\)',133),(39,'','Let \\(U = \\{B(0, n) : n \\in \\mathbb{N}\\}\\) be an open cover for \\(C\\), then because \\(C\\) is compact there exists \\(n_1 \\lt ... \\lt n_k\\) such that \\(\\{B(0, n_1), ..., B(0, n_k)\\}\\) is a finite subcover.<br/>\r\nBecause the balls are all nested, \\(C \\subset B(0, n_k)\\), so \\(C\\) is bounded.',135),(40,'','Suppose for a contradiction that there is a limit point \\(x \\not\\in C\\).<br/>\r\nLet \\(U_r = \\{y \\in \\mathbb{R}^n : |x-y| > r\\}\\) which are all open sets.<br/>\r\nAs \\(C \\subset \\bigcup_{n=1}^\\infty U_{1 \\over n}\\), then because \\(C\\) is compact, there exists a finite subcover \\(\\{U_{1 \\over n_1}, ..., U_{1 \\over n_k}\\}\\) where \\(n_1 \\lt ... \\lt n_k\\).<br/>\r\nSo \\(C \\subset \\bigcup_{i=1}^k U_{1 \\over n_i} = U_{1 \\over n_k}\\) which contradicts \\(x\\) being a limit point.<br/>\r\nTherefore \\(C\\) contains all its limit points and is closed.',136),(41,'','Let \\(\\{U_i : i \\in I\\}\\) be an open cover for \\(f(C)\\), then by continuity \\(\\{V_i = f^{-1}(U_i) : i \\in I\\}\\) is an open cover for \\(C\\).<br/>\r\nBy compactness there exists a finite subcover \\(\\{V_{i_1}, ..., V_{i_n}\\}\\).<br/>\r\nThen \\(\\{U_{i_1}, ..., U_{i_n}\\}\\) is a finite subcover of \\(f(C)\\), so \\(f(C)\\) is compact.',137),(42,'','\\((\\Rightarrow)\\)<br/>\r\n\\(f(C)\\) is compact, so bounded and closed and it contains its limit points.<br/>\r\n<br/><br/>\r\n\\((\\Leftarrow)\\)<br/>\r\nSuppose \\(C\\) were not bounded, then \\(z\\mapsto z\\) contradicts our assumption.<br/>\r\nSuppose \\(C\\) were not closed, say it has a limit point \\(a\\not\\in C\\), then \\(z\\mapsto{1\\over|z-a|}\\) contradicts our assumption.<br/>\r\nHence by the Heine-Borel theorem, \\(C\\) is compact',138),(43,'','Let \\(A \\subset C \\subset \\mathbb{R}^n\\) with \\(C\\) compact and \\(A\\) closed.<br/>\r\nLet \\(\\{U_i : i \\in I\\}\\) be an open cover of \\(A\\), then \\(\\{U_i : i \\in I\\} \\cup A^C\\) is an open cover for \\(C\\) and hence has a finite subcover \\(\\{U_j : j \\in J\\} \\cup A^C\\) where \\(J \\subset I\\) and \\(J\\) is finite.<br/>\r\nBut then \\(\\{U_j : j \\in J\\}\\) covers \\(A\\), so \\(A\\) is compact.',139),(44,'','\\((\\Rightarrow)\\)<br/>\r\nCompact \\(\\Rightarrow\\) closed and bounded already proved.<br/>\r\n<br/>\r\n\\((\\Leftarrow)\\)<br/>\r\nSay \\(C\\) is closed and bounded, then \\(C \\subset [a_1, b_1] \\times ... \\times [a_n, b_n]\\). We know the right hand side \"hyper-rectangle\" is compact, as \\(C\\) is closed within this set, \\(C\\) is compact.',140),(45,'','If \\(a \\in I\\), then because \\(0 \\in R\\), \\(a \\cdot 0 \\in I\\), so \\(0 \\in I\\)',146),(46,'','Suppose \\(R,S\\) are rings, \\(\\phi : R \\to S\\) is a ring homomorphism.<br/>\r\nThen \\(\\phi(0) = 0\\), so \\(ker(\\phi) \\neq \\emptyset\\)<br/>\r\nIf \\(a,b \\in ker(\\phi)\\), then \\(\\phi(a) = \\phi(b) = 0\\), so \\(\\phi(a+b) = \\phi(a) + \\phi(b) = 0\\)<br/>\r\nIf \\(a \\in ker(\\phi)\\), \\(b \\in R\\), then \\(\\phi(ar) = \\phi(a)\\phi(r) = 0 \\cdot \\phi(r) = 0\\)',148),(47,'','Define \\(\\tilde{\\phi} : {R \\over ker(\\phi)} \\to im(\\phi)\\) by \\(\\tilde{\\phi}(a + ker(\\phi)) = \\phi(a)\\).<br/>\r\n\\(\\tilde{\\phi}\\) is well defined as if \\(a + ker(\\phi) = b + ker(\\phi)\\) then \\(a - b \\in ker(\\phi)\\) so \\(\\phi(a) = \\phi(b)\\).<br/>\r\n\\(\\tilde{\\phi}\\) is a homomorphism, 1-1 and onto.',153),(48,'','Define \\(\\phi : S \\to {S + I \\over I}\\) by \\(\\phi(a) = a + I\\).<br/>\r\n<br/>\r\n\\(a \\in ker(\\phi)\\) iff \\(a \\in S\\) and \\(\\phi(a) = 0 + I\\) iff \\(a \\in I \\cap S\\)<br/>\r\n<br/>\r\nAny element of \\(S + I\\) has the form \\(a + b\\), where \\(a \\in S\\), \\(b \\in I\\), so any element of \\(S + I \\over I\\) is of the form \\((a + b) + I\\)<br/>\r\n\\(\\phi(a) = a + I = (a + b) + I\\) because \\((a + b) - a = b + I\\), so \\(im(\\phi) = {S + I \\over I}\\).<br/>\r\n<br/>\r\nSo by the first isomorphism theorem, \\({S + I \\over I} \\cong {S \\over S \\cap I}\\)',154),(49,'','Define \\(\\phi : {R \\over I} \\to {R \\over J}\\) by \\(\\phi(a + I) = a + J\\)<br/>\r\nIf \\(a + I = b + I\\), then \\(a - b \\in I\\), \\(I \\subset J\\) so \\(a - b \\in J\\), so \\(a + J = b + J\\), so \\(\\phi\\) is well defined.<br/>\r\n\\(\\phi\\) is clearly a ring homomorphism.<br/>\r\n\\(a + I \\in ker(\\phi) \\Leftrightarrow \\phi(a + I) = 0 + J \\Leftrightarrow a + J = 0 + J \\Leftrightarrow a \\in J \\Leftrightarrow a + I \\in {J \\over I}\\)<br/>\r\nLet \\(a + J \\in {R \\over J}\\), then \\(a + J = \\phi(a + I)\\) so \\(im(\\phi) = {R \\over J}\\)<br/>\r\nSo by the first isomorphism theorem, \\({R \\over J} \\cong {{R / I} \\over {J / I}}\\)',155),(50,'','As \\(\\lim_{h \\to 0} {f(z+h) - f(z) \\over h}\\) exists, no matter how \\(h \\to 0\\), the limit is the same.<br/>\r\n<br/>\r\nSo if \\(h \\in \\mathbb{R}\\) and \\(h \\to 0\\), the above limit is\r\n\\[(u(x+h, y) + iv(x+h, y)) - (u(x,y) + iv(x,y)) \\over h\\]\r\n\\[= {u(x+h,y)-u(x,y) \\over h} + i{v(x+h,y) - v(x,y) \\over h}\\]\r\n\\[= U_x(x,y) + iV_x(x,y)\\]\r\nAlternatively if \\(h=ik\\) where \\(k \\in \\mathbb{R}\\), then the limit is\r\n\\[{1 \\over i}(U_y(x,y) + V_y(x,y)) = V_y(x,y) - iU_y(x,y)\\]\r\nEquating real and imaginary parts from both, you get that\r\n\\[U_x(x,y) = V_y(x,y)\\]\r\n\\[U_y(x,y) = -V_x(x,y)\\]',142),(51,'','\\[{\\partial z \\over \\partial \\bar z} = {\\partial x \\over \\partial \\bar z}{\\partial f \\over \\partial x} + {\\partial y \\over \\partial \\bar z}{\\partial f \\over \\partial y} = {1 \\over 2}{\\partial f \\over \\partial x} + {i \\over 2}{\\partial f \\over \\partial y}\\]\r\n\\[= {1 \\over 2}(U_x + iV_x) + {i \\over 2}(U_y + iV_y) = {1 \\over 2}(U_x - V_y) + {i \\over 2}(U_y + V_x) = 0\\]',156),(52,'','<ol>\r\n<li>\r\nSuppose \\(f\'=0\\), write \\(f(z)=u(z)+iv(z)\\) where \\(u,v:D(a,r)\\to\\mathbb R\\).\r\nThen \\(f\' = u_x + iv_x = v_y - iu_x = 0\\), in particular, \\(u_x = 0 = u_y\\)<br/>\r\nThen \\(f\\) is constant on each horizontal and vertical line, so \\(f\\) is constant on \\(D(a,r)\\)<br/>\r\n<br/><Br/><br/>\r\n</li>\r\n<li>\r\nSuppose \\(|f|=c\\) for \\(z\\in D(a,r)\\), where \\(c\\in\\mathbb C\\) is a constant. Write \\(f = u + iv\\) as before, then we have that \\(u^2+v^2=c^2\\). Therefore by differentiating,\r\n\\[uu_x+vv_x=0, uu_y+vv_y=0\\]\r\nHence by the Cauchy-Riemann equations,\r\n\\[uu_x-vu_y=0, uu_y+vu_x=0\\]\r\nElimination of \\(u_y\\) gives \\(0=(u^2+v^2)u_x=c^2u_x\\), so \\(u_x=0\\). By similar methods, \\(u_y,v_x,v_y=0\\). So by part 1, \\(f\\) is constant.<br/>\r\n<br/><Br/><Br/>\r\n</li>\r\n<li>\r\nSuppose \\(f\\) is real valued. Writing \\(f=u+iv\\) as before, \\(v=0\\). Then by the Cauchy-Riemann equations, \\(u_x=v_y=0\\) and \\(u_y=-v_x=0\\). So by part 1, \\(f\\) is constant.\r\n</li>\r\n</ol>',157),(53,'','\\[U_{xx}\\]\r\n(By the Cauchy-Riemann equations)\r\n\\[= (V_y)_x\\]\r\n(By continuity)\r\n\\[= (V_x)_y\\]\r\n(By the Cauchy-Riemann equations)\r\n\\[= (-U_y)_y\\]',159),(54,'','\\(T\'(f) : U \\to \\mathbb{F}\\) so the domain is correct.<br/>\r\n<br/>\r\n(Want \\(T\'(f)\\) is linear)<br/>\r\n\\[T\'(f)(\\alpha u + \\beta v) = f(T(\\alpha u + \\beta v)) = \\alpha f(T(u)) + \\beta f(T(v))\\]\r\n\\[ = \\alpha T\'(f)(u) + \\beta T\'(f)(v),&nbsp;so&nbsp;T\'(f) \\in U\'\\]\r\nTherefore \\(T\' : V\' \\to U\'\\)<br/>\r\n<br/>\r\n(Want \\(T\'\\) is linear)<br/>\r\n\\[T\'(\\alpha f + \\beta g)(v) = (\\alpha f + \\beta g)(T(v))\\]\r\n\\[ = \\alpha f(T(v)) + \\beta g(T(v)) = \\alpha T\'(f)(v) + \\beta T\'(f)(v)\\]\r\n<br/>\r\nTherefore \\(T\'\\) exists and uniqueness is clear as we\'ve given a definition of \\(T\'\\)',165),(55,'','\\[(\\alpha S + \\beta T)\'(f)(u) = f((\\alpha S + \\beta T)(u)) = f(\\alpha S(u) + \\beta T(u))\\]\r\n\\[= \\alpha f(S(u)) + \\beta f(T(u)) = \\alpha S\'(f)(u) + \\beta T\'(f)(u)\\]',166),(56,'','Suppose \\(T\' = 0\\), then \\(\\forall f \\in V\'\\), \\(T\'(f) = 0\\). So \\(\\forall u \\in U\\), \\(T\'(f)(u) = 0\\) so \\(f(T(u)) = 0\\).<br/>\r\nSuppose \\(T(u_1) \\neq 0\\), extend to a basis \\(\\{T(u_1), v_2, v_3, ..., v_n\\}\\), let \\(\\{f_1, f_2, ..., f_n\\}\\) be the dual basis, then \\(f_1(T(u_1)) = 1 \\neq 0\\), therefore \\(T = 0\\)',167),(57,'','By earlier results it is linear and one-to-one.\r\n\\[dim(Hom(V\',U\')) = dim(V) \\times dim(U) = dim(Hom(U,V))\\]\r\nso by the rank-nullity formula it is onto.',168),(58,'','\\(TS \\in Hom(U,W)\\) so \\((TS)\' \\in Hom(W\', U\')\\).<br/>\r\n<br/>\r\nThen \\(\\forall g \\in W\', \\forall u \\in U\\)\r\n\\[(TS)\'(g)(u) = g(TS)(u) = g(T(S(u)))\\]\r\n\\[= T\'(g)(S(u)) = S\'(T\'(g)(u)) = (S\'T\')(g)(u)\\]',169),(59,'','Since \\(T^{-1} \\cdot T = I\\), \\((T^{-1} \\cdot T)\' = I\'\\), so \\((T\') \\cdot (T^{-1})\' = I\\)',171),(60,'','Suppose the \\((i,j)^{th}\\) entry of \\(M^C_B(T)\\) is \\(a_{ij}\\)<br/>\r\nThen\r\n\\[T(u_j) = \\sum^m_{i=1} a_{ij}u_i\\]\r\n\\[g_k(T(u_j)) = g_k(\\sum^n_{i=1} a_{ij}u_i) = a_{kj}\\]\r\nso \\(T\'(g_k) = \\sum^n_{i=1}a_{ki}f_i\\)<br/>\r\n<br/>\r\nSo the \\((i,k)^{th}\\) entry of \\(M^{B\'}_{C\'}(T\')\\) is \\(a_{ki}\\)<br/>\r\nIt follows that \\(M^{B\'}_{C\'}(T\') = (M^C_B(T))^T\\)',172),(61,'Induction','Base case of \\(n=1\\) is trivial.<br/>\r\n<br/>\r\nInductive step: Suppose \\(\\{v_1, ..., v_{n-1}\\}\\) is linearly independent and \\(\\alpha_1 v_1 + ... + \\alpha_n v_n = 0\\)<br/>\r\nThen \\((T - \\lambda_n)(\\alpha_1 v_1 + ... + \\alpha_n v_n) = 0\\) so \\(\\alpha_1(T - \\lambda_n)(v_1) + ... + \\alpha_n(T - \\lambda_n)(v_n) = 0\\) so \\(\\alpha_1(\\lambda_1 - \\lambda_n)v_1 + ... + \\alpha_{n-1}(\\lambda_{n-1} - \\lambda_n)(v_{n-1}) = 0\\).\r\nBy the inductive hypothesis \\(\\alpha_i(\\lambda_i - \\lambda_n) = 0\\) for all \\(i \\lt n\\), \\(\\lambda_i \\neq \\lambda_n\\) by assumption, so \\(\\alpha_i = 0\\) for all \\(i \\lt n\\).<br/>\r\nSO \\(\\alpha_nv_n = 0\\), so \\(\\alpha_n = 0\\) also.',174),(62,'','Suppose \\(p(x), q(x)\\) are monic polynomials of equal degree with \\(p(T) = q(T) = 0\\) and \\(p(x) \\neq q(x)\\).<br/>\r\nThen \\(p(x) - q(x)\\) is a polynomial of lower degree that either \\(p(x)\\) or \\(q(x)\\).<br/>\r\nLet \\(\\alpha \\neq 0\\) be its leading coefficient, then \\({1 \\over \\alpha}(p(x) - q(x))\\) is monic with \\({1 \\over \\alpha}(p - q)(T) = {1 \\over \\alpha}(p(T) - q(T)) = 0\\).<br/>\r\nThis is a contradiction of \\(p(x), q(x)\\) be minimum polynomials, so they are unique.',176),(63,'','Let \\(\\alpha\\) be the leading coefficient of \\(p(x)\\). Then \\({1 \\over \\alpha}(p(x))\\) is monic and sends \\(T\\) to zero. So there must be some such polynomial of least degree.',177),(64,'','Say \\(dim(V) = n\\), then \\(dim(Hom(V,V)) = n^2\\), so \\(\\{I, T, ..., T^{n^2}\\}\\) has \\(n^2 + 1\\) elements and so must be linearly dependent.<br/>\r\nThen \\(\\exists \\alpha_i\\) s.t. \\(\\sum_{i=0}^{n^2} \\alpha_i T^i = 0\\) with not all \\(\\alpha_i = 0\\).<br/>\r\nThen \\(p(x) = \\alpha_0 + \\alpha_1x + ... + \\alpha_{n^2}x^{n^2}\\) is a polynomial with \\(p(T) = 0\\)',178),(65,'','(\\(\\Leftarrow)\\)<br/>\r\nSuppose \\(\\lambda\\) is a root of \\(m_T(x)\\), write this as \\((x - \\lambda)p(x)\\).<br/>\r\n\\(m_T(x)\\) is monic, so so is \\(p(x)\\), \\(deg(p(x)) \\lt deg(m_T(x))\\), so \\(p(T) \\neq 0\\).<br/>\r\nSo \\(\\exists v \\in V s.t. p(T)(v) \\neq 0\\)<br/>\r\nBut \\((T - \\lambda I)(p(T)(v)) = m_T(T)(v) = 0\\)<br/>\r\nThus \\(T(p(T)(v)) = \\lambda p(T)(v)\\)<br/>\r\nso \\(p(T)(v)\\) is an eigenvector of \\(T\\) with eigenvalue \\(\\lambda\\).<br/>\r\n<br/>\r\n<br/>\r\n(\\(\\Rightarrow)\\)<br/>\r\nSuppose \\(\\lambda\\) is an eigenvalue of \\(T\\) and \\(T(v) = \\lambda v\\) with \\(v \\neq 0\\).<br/>\r\nBy induction on \\(n\\), \\(T^n(v) = \\lambda^n v\\).<br/>\r\nSo \\((\\alpha_0 I + \\alpha_1 T + ... + \\alpha_k T^k)(v) = \\alpha_0 v + \\alpha_1 \\lambda v + ... + \\alpha_k \\lambda^k v\\)<br/>\r\nIf \\(p(x)\\) is any polynomial, then \\(p(T)(v) = p(\\lambda)(v)\\), then in particular \\(m_T(T)(v) = m_T(\\lambda)(v)\\), so \\(m_T(\\lambda)(v) = 0\\) but \\(v \\neq 0\\) so \\(m_T(\\lambda) = 0\\)',179),(66,'','Over \\(\\mathbb C\\), every polynomial is a product of linear factors.',180),(67,'','\\((1)\\Rightarrow(2)\\) and \\((3)\\Rightarrow(1)\\) are obvious.<br/>\r\n<br/>\r\nGiven \\((2)\\), let \\(a\\in I\\) be a unit, then \\(1=uu^{-1}\\in I\\), hence \\(r=r\\cdot1\\in I\\) for all \\(r\\in R\\). So \\(I=R\\).',184),(68,'','Suppose that \\(I\\) is an ideal of a field \\(F\\), \\(a\\in I\\) with \\(a\\neq 0\\). Then \\(aa^{-1}\\in I\\), so \\(1\\in I\\). Therefore \\(I=\\{0\\}\\) or \\(I=F\\).<br/>\r\n<br/>\r\nSuppose \\(R\\) is a ring with no non-trivial ideals, let \\(a\\neq 0\\), then \\(aR\\) is an ideal. But \\(a1=a\\in aR\\), so \\(aR\\neq\\{0\\}\\), so \\(aR=R\\), so there exists \\(b\\) such that \\(1=ab\\). Thus \\(R\\) is a field.',185),(70,'','Define \\(\\pi : R \\to {R \\over I} \\times {R \\over J}\\) by \\(\\pi(a) = (a+I, a+J)\\).<br/>\r\n\\(\\pi\\) is clearly a homomorphism.<br/>\r\n\\[ker(\\pi) = \\{a \\in R : \\pi(a) = (0+I, 0+J)\\} = I \\cap J\\]\r\n<br/>\r\n(Want \\(\\pi\\) is onto)<br/>\r\nLet \\((a+I,b+J) \\in {R \\over I} \\times {R \\over J}\\),<br/>\r\nwrite \\(a=i+j\\), \\(b=i\'+j\'\\), \\(x=i\'+j\\), where \\(i,i\' \\in I\\), \\(j,j\' \\in J\\).<br/>\r\nSince \\(x-a=i\'-i \\in I\\), \\(x + I = a + I\\)<br/>\r\n\\(x - b = j - j\' \\in J\\), \\(x + J = b + J\\)<br/>\r\nSo \\((a + I, b + J) = (x+I, x+J) = \\pi(x) \\in im(\\pi)\\), by the first isomorphism theorem,\r\n\\[{R \\over I \\cap J} \\cong {R \\over I} \\times {R \\over J}\\]',188),(71,'','Let \\(I = (m)\\), \\(J = (n)\\), then \\(I \\cap J = (lcm(m,n)) = (mn)\\) since they are coprime.<br/>\r\nBy Bezout\'s lemma, \\(\\exists h, k \\in \\mathbb{Z}&nbsp;s.t.&nbsp;hm + kn = 1\\), so \\(1 \\in I + J\\), so \\(I + J = \\mathbb{Z}\\)<br/>\r\nThen by the Chinese remainder theorem, \\({\\mathbb{Z} \\over (m) \\cap (n)} \\cong {\\mathbb{Z} \\over (m)} \\times {\\mathbb{Z} \\over (n)}\\), so \\(\\mathbb{Z}_{mn} \\cong \\mathbb{Z}_m \\times \\mathbb{Z}_n\\)',189),(72,'','If \\(0 \\lt m \\lt n\\), \\(m\\) is coprime to \\(n\\) iff \\(p \\not|&nbsp;m\\)<br/>\r\nThere are \\(p^{k-1} - 1\\) multiples of \\(p\\) in \\(\\{1, ..., p^{k-1}\\}\\) , so there are \\((p^k - 1) - (p^{k-1} - 1) = p^{k-1}(p-1)\\) elements which are not multiples of \\(p\\).',192),(73,'','By the Chinese remainder theorem \\(\\mathbb{Z}_n \\cong \\prod_{i=1}^m \\mathbb{Z}_{p_i^{k_i}}\\)<br/>\r\nSo\r\n\\[|\\mathbb{Z}_n^*| = |(\\prod_{i=1}^m \\mathbb{Z}_{p_i^{k_i}})^*| = |\\prod_{i=1}^m (\\mathbb{Z}_{p_i^{k_i}})^*| = \\prod_{i=1}^m \\phi(p_i^{k_i})\\]',193),(74,'','Choose \\(r = |z|\\), \\(\\theta = arg(z)\\) in the given range \\((-\\pi, \\pi)\\)<br/>\r\nIn the notation of CREqs,\r\n\\[U(x,y) = log(\\sqrt{x^2 + y^2}) = {1 \\over 2}log(x^2 + y^2)\\]\r\n\\[V(x,y) = tan^{-1}({y \\over x})\\]\r\nSo \\(U_x = {x \\over x^2 + y^2}\\), \\(U_y = {y \\over x^2 + y^2}\\)<br/>\r\nand \\(V_x = {-y \\over x^2 + y^2}\\), \\(V_y = {x \\over x^2 + y^2}\\)<br/>\r\nSo \\(U_x = V_y\\) and \\(U_y = -V_x\\), so the CREqs hold.<br/>\r\nAll \\(U_x, U_y, V_x, V_y\\) are continuous so \\(L\\) is holomorphic by the Goursat theorem.<br/>\r\n\\[L\'(z) = U_x + i V_x = {x - iy \\over x^2 + y^2} = {1 \\over z}\\]\r\nFinally,\r\n\\[exp(L(z)) = exp(log(r) + i \\theta) = exp(log(r))exp(i \\theta) = re^{i \\theta} = z\\]',194),(75,'','\\(z^\\alpha = exp(\\alpha L(z))\\) is holomorphic by the chain rule.<br/>\r\n\\[{d \\over dz}(z^\\alpha) = \\alpha L\'(z)exp(\\alpha L(z)) = {\\alpha \\over z} exp(\\alpha L(z))\\]\r\n\\[= \\alpha exp(-L(z))exp(\\alpha L(z)) = \\alpha exp((\\alpha-1)L(z)) = \\alpha z^{\\alpha-1}\\]',195),(76,'','Easy to see that it converges on \\(D(0,1)\\), then writing \\(f(z) = \\sum_{n=1}^\\infty {z^n \\over n}\\), \\(f\'(z) = \\sum_{n=0}^\\infty z^n = (1-z)^{-1}\\), hence \\(f(z) = -L(1-z) + k\\).<br/>\r\nAs \\(f(0) = L(1) = 0\\), \\(k=0\\), so \\(f(z) = -L(1-z)\\)',196),(77,'','<ol>\r\n<li>\r\nWe have \\(e^{w_0} = z\\), \\(w \\in [log(z)] \\Leftrightarrow e^w = z \\Leftrightarrow e^w = e^{w_0} \\Leftrightarrow e^{w - w_0} = 1 \\Leftrightarrow w_0 - w \\in 2 \\pi i \\mathbb{Z}\\) so \\([log(z)] = w_0 + 2 \\pi i \\mathbb{Z}\\)<br/>\r\n\\(\\theta \\in [arg(z)] \\Leftrightarrow e^{i \\theta} = {z \\over |z|} \\Leftrightarrow e^{i \\theta + log(|z|)} = z \\Leftrightarrow i \\theta + log(|z\\) \\in [log(z)]\\)\r\n<br/><br/>\r\n</li>\r\n<li>\r\nTake w_0 \\in [log(w)]\\), \\(z_0 \\in [log(z)]\\), note \\(e^{z_0 + w_0} = e^{z_0}e^{w_0} = zw\\), ie: \\(z_0 + w_0 \\in [log(zw)]\\)<br/>\r\nThen \\([log(zw)] = z_0 + w_0 + 2 \\pi i \\mathbb{Z} = [log(z)] + [log(w)]\\)\r\n</li>\r\n</ol>',197),(78,'','Let \\(\\alpha : [a_1, b_1] \\to [a_2, b_2]\\) be the change of coordinate function so that \\(\\gamma_2(\\alpha(t)) = \\gamma_1(t)\\).<br/>\r\nAs \\(\\gamma_1\\) and \\(\\gamma_2\\) have the same orientation then \\(\\gamma(a_1) = \\gamma(a_2)\\) and \\(\\gamma(b_1) = \\gamma(b_2)\\).<br/>\r\nSo we have\r\n\\[\\int_{a_2}^{b_2} f(\\gamma_2(t))\\gamma_2\'(t)dt = \\int_{a_1}^{b_1}(f(\\gamma_2(\\alpha(u)))\\gamma_2\'(\\alpha(u))\\alpha\'(u))du\\]\r\n\\[= \\int_{a_1}^{b_1} f(\\gamma_1(u))\\gamma_1\'(u)du\\]\r\nSo path integration is independent of parametrization of the same orientation.<br/>\r\n<br/>\r\nFinally, if instead we had \\(\\Gamma : [-b_1, -a_1] \\to U\\) given by \\(\\Gamma(t) = \\gamma_1(-t)\\)<br/>\r\nThen\r\n\\[\\int_\\Gamma f(z)dz = \\int_{-b_1}^{-a_1}f(\\Gamma(t))\\Gamma\'(t)dt\\]\r\n\\[= \\int_{b_1}^{a_1}f(\\gamma_1(u))(-\\gamma_1\'(u))(-du)\\]\r\n\\[= - \\int_{a_1}^{b_1} f(\\gamma_1(u))\\gamma_1\'(u)du = -\\int_{\\gamma_1}f(z)dz\\]',205),(79,'','Let \\(A = (a_{ij})\\), \\(B_{ij}\\) is the matrix obtained by deleting the \\(i^{th}\\) row and \\(j^{th}\\) column from \\(A\\).<br/>\r\n<br/>\r\nThe \\(ij^{th}\\) entry of \\(adj(A)\\) is:\r\n\\[\\sum_{k=1}^na_{ik}b_{kj} = \\sum_{k=1}^na_{ik}(-1)^{k+j}det(B_{kj})\\]\r\n\\[= \\sum_{k=1}^na_{ik}(-1)^{k+j}\\sum_{k = j \\sigma} sign(\\sigma)(\\prod_{k \\neq l}^na_{l l \\sigma} \\times (-1)^{(pariry fudge factor)})\\]\r\n\\[= \\sum_{k=1}^na_{ik}\\sum_{k = j \\sigma}sign(\\sigma)(\\prod_{j \\neq l}a_{l l \\sigma}) = \\sum_{k=1}^n\\sum_{k = j \\sigma}sign(\\sigma)a_{ik}\\prod_{l \\neq k}a_{l l \\sigma}\\]\r\nLetting \\(c_{pq} = \\left\\{\\begin{array}{ll}a_{pq} & \\mbox{if } p \\neq j \\\\ a_{iq} & \\mbox{if } p = j \\end{array} \\right.\\)\r\n\\[= \\sum_{k=1}^n\\sum_{k = j \\sigma} sign(\\sigma)c_{jk}\\prod_{l \\neq k}c_{l l \\sigma} = \\sum_{k=1}^n\\sum_{k = j \\sigma}sign(\\sigma)\\prod_{l=1}^nc_{l l \\sigma}\\]\r\n\\[= \\sum_{\\sigma \\in sym(n)}sign(\\sigma)\\prod_{l=1}^nc_{l l \\sigma} = det(c_{pq})\\]\r\nIf \\(i = j\\) then \\(c_{pq} = a_{pq}\\) and the above is \\(det(A)\\)<br/>\r\nIf \\(i \\neq j\\) then \\(c_{iq} = c_{jq}\\) for all \\(q\\), so 2 rows of \\((c_{pq})\\) are equal, so \\(det(c_{pq}) = 0\\).<br/>\r\n<br/>\r\nSo \\(Aadj(A) = det(A)I\\)',206),(80,'','Write \\(\\chi_T(x) = q(x)m_T(x) + r(x)\\) where \\(r(x) = 0\\) or \\(deg(r(x)) \\lt deg(m_T(x))\\).<br/>\r\nThen \\(r(x) = \\chi_T(x) - q(x)m_T(x)\\)<br/>\r\nSo \\(r(T) = \\chi_T(T) - q(T)m_T(T) = 0\\) by the Cayley-Hamilton theorem.<br/>\r\nIf \\(r(x) \\neq 0\\) then \\(deg(r(x)) \\lt deg(m_T(x))\\) and \\(r(T) = 0\\).<br/>\r\nThis is a contradiction to the minimum polynomial, so \\(r(x) = 0\\), so \\(m_T(x)&nbsp;|&nbsp;\\chi_T(x)\\)',209),(81,'','Suppose \\(A\\) is an \\(n \\times n\\) matrix, then \\(\\chi_A(x) = det(xI - A)\\), \\(det(xI-A)I = (xI-A)adj(xI-A)\\)<br/>\r\nThe entries of \\(adj(xI-A)\\) are each a factor of \\((\\pm1)\\) times an \\(n-1 \\times n-1\\) sub-determinant of \\(xI-A\\). Such a determinant is a polynomial of degree no more than \\(n-1\\).<br/><br/>\r\nWrite \\(adj(xI-A) = B_0 + xB_1 + x^2B_2 + ... + x^{n-1}B_{n-1}\\), then\r\n\\[(xI-A)adj(xI-A) = (xI-A)(B_0 + xB_1 + ... + x^{n-1}B_{n-1})\\]\r\n\\[= xB_0 - AB_0 + x^2B_1 - xAB_1 + ... + x^2B_{n-1} - x^{n-1}B_{n-1}\\]\r\n\\[= det(xI-A)I\\]\r\nSay \\(\\chi_A(x) = det(xI-A) = a_0 + a_1x + ... + a_{n-1}x^{n-1} + x^n\\)<br/>\r\nThen \\(\\chi_A(A) = a_0I + a_1A + ... + a_{n-1}A^{n-1} + A^n\\)<br/>\r\nSo \\(\\chi_A(A) = AB_0 - AB_0 + ... + A^nB_{n-1} - A^nB_{n-1} = 0\\)',208),(82,'','We set \\(z = a + re^{i \\theta}\\), \\(0 \\leq \\theta \\leq 2 \\pi\\) and get\r\n\\[\\int_{\\gamma(a,r)} (z-a)^k dz = \\int_0^{2 \\pi} (re^{i\\theta})^k(ire^{i\\theta})d\\theta\\]\r\n\\[ = ir^{k+1}\\int_0^{2\\pi}(cos((k+1)\\theta) + isin((k+1)\\theta))d\\theta = 0 when k \\neq -1\\]\r\nWhen \\(k=-1\\), this gives \\(ir^0 \\int_0^{2\\pi}d\\theta = 2\\theta i\\)',210),(83,'','Let \\(\\gamma : [a,b] \\to \\mathbb{C}\\) be a parametrization, where \\(\\gamma(a) = p\\) and \\(\\gamma(b) = q\\)\r\n\\[\\int_\\gamma f\'(z)dz = \\int_a^b f\'(\\gamma(t))\\gamma\'(t)dt\\]\r\n\\[= \\int_a^b {d \\over dt}(f(\\gamma(t)))dt = f(\\gamma(b)) - f(\\gamma(a)) = f(q) - f(p)\\]',211),(84,'','\\(U\\), being open and connected in \\(\\mathbb{C}\\) is then path-connected. Take \\(p,q \\in U\\) and \\(\\gamma\\) a path from \\(p\\) to \\(q\\).<br/>\r\nThen\r\n\\[f(q) - f(p) = \\int_\\gamma f\'(z)dz = 0\\]',212),(85,'','For a complex function \\(f\\), it still remains the case that \\(|\\int_a^bf(t)dt| \\leq \\int_a^b|f(t)|dt\\) as with real integrals, so\r\n\\[|\\int_\\gamma f(z)dz| = |\\int_a^bf(\\gamma(t))\\gamma\'(t)dt| \\leq \\int_a^b|f(\\gamma(t))\\gamma\'(t)|dt\\]\r\n\\[\\leq \\int_a^bM|\\gamma\'(t)|dt = M \\times L(\\gamma)\\]',213),(86,'','Let \\(\\epsilon \\gt 0\\), by uniform convergence \\(\\exists N \\in \\mathbb{N}\\) s.t. \\(\\forall n \\gt N\\), \\(\\forall z \\in \\gamma\\), \\(|f_n(z) - f(z)| \\lt {\\epsilon \\over L(\\gamma)}\\)<br/>\r\nSo for \\(n \\geq N\\),\r\n\\[|(\\int_\\gamma f_n(z)dz) - \\int_\\gamma f(z)dz| = |\\int_\\gamma (f_n(z) - f(z))dz|\\]\r\n\\[\\leq L(\\gamma) \\times sup_\\gamma |f_n(z) - f(z)| \\lt L(\\gamma) \\times {\\epsilon \\over L(\\gamma)} = \\epsilon\\]',214),(87,'','Let \\(B\\) be a basis such that \\(M_B^B(T)\\) is diagonal and has diagonal entries \\(\\lambda_1, ..., \\lambda_k\\), possibly with repetitions.<br/>\r\nLet \\(A = M_B^B(T)\\), then \\(\\prod_{i=1}^k(A-\\lambda_iI) = 0\\)<br/>\r\nSo if \\(p(x) = \\prod_{i=1}^k(x-\\lambda_i)\\), then \\(p(A) = 0\\) so \\(p(T) = 0\\). So \\(m_T(x)&nbsp;|&nbsp;p(x)\\).<br/>\r\n\\(m_T(x)\\) and \\(p(x)\\) have the same roots and \\(p(x)\\) has no repeated roots, so \\(m_T(x)\\) has no repeated roots.',215),(88,'','<ol>\r\n<li>\r\nAs \\(hcf(p(x), q(x)) = 1\\),\r\n\\[\\exists h(x), k(x)&nbsp;s.t.&nbsp;h(x)p(x) + k(x)q(x) = 1\\]\r\nLet \\(v \\in V\\), then\r\n\\[v = Iv = (h(T)p(T) + k(T)q(T))(v) = (h(T)p(T))(v) + (k(T)q(T))(v)\\]\r\n\\[and&nbsp;(p(T)h(T)q(T))(v) = (h(T)p(T)q(T))(v) = (h(T)m_T(T))(v) = 0\\]\r\nso \\(h(T)p(T) \\in ker(q(T)) = W\\)<br/>\r\nand \\(k(T)q(T) \\in ker(p(T)) = U\\)<br/>\r\nSo \\(V = U + W\\)<br/>\r\n<br/>\r\nSuppose \\(v \\in U \\cap W\\), so \\(v \\in U\\) and \\(v \\in W\\), then\r\n\\[v = h(T)p(T)(v) + k(T)q(T)(v) = 0\\]\r\nSo \\(V = U \\oplus W\\)<br/>\r\n<br/>\r\n<br/>\r\n</li>\r\n<li>\r\nIf \\(u \\in U\\), then \\(u \\in ker(p(T))\\) so \\(p(T)(u) = 0\\), then\r\n\\[T(p(T))(u) = 0 \\Rightarrow p(T)(T(u)) = 0 \\Rightarrow T(u) \\in ker(p(T))\\]\r\nSo \\(U\\) is \\(T\\) invariant.<br/>\r\nThe proof for \\(W\\) is identical.<br/>\r\n<br/>\r\n<br/>\r\n</li>\r\n<li>\r\nIf \\(u \\in U\\), then \\(u \\in ker(p(T))\\), so \\(p(T)(u) = 0\\), then\r\n\\[p(T|_U) = 0 \\Rightarrow m_{T|_U}(x)&nbsp;|&nbsp;p(x)\\]\r\nSimilarly \\(m_{T|_W}(x)&nbsp;|&nbsp;q(x)\\)<br/>\r\nFinally,\r\n\\[(m_{T|_U}(T)m_{T|_W}(T)(v) = \\left\\{\\begin{array}{ll}0 & \\mbox{if } v \\in W \\\\ 0 & \\mbox{if } v \\in U \\end{array} \\right.\\]\r\nSo \\(m_{T|_U}(T)m_{T|_W}(T) = 0\\)\r\n\\[\\Rightarrow m_T(x)&nbsp;|&nbsp;m_{T|_U}(x)m_{T|_W}(x)&nbsp;|&nbsp;p(x)q(x) = m_T(x)\\]\r\n\\[\\Rightarrow m_T(x) = m_{T|_U}(x)m_{T|_W}(x)\\]\r\n\\[\\Rightarrow m_{T|_U}(x) = p(x)&nbsp;and&nbsp;m_{T|_W}(x) = q(x)\\]\r\n</li>\r\n</ol>',216),(89,'','Induction of the primary decomposition theorem.',217),(90,'','Suppose \\(m_T(x) = \\prod_{i=1}^n(x-\\lambda_i)\\), all \\(\\lambda_i\\) different.<br/>\r\nBy a corollary to the primary decomposition theorem \\(V = \\prod_{i=1}^nV_i\\) where \\(V_i = ker(T - \\lambda_iI)\\)<br/>\r\nAll elements of \\(V_i\\) are eigenvectors of \\(T\\), let \\(B_i\\) be a basis for \\(V_i\\)<br/>\r\nIf \\(B = \\bigcup_{i=1}^nB_i\\) then \\(B\\) is a basis for \\(V\\) consisting of eigenvectors, so \\(T\\) is diagonalizable.',218),(91,'','Firstly, observe that \\(d(1)\\) is minimal as for any \\(x \\neq 0\\), \\(d(x) = d(1x) \\geq d(1)\\).<br/>\r\nSuppose \\(a\\) is a unit with inverse \\(b\\), then \\(d(ab) = d(1) \\geq d(a)\\), hence \\(d(a)\\) is minimal.<br/>\r\nSuppose \\(a\\) has minimal degree, then \\(\\exists q,r\\) s.t. \\(1 = qa + r\\) where \\(r = 0\\) or \\(d(r) \\lt d(a)\\), hence \\(r = 0\\), so \\(a\\) has an inverse.',221),(92,'','\\(\\exists q,r \\in R\\) s.t. \\(a = qb + r\\) where \\(r = 0\\) or \\(d(r) \\lt d(b)\\), then \\(r = a - qb\\) which is a multiple of \\(a\\).<br/>\r\nSo \\(a&nbsp;|&nbsp;r\\), suppose \\(r \\neq 0\\) then \\(d(r) \\lt d(b)\\) but \\(d(a) = d(b)\\), so \\(d(r) \\lt d(a)\\), contradicts \\(d\\) being a euclidean degree function.<br/>\r\nHence \\(r = 0\\), so \\(a = qb\\) so \\(b&nbsp;|&nbsp;a\\)',222),(93,'','If \\(a, b \\in R \\setminus \\{0\\}\\), then \\(d(ab) \\geq d(a)\\), then \\(ab \\neq 0\\) and \\(d(ab)\\) is defined.',223),(94,'','Suppose \\(a\\) is irreducible, so if \\(a = bc\\) then \\(b\\) or \\(c\\) is a unit.<br/>\r\nSuppose for a contradiction that \\(a&nbsp;|&nbsp;bc\\) but \\(a \\not|&nbsp;b\\) and \\(a \\not|&nbsp;c\\), then \\(b \\neq 0\\) and \\(c \\neq 0\\), so \\(bc \\neq 0\\) also.<br/>\r\nTherefore \\(hcf(a,b) = hcf(a,c) = 1\\), so \\(\\exists h,h\',k,k\'\\) s.t. \\(ah+bk=ah\'+ck\'=1\\)<br/>\r\nSo \\(1 = (ah+bk)(ah\'+ck\') = a(ahh\'+bkh\'+chk\') + (bc)(kk\')\\), \\(a&nbsp;|&nbsp;bc\\) so \\(a&nbsp;|&nbsp;1\\), so \\(a\\) is a unit.<br/>\r\nContradiction to \\(a\\) being ireducible, hence \\(a\\) is prime.',224),(95,'','Suppose for a contradiction that \\(\\bigcap_{n=1}^\\infty C_n = \\emptyset\\), then \\(\\mathbb C = \\mathbb C \\setminus \\bigcap_{n=1}^\\infty C_n = \\bigcup_{n=1}^\\infty (\\mathbb C \\setminus C_n)\\)<br/>\r\nSo \\(\\{\\mathbb C \\setminus C_n : n \\geq 1\\}\\) is an open cover for \\(C_1\\), so by compactness we only need a finite cover, say \\(\\mathbb C \\setminus C_{n_1}, ..., \\mathbb C \\setminus C_{n_k}\\), with \\(n_i\\) increasing.<br/>\r\nAs all the sets are nested, \\(C_1 \\subset C_1 \\setminus C_{n_k}\\), so \\(C_{n_k} = \\emptyset\\), this is a contradiction.',228),(96,'','Let \\(a,x \\in U\\) with \\(a\\) fixed, then define \\(F(z) = \\int_{[a,z]} f(w)dw\\)<br/>\r\nAs \\(U\\) is open, \\(z\\) is an interior point, so \\(\\exists \\epsilon \\gt 0\\) s.t. \\(D(z, \\epsilon) \\subset U\\), take \\(h\\) with \\(|h| \\lt \\epsilon\\)<br/>\r\nBy Cauchy\'s theorem for triangles, we have\r\n\\[\\int_{[a,z]}f(w)dw + \\int{[z,z+h]}f(w)dw + \\int_{[z+h,a]}f(w)dw = 0\\]\r\nRewriting this,\r\n\\[F(z+h) - F(z) = \\int_{[z,z+h]}f(w)dw\\]\r\nThen\r\n\\[|{F(z+h)-F(z) \\over h} - f(z)| = |({1 \\over h} \\int_{[z,z+h]}f(w)dw) - f(z)|\\]\r\n\\[ = |{1 \\over h}\\int_{[z,z+h]}(f(w) - f(z))dw|\\]\r\nwhich by the estimation theorem\r\n\\[\\leq {1 \\over |h|}L([z,z+h]) \\times sup_{[z,z+h]}|f(z) - f(w)|\\]\r\n\\[ = sup_{[z,z+h]}|f(z) - f(w)|\\]\r\nwhich tends to zero as \\(h\\) tends to zero by the continuity of \\(f\\) at \\(z\\)',229),(97,'','<u>Step one: subdivide \\(\\Delta\\)</u><br/>\r\nTake midpoints of the sides of \\(\\Delta\\) to form 4 smaller triangles, \\(A,B,C,D\\) with \\(B\\) in the center. Then\r\n\\[\\int_\\Delta f(z)dz = \\int_Af(z)dz + ... + \\int_Df(z)dz\\]\r\nOne of the four triangles has smallest modulus, call it \\(\\Delta_1\\) and then by the triangle inequality\r\n\\[|\\int_\\Delta f(z)dz| \\leq 4|\\int_{\\Delta_1}f(z)dz|\\]\r\nRepeat this to get \\(\\Delta_1 \\supset \\Delta_2 \\supset ...\\), then\r\n\\[|\\int_\\Delta f(z)dz| \\leq 4^n|\\int_{\\Delta_n}f(z)dz|\\]\r\nAs the \\(\\Delta_n\\) are compact, nested and non-empty, their intersection is also non-empty. But this intersection \\(\\bigcap_{n=1}^\\infty \\Delta_n\\) can only contain one point \\(\\xi\\) as the triangles sit in disks whose radii tend to 0.<br/><br/><br/>\r\n<u>Step two: differentiability at \\(\\xi\\)</u><br/>\r\nLet \\(\\epsilon \\gt 0\\), as \\(f\'(\\xi)\\) exists, \\(\\exists \\delta \\gt 0\\) s.t. \\(|{f(z) - f(\\xi) \\over z - \\xi} - f\'(\\xi)| \\lt \\epsilon\\) whenever \\(|z - \\xi| \\lt \\delta\\), or equivalently \\(f(z) = f(\\xi) + f\'(\\xi)(z-\\xi) + w(z)(z-\\xi)\\) on \\(D(\\xi,\\delta)\\) and where \\(|w(z)| \\lt \\epsilon\\)<br/>\r\nSo if we have \\(N\\) large enough that \\(\\Delta_N \\subset D(\\xi, \\delta)\\), the we have\r\n\\[\\int_{\\Delta_N}f(z)dz = f(\\xi)\\int_{\\Delta_N}dz + f\'(\\xi)\\int_{\\Delta_N}(z-\\xi)dz + \\int_{\\Delta_N}w(z)(z-\\xi)dz\\]\r\nwhich by the fundamental theorem of calculus tends to\r\n\\[\\int_{\\Delta_N}w(z)(x-\\xi)dz\\]\r\nSo for any \\(z \\in \\Delta_N\\), \\(|z-\\xi| \\lt L(\\Delta_N)\\), so by the estimation theorem\r\n\\[|\\int_{\\Delta_N}f(z)dz| \\leq \\epsilon L(\\Delta_N)^2\\]\r\nBy construction\r\n\\[L(\\Delta_N) = {1 \\over 2} L(\\Delta_{N-1}) = {1 \\over 2^n} L(\\Delta)\\]\r\nHence\r\n\\[|\\int_\\Delta f(z)dz| \\leq 4^N|\\int_{\\Delta_N}f(z)dz| \\leq 4^N \\epsilon ({L(\\Delta) \\over 2^N}) = \\epsilon L(\\Delta)^2\\]\r\n\\[\\Rightarrow |\\int_\\Delta f(z)dz| = 0\\]',227),(98,'','As \\(U\\) is simply connected, \\(\\gamma\\) is homotopic deformable to some constant point \\(\\Gamma\\). Then by the deformation theorem\r\n\\[\\int_\\gamma f(z)dz = \\int_\\Gamma f(z)dz = 0\\]',233),(99,'','\\(\\gamma_1 \\cup (-\\gamma_2)\\) is a closed loop, so by Cauchy\'s theorem\r\n\\[\\int_{\\gamma_1}f(z)dz - \\int_{\\gamma_2}f(z)dz = \\int_{\\gamma_1 \\cup (-\\gamma_2)}f(z)dz = 0\\]',234),(100,'','Fix \\(a \\in U\\) and define \\(F(z) = \\int_\\gamma f(w)dw\\) where \\(\\gamma\\) is a path from \\(a\\) to \\(z\\). This is well defined.<br/>\r\nThen continue as in the convex domain proof.',235),(101,'','Let \\(a \\in U\\), \\(c \\in [log(a)]\\), so \\(e^c = a\\), then for \\(z \\in U\\) define \\(l(z) = c + \\int_\\gamma {1 \\over w}dw\\) where \\(\\gamma\\) is a path from \\(a\\) to \\(z\\)<br/>\r\nThen \\(l\'(z) = {1\\over z}\\) as before<br/>\r\nDefine \\(G(z) = {exp(l(z)) \\over z}\\), then \\(G\'(z) = 0\\) and \\(G(a) = 1\\), so \\(G(z) = 1\\) for all \\(z\\), so \\(exp(l(z)) = z\\)',236),(102,'','Define \\(f = u_x - iu_y\\), using CREqs to show that \\(f\\) is holomorphic.<br/>\r\nBy the antiderivative theorem, there is \\(F\\) such that \\(F\'(z) = f(z)\\)<br/>\r\nThen \\(v = Im(F)\\) is a harmonic conjugate of \\(u\\)',237),(103,'','Apply theorem for eigenvalue of zero to \\(T - \\lambda I\\)',240),(104,'','Write \\(m_T(x) = \\prod_{i=1}^k(x-\\lambda_i)^{m_i}\\) where \\(\\lambda_i\\) are distinct and \\(m_i \\geq 1\\)<br/>\r\nIf \\(i \\neq j\\) then \\((x - \\lambda_i)^{m_i}\\) and \\((x - \\lambda_j)^{m_j}\\) are coprime, so by the primary decomposition theorem,\r\n\\[V = \\oplus_{i=1}^k ker((T-\\lambda_iI)^{m_i})\\]\r\n\\[m_{T|_{ker((T-\\lambda_iI)^{m_i})}} = (x - \\lambda_i)^{m_i}\\]\r\nBy the above corollary, there is a basis \\(B_i\\) of \\(ker((T-\\lambda_iI)^{m_i})\\) such that\r\n\\[A_i = M_{B_i}^{B_i}(T|_{ker((T-\\lambda_i)^{m_i})})\\]\r\nwhere the diagonal entries are \\(\\lambda_i\\), all non-diagonal entries are 0 except for immediately above the main diagonal, which may be 1.<br/>\r\nThen \\(B = \\bigcup_{i=1}^nB_i\\) is a basis of \\(V\\) and \\(M_B^B(T)\\) is constructed by placing the \\(A_i\\) along the diagonal.<br/>\r\nThis matrix is in Jordan canonical form.',241),(105,'','Suppose \\(\\{v_1, ..., v_n\\}\\) is orthogonal and all \\(v_i \\neq 0\\)<br/>\r\nSuppose \\(\\alpha_1 v_1 + ... + \\alpha_n v_n = 0\\)\r\n\\[\\Rightarrow \\langle \\alpha_1 v_1 + ... + \\alpha_n v_n, v_i \\rangle = 0\\]\r\n\\[\\Rightarrow \\alpha_1 \\langle v_1, v_i \\rangle + ... + \\alpha_n \\langle v_n, v_i \\rangle = 0\\]\r\n\\[\\Rightarrow \\alpha_i \\langle v_i, v_i \\rangle = 0\\]\r\nSo by positive definiteness \\(\\alpha_i = 0\\)',247),(106,'','Follows from Gran-Schnidt process',248),(107,'','Suppose \\(I\\) is an ideal of a Euclidean ring \\(R\\), \\(I \\neq \\{0\\}\\)<br/>\r\nFind \\(a \\in I\\) s.t. \\(d(a)\\) is minimal of all elements in \\(I\\)<br/>\r\nSuppose \\(b \\in I\\), then \\(\\exists q,r\\) s.t. \\(b = aq + r\\) where \\(r = 0\\) or \\(d(r) \\lt d(a)\\), but \\(d(a)\\) is minimal so \\(r = 0\\), therefore \\(b\\) is a multiple of \\(a\\)<br/>\r\nHence \\(I\\) is principle and \\(I = (a)\\)',253),(108,'','Let \\(R\\) be a principle domain, suppose \\(I_n\\) is an ideal for all \\(n\\) and that \\(I_0 \\subset_\\neq I_1 \\subset_\\neq ...\\)<br/>\r\nLet \\(I = \\bigcup_{n=0}^\\infty I_n\\)<br/>\r\n<br/>\r\nSuppose \\(a,b \\in I\\), then \\(\\exists m,n\\) s.t. \\(a \\in I_m, b \\in I_n\\), suppose without loss of generality that \\(m \\leq n\\), then \\(I_m \\subset I_n\\), so \\(a \\in I_n\\).<br/>\r\nThen as \\(I_n\\) is an ideal, \\(a + b \\in I\\)<br/>\r\nIf \\(a \\in I\\), \\(r \\in R\\), then \\(a \\in I_n\\) for some \\(n\\), so \\(ar \\in I_n \\subset I\\)<br/>\r\nTherefore \\(I\\) is an ideal and \\(I \\neq \\emptyset\\)<br/>\r\n<br/>\r\nHowever if \\(a \\in I\\), then \\(a \\in I_n\\) for some \\(n\\), \\(I_n\\) is an ideal so \\((a) \\subset I_n\\)<br/>\r\nBut \\(I_n \\subset_\\neq I_{n+1}\\) so \\(I_n \\subset_\\neq I\\), so \\((a) \\neq I\\)<br/>\r\nHence \\(I\\) is not principle, this is a contradiction as \\(R\\) is a principle domain.',254),(109,'','Suppose \\(a_0 \\in R\\), \\(a_0 \\neq 0\\), not a unit and has no irreducible factors, thus \\(a_0\\) is not irreducible, then \\(\\exists a_1, b_1\\) s.t. \\(a_1b_1 = a_0\\) and \\(a_1, b_1\\) are not units.<br/>\r\nThen \\(a_1, b_1\\) have no irreducible factors, this process can be repeated to construct \\(a_n, b_n\\) s.t. \\(a_{n-1} = a_nb_n\\) and \\(a_n, b_n\\) are not units.<br/>\r\nLet \\(I_n = (a_n)\\), then \\(I_{n+1} \\subset_\\neq I_n\\), but this is impossible by the above theorem.',255),(110,'','Suppose \\(a_0 \\in R\\setminus\\{0\\}\\) and not a unit.<br/>\r\nIf \\(a_0\\) is irreducible we\'re done, if not then let \\(a_0 = p_1a_1\\) where \\(p_1\\) is an irreducible factor.<br/>\r\nWe proceed by recursion.<br/>\r\nEither for some \\(m\\), \\(a_0 = p_1p_2...p_ma_m\\) and \\(p_i,a_m\\) are irreducible, or for all \\(n\\), we can find \\(p_i, a_i\\) s.t. \\(a_0 = p_1...p_na_n\\) and \\(a_n\\) is not a unit and is not irreducible, and \\(a_n = p_{n+1}a_{n+1}\\)<br/>\r\nNow, let \\(I_n = (a_n)\\), \\(a_{n+1} | a_n\\) so \\(I_n \\subset I_{n+1}\\) and \\(p_{n+1}\\) is not a unit so \\(I_n \\neq I_{n+1}\\). This is a contradiction, hence the process terminates.',256),(111,'','Suppose \\(r \\in R \\setminus \\{0\\}\\), where \\(R\\) is a principle ideal domain.<br/>\r\nSuppose \\(r = up_1...p_k = vq_1...q_l\\) where \\(u,v\\) are units and \\(p_i, q_i\\) are irreducible<br/>\r\nWe use induction on k<br/>\r\n<br/>\r\nBase case: \\(k = 0\\)<br/>\r\nIn this case \\(r\\) is a unit so every factor of \\(r\\) is a unit, so \\(l = 0, u = v\\)<br/>\r\n<br/>\r\nInductive step, \\(k \\gt 0\\)<br/>\r\n\\(p_1 | r\\) so \\(p_1 | vq_1...q_l\\), \\(p_1\\) is irreducible and hence prime, so \\(p_1 | q_i\\) for some \\(i\\), (\\(p_1\\not| v\\) as \\(v\\) is a unit)<br/>\r\nWrite \\(q_i = \\alpha p_1\\), so \\(\\alpha\\) is a unit<br/>\r\nSo \\(r = up_q...p_k=vq_1...q_{i-1}\\alpha p_1q_{i+1}...q_l=up_2...p_k=v\\alpha q_1...q_{i-1}q_{i+1}...q_l\\), we use the inductive hypothesis (\\(v\\alpha\\) is a unit)<br/>\r\nFind \\(f : \\{2,...,k\\}\\to\\{1,...,i-1,i+1,...,l\\}\\) s.t. \\(q_{f(j)}\\) is an associate of \\(p_j\\)<br/>\r\nDefine \\(g:\\{1,...,k\\}\\to\\{1,...,l\\}\\) by \\(g(j) = f(j)\\) is \\(j \\neq 1\\) and \\(g(j) = i\\) if \\(j = 1\\)<br/>\r\n<br/>\r\nTherefore \\(R\\) is a unique factorization domain.',257),(112,'','Consider\r\n\\[\\Delta = |{1\\over 2\\pi i}\\int_{\\gamma(a,r)}{f(w)\\over w-a}dw - f(a)|\\]\r\nwe will parametrize \\(\\gamma(a,r)\\) as \\(w = re^{i\\theta} + a\\)<br/>\r\nSo we have\r\n\\[{1\\over 2\\pi i}\\int_{\\gamma(a,r)}{f(w)\\over w-a}dw - f(a) = {1\\over 2\\pi i}\\int_{\\gamma(a,r)}{f(w)-f(a) \\over w-a}dw\\]\r\n\\[= {1\\over 2\\pi i}\\int_0^{2\\pi}{f(a+re^{i\\theta})-f(a)\\over re^{i\\theta}}ire^{i\\theta}d\\theta = {1\\over 2\\pi}\\int_0^{2\\pi}(f(a+re^{i\\theta})-f(a))d\\theta\\]\r\nThen we have by the estimation theorem, \r\n\\[|\\Delta| \\leq \\sup_{\\theta \\in [0,2\\pi]}|f(a+re^{i\\theta})-f(a)|\\]\r\nwhich tends to zero as \\(r\\) tend to zero by continuity of \\(f\\) at \\(a\\)',258),(113,'','By Cauchy\'s Integral formula\r\n\\[f(z) = {1\\over 2\\pi i}\\int_{\\gamma(a,r)}{f(w)\\over w-z}dw = {1\\over 2\\pi i}\\int_{\\gamma(a,r)}{{f(w) \\over w-a} \\over 1 - {z-a \\over w-a}}dw\\]\r\nWith by binomial theorem\r\n\\[= {1\\over 2\\pi i}\\int_{\\gamma(a,r)}\\sum_{k=0}^\\infty f(w){(z-a)^k\\over (w-a)^{k+1}}dw\\]\r\nNow we want to swap the integral and sum, so we want uniform convergence\r\n\\[|\\int_{\\gamma(a,r)}f(w){(z-a)^k\\over (w-a)^{k+1}}dw| \\leq 2\\pi r sup_{w \\in \\gamma(a,r)}|f(w)|{|z-a|^k\\over r^{k+1}}\\]\r\nwhich exists as \\(f\\) is continuous and \\(\\gamma(a,r)\\) is compact<br/>\r\nSo set\r\n\\[M_k = 2\\pi r sup_{w\\in\\gamma(a,r)}|f(w)|{|z-a|^k\\over r^{k+1}}\\]\r\n\\(M_k\\) converges as it\'s a geometric sum, so by the Weierstrass M-test, the above converges absolutely.<br/>\r\nSo\r\n\\[f(z) = \\sum_{k=0}^\\infty({1\\over 2\\pi i}\\int_{\\gamma(a,r)}{f(w)\\over (w-a)^{k+1}}dw)(z-a)^k\\]\r\nso the Taylow coefficients exist, but we know it\'s valid to differentiate term by term inside \\(D(a,r)\\), so\r\n\\[c_k = {f^{(k)}(a) \\over k!}\\]\r\nand hence are unique.',259),(114,'','From mods analysis we know a power series defines an infinitely differentiable function on its disk of convergence.',260),(115,'','Say \\(|f| \\leq M\\) on \\(\\mathbb C\\) and \\(n \\geq 1\\). We know from Taylor\'s theorem that\r\n\\[f(z) = \\sum_{n=0}^\\infty c_nz^n, |c_n| = |{1\\over 2\\pi i}\\int_{\\gamma(0,r)}{f(w)\\over w^{n+1}}dw|\\]\r\nand by the estimation theorem\r\n\\[|c_n|\\leq {1\\over 2\\pi}\\times 2\\pi r \\times {M\\over r^{n+1}} = {M\\over r^n}\\]\r\nwhich tends to zero as \\(r\\to\\infty\\) for all \\(n\\gt0\\). Hence \\(f(z) = c_0\\)',261),(116,'','Suppose for a contradiction that \\(D(a,r) \\subset \\mathbb C \\setminus f(\\mathbb C)\\), so for all \\(z\\in\\mathbb C\\), \\(|f(z) - a| \\geq r\\) or equivalently \\(|{1\\over f(z)-a}| \\leq {1\\over r}\\)<br/>\r\nSo \\((f(z)-a)^{-1}\\) is a bounded holomorphic function on \\(\\mathbb C\\) and hence by Liouville\'s theorem is constant. Therefore \\(f\\) is constant, this is a contradiction.',262),(117,'','Say \\(p(z) = a_nz^n + ... + a_1z + a_0\\) where \\(a_i \\in \\mathbb C\\) and \\(a_n \\neq 0\\)<br/>\r\nAs \\({p(z) \\over z^n} \\to a_n\\) and \\(z \\to \\infty\\), there exists \\(R \\gt 0\\) s.t. \\(|{p(z)\\over z^n}| \\gt {1\\over 2}|a_n|\\) for \\(|z|\\gt R\\)<br/><br/>\r\nSuppose for a contradiction that \\(p(z)\\) has no root, then \\({1\\over p(z)}\\) is holomorphic on \\(\\mathbb C\\)<br/>\r\nThen\r\n\\[|{1\\over p(0)}| = |{1\\over 2\\pi i}\\int_{\\gamma(0,r)}{dw\\over wp(w)}|\\]\r\n\\[^{(for&nbsp;r\\gt R)} \\leq r \\times sup_{\\gamma(0,r)}|{1\\over wp(w)}| \\leq {2\\over |a_n|r^n}\\]\r\n\\[0 \\neq {1\\over |p(0)|} \\leq {2\\over |a_n|r^n}\\to 0&nbsp;as&nbsp;r\\to\\infty\\]\r\nThis is a contradiction, hence \\(p(x)\\) must have a root',264),(118,'','As \\(U\\) is a domain, (so open and connected), \\(U\\) is path connected.<br/>\r\nFix \\(a\\in U\\) and take \\(z\\in U\\), let \\(\\gamma\\) be a path from \\(a\\) to \\(z\\) and define \\(F(z) = \\int_\\gamma f(w)dw\\), this is well defined.<br/>\r\n<br/>\r\nTake \\(D(z,r)\\subset U\\) and \\(|h|\\lt r\\), then as \\(\\gamma_{z+h}\\cup [z+h,z]\\cup(-\\gamma_z)\\) is a closed path,\r\n\\[F(z+h)-F(z)-\\int_{[z,z+h]}f(w)dw = 0\\]\r\nThen\r\n\\[|{F(z+h)-F(z)\\over h} - f(z)| = |({1\\over h}\\int_{[z,z+h]}f(w)dw)-f(z)|\\]\r\n\\[ = |{1\\over h}\\int_{[z,z+h]}(f(w)-f(z))dw|\\]\r\n\\[\\leq {1\\over h}\\times L([z,z+h])\\times sup_{w\\in [z,z+h]}|f(w)-f(z)|\\]\r\nwhich tends to zero as \\(h \\to 0\\) by continuity of \\(f\\) at \\(z\\)<br/>\r\nTherefore \\(F\'(z) = f(z)\\), so \\(f\\) is holomorphic',265),(119,'','(a) \\(\\Rightarrow\\) (c)<br/>\r\nnothing to prove<br/>\r\n<br/>\r\n(c) \\(\\Rightarrow\\) (b)<br/>\r\nSuppose \\(a \\in U\\), \\(f^{(k)}(a) = 0\\) for all \\(k \\geq 0\\).<br/>\r\nBy Taylor\'s theorem there is \\(D(a,\\epsilon) \\subset U\\) s.t.\r\n\\[f(z) = \\sum_{n=1}^\\infty c_n(z-a)^n = 0 where c_n = {f^{(n)}(a) \\over n!} = 0\\]\r\nAs \\(D(a,\\epsilon) \\subset f^{-1}(0)\\), (b) follows<br/>\r\n<br/>\r\n(b) \\(\\Rightarrow\\) (a)<br/>\r\nLet \\(a \\in U\\) be a limit point of \\(f^{-1}(0)\\)<br/>\r\nBy Taylor\'s theorem there are \\(c_n\\) and \\(D(a,\\epsilon) \\subset U\\) s.t.\r\n\\[f(z) = \\sum_{n=1}^\\infty c_n(z-a)^n\\]\r\nFor a contradiction suppose not all of the \\(c_n\\) are zero, let \\(K\\) be the smallest integer s.t. \\(c_K \\neq 0\\)<br/>\r\nThen\r\n\\[f(z) = (z-a)^Kg(z) where g(z) = \\sum_{n=K}^\\infty c_n(z-a)^{n-K}\\]\r\nas \\(g(z)\\) is given by a power series, it is holomorphic.<br/>\r\nAlso, \\(g(a) = c_K \\neq 0\\), by continuity \\(\\exists \\delta\\) s.t. \\(g(z) \\neq 0\\) on \\(D(a, \\delta)\\)<br/>\r\nThen \\(f(z) = (z-a)^Kg(z)\\) is \\(0\\) in \\(D(a,\\delta)\\) only at \\(z=0\\) which contradicts \\(a\\) being a limit point of \\(f^{-1}(0)\\)<br/>\r\nTherefore \\(f(z) = 0\\) on some \\(D(a,\\epsilon)\\)<br/>\r\n<br/>\r\nLet \\(S\\) be the set of limit points of \\(f^{-1}(0)\\), as \\(f\\) is continuous, this is closed, so \\(S \\subset f^{-1}(0)\\)<br/>\r\nBy assumption \\(S \\neq \\emptyset\\), further is \\(a \\in S\\) then \\(f\\) is locally zero at \\(a\\), so \\(S\\) is open.<br/>\r\nIf \\(z \\in U \\setminus S\\), then \\(z\\) is not a limit point of \\(f^{-1}(0)\\), so \\(\\exists r \\gt 0\\) s.t. \\(D(a,r) \\subset U \\setminus S\\), this means that \\(S\\) is closed.<br/>\r\nBy connectedness of \\(U\\), \\(S = U\\), therefore \\(f(z) = 0\\) for all \\(z \\in U\\)',267),(120,'','Apply identity theorem to \\(f-g\\)',268),(121,'','Say the zeros of \\(f\\) are \\(a_1,...,a_k\\) with multiplicities \\(m_1,...,m_k\\), \\({f\'(z)\\over f(z)}\\) is holomorphic in \\(\\gamma\\) except at \\(a_1,...,a_k\\)<br/>\r\nNear \\(a_i\\), we can write \\(f(z) = (z-a_i)^{m_i}g_i(z)\\) where \\(g_i(z)\\) is holomorphic and \\(g_i(a_i) \\neq 0\\)\r\n\\[{f\'(z)\\over f(z)} = {m_i\\over z-a_i} + {g_i\'(z)\\over g_i(z)}\\]\r\nhence \\({f\'(z)\\over f(z)}-{m_i\\over z-a_i}\\) is holomorphic at \\(a_i\\)<br/>\r\nSo \\({f\'(z)\\over f(z)}-\\sum_{i=1}^k{m_i\\over z-a_i}\\) is holormorphic on and inside \\(\\gamma\\)<br/>\r\nSo by Cauchy\'s theorem\r\n\\[\\int_\\gamma{f\'(z)\\over f(z)}dz = \\int_\\gamma\\sum_{i=1}^k{m_i\\over z-a_i}dz\\]\r\n\\[= \\sum_{i=1}^k\\int_\\gamma{m_i\\over z-a_i}dz = \\sum_{i=1}^k\\int_{\\gamma(a_i,\\epsilon_i)}{m_i\\over z-a_i}dz\\]\r\n\\[= \\sum_{i=1}^k2\\pi im_i = 2\\pi i\\times(number&nbsp;of&nbsp;zeros)\\]',270),(122,'','(Existance)<br/>\r\nLet \\(\\{e_1,...,e_n\\}\\) be an orthonormal basis for \\(V\\), let \\(\\{f_1,...,f_n\\}\\) be the dual basis.<br/>\r\nDefine \\(\\phi(\\alpha_1e_1+...+\\alpha_ne_n) = \\overline{\\alpha_1}f_1+...+\\overline{\\alpha_n}f_n\\), then\r\n\\[\\phi(e_i)(e_j) = f_i(e_j) = \\delta_{ij} = \\langle e_j,e_i \\rangle\\]\r\nSo as the above are linear and agree on a basis \\(\\phi(e_i)(v) \\equiv \\langle v,e_i \\rangle\\)<br/>\r\nFor any \\(v\\in V\\), \\(v = \\alpha_1e_1+...+\\alpha_ne_n\\), then\r\n\\[\\phi(v)(u) = (\\overline\\alpha_1f_1+...+\\overline\\alpha_nf_n)(u)\\]\r\n\\[= \\overline\\alpha_1f_1(u)+...+\\overline\\alpha_nf_n(u)=\\overline\\alpha_1\\phi(e_1)(u)+...+\\overline\\alpha_n\\phi(e_n)(u)\\]\r\n\\[=\\overline\\alpha_1\\langle u,e_1\\rangle+...+\\overline\\alpha_n\\langle u,e_n\\rangle=\\langle u,\\alpha_1e_1+...+\\alpha_ne_n\\rangle=\\langle u,v\\rangle\\]\r\n<br/>\r\n(Uniqueness)<br/>\r\n\\[\\phi(e_i)(e_j)=\\langle e_j,e_i\\rangle=\\delta_{ij}=f_i(e_j)\\]\r\nso \\(\\phi(e_i)=f_i\\), uniqueness of \\(\\phi\\) follows',272),(123,'','Let \\(w = \\sum_{i=1}^n\\langle v,e_i\\rangle e_i\\), then\r\n\\[0 \\leq \\langle v-w,v-w\\rangle = \\langle v-\\sum_{i=1}^n\\langle v,e_i\\rangle e_i, v-\\sum_{i=1}^n\\langle v,e_i\\rangle e_i\\rangle\\]\r\n\\[= \\langle v,v\\rangle-\\sum_{i=1}^n\\overline{\\langle v,e_i\\rangle}\\langle v,e_i\\rangle - \\sum_{i=1}^n\\langle v,e_i\\rangle\\langle e_i,v\\rangle + \\sum_{i=1}^n\\sum_{j=1}^n\\langle v,e_i\\rangle\\overline{\\langle v,e_j\\rangle}\\langle e_i,e_j\\rangle\\]\r\n\\[= \\langle v,v\\rangle - \\sum_{i=1}^n\\langle v,e_i\\rangle\\overline{\\langle v,e_i\\rangle} = \\langle v,v\\rangle - \\sum_{i=1}^n|\\langle v,e_i\\rangle|^2\\]\r\nSo\r\n\\[\\langle v,v\\rangle \\geq \\sum_{i=1}^n|\\langle v,e_i\\rangle|^2\\]\r\n<br/>\r\n<br/>\r\nEquality occurs iff \\(v-w=0\\)<br/>\r\n<ul>\r\n<li>If \\(v=w\\), then \\(v \\in span\\{e_1,...,e_n\\}\\)</li>\r\n<li>\r\nIf \\(v \\neq w\\), then\r\n\\[\\langle v-w,e_i\\rangle = \\langle v-\\sum_{j=1}^n\\langle v,e_j\\rangle e_j, e_i\\rangle = \\langle v,e_i\\rangle - \\sum_{i=1}^n\\langle v,e_j\\rangle\\langle e_j,e_i\\rangle = 0\\]\r\nSo \\(\\langle v-w,u\\rangle=0\\) for all \\(u\\in span\\{e_1,...,e_n\\}\\)<br/>\r\nIf \\(v \\in span\\{e_1,...,e_n\\}\\), then \\(v-w\\in span\\{e_1,...,e_n\\}\\), so \\(v=w\\)\r\n</li>\r\n</ul>',276),(124,'','Let \\(B = \\{e_1,...,e_n\\}\\) be an orthonormal basis.<br/>\r\nIf \\(v\\in V\\), write \\([v]\\) for the representation of \\(v\\) with respect to \\(B\\).<br/>\r\nIf \\(S \\in Hom(V,V)\\), write \\([S]\\) to mean \\(M_B^B(S)\\)<br/>\r\n<br/>\r\n\\((1)\\Rightarrow(2)\\)<br/>\r\n\\[\\langle T(v),T(w)\\rangle=[T(v)]^T\\overline{[T(w)]}=([T][v])^T\\overline{([T][w])}\\]\r\n\\[= [V]^T[T]^T\\overline{[T]}\\overline{[w]}=[v]^T\\overline{[w]}=\\langle v,w\\rangle\\]\r\n<br/>\r\n\\((2)\\Rightarrow(1)\\)<br/>\r\nSuppose \\(\\langle T(v),T(w)\\rangle=\\langle v,w\\rangle\\) for all \\(v,w\\in V\\). Then for all \\(i,j\\),\r\n\\[\\langle T(e_i),T(e_j)\\rangle=\\angle e_i,e_j\\rangle=\\delta_{ij}\\]\r\nBut \\[\\langle T(e_i),T(e_j)\\rangle=[e_i]^T[T]^T\\overline{[T]}\\overline{[e_j]}=ij^{th}&nbsp;element&nbsp;of&nbsp;[T]^T\\overline{[T]}=\\delta_{ij}\\]\r\nHence \\([T]^T\\overline{[T]}=I\\), so \\(T\\) is orthogonal',275),(125,'Induction','Suppose \\(a = up_1...p_k\\), \\(b = vq_1...q_l\\) where \\(u,v\\) are units, \\(p_i,q_i\\) are irreducible.<br/>\r\n<br/>\r\n<ul>\r\n<li>Base case:<br/>\r\n\\(k=0\\), then \\(a\\) is a unit, so the highest common factor \\(hcf(a,b) = 1\\)<br/><br/><br/>\r\n</li>\r\n<li>Inductive step case 1: \\(p_1 \\not|  b\\)<br/>\r\nlet \\(a\' = up_2...p_k\\), by the inductive hypothesis \\(a\', b\\) have a highest common factor \\(d\\).<br/>\r\nClaim that \\(d = hcf(a,b)\\)<br/>\r\nWell, \\(d |  a\'\\) and \\(d  |  b\\), so \\(d  |  a\\) and \\(d  |  b\\).<br/>\r\nSuppose \\(f  |  a\\) and \\(f  |  b\\), then \\(a = fg\\), look at the factorizations of \\(f\\) and \\(g\\), the product of these gives a factorization of \\(a\\), but the factorization of \\(a\\) is unique, so \\(p_1 \\not|  f\\) or \\(p_1  |  b\\).<br/>\r\nSo \\(p_1  |  g \\Rightarrow g = p_1h \\Rightarrow a = fp_1h \\Rightarrow a\'=fh \\Rightarrow f |  a\'\\)<br/>\r\nso \\(f |  a\'\\) and \\(f  |  b\\), so \\(f  |  d\\) as \\(d = hcf(a\',b)\\)<br/>\r\nSo \\(d = hcf(a,b)\\)<br/><br/><br/>\r\n</li>\r\n<li>Inductive step case 2: \\(p_1  |  b\\)<br/>\r\nWrite \\(b = p_1e\\), the factorization of \\(e\\) together with \\(p_1\\) gives a factorization of \\(b\\). But \\(b\\) has a unique factorization, so \\(\\exists j\\) s.t. \\(q_j\\) is a unit multiple of \\(p_1\\), so \\(q_j = wp_1\\).<br/>\r\nLook at \\(a\' = up_2...p_k\\) and \\(b\' = vq_1...q_{j-1}q_P{j+1}...q_l\\), let \\(d = hcf(a\',b\')\\), by inductive hypothesis.<br/>\r\nThen \\(p_1d = hcf(a,b)\\)\r\n</li>',277),(126,'','Suppose \\(p(x) = a_0 + a_1x + ... + a_nx^n\\) and \\(q(x) = b_0 + b_1x + ... + b_mx^m\\) are primitive.<br/>\r\nLet \\(k \\in \\mathbb Z\\) be prime, \\(p(x)\\) is primitive, so \\(k\\) is not a factor of some \\(a_s\\) where \\(s\\) is minimal. Also let \\(t\\) be least s.t. \\(k \\not|&nbsp; b_t\\)<br/>\r\nLook at the coefficient \\(c_{s+t}\\) of \\(x^{s+t}\\) in \\(p(x)q(x)\\),<br/>\r\n\\[c_{s+t} = a_0b_{s+t} + a_1b_{s+t-1} + ... + a_{s+t-1}b_1 + a_{s+t}b_0\\]\r\n\\[k&nbsp;|&nbsp;a_0, ..., a_{s-1}&nbsp;and&nbsp;k&nbsp;|&nbsp;b_0, ..., b_{t-1}\\]\r\nSo \\(k&nbsp;|&nbsp;c_{s+t}-a_sb_t\\), but \\(k \\not|&nbsp;a_s, b_t\\), so \\(k\\not|&nbsp;a_sb_t\\), hence \\(k\\not|&nbsp;c_{s+t}\\)<br/>\r\nTherefore \\(p(x)q(x)\\) is primitive.',279),(127,'','\\((\\Rightarrow)\\) trivial<br/>\r\n<br/>\r\n\\((\\Leftarrow)\\)<br/>\r\nSuppose \\(p(x) = q(x)r(x)\\) where \\(q(x), r(x) \\in \\mathbb Q[x]\\), \\(q,r\\) are not constant.<br/>\r\nSay \\(q(x) = a_0 + a_1x + ... + a_mx^m\\), \\(r(x) = b_0 + b_1x + ... + b_nx^n\\).<br/>\r\nPut all \\(a_i\\) over a common denominator, write \\(q(x) = {1\\over c}q\'(x)\\) where \\(c \\in \\mathbb Z\\), \\(q\'(x) \\in \\mathbb Z[x]\\)<br/>\r\nLet \\(a\\) be the content of \\(q\'(x)\\), write \\(q(x) = {a\\over c}q\'\'(x)\\) where \\(q\'\'(x)\\) is primitive.<br/>\r\nSimilarly write \\(r(x) = {b\\over d}r\'\'(x)\\) where \\(r\'\'(x) \\in \\mathbb Z[x]\\) and is primitive.<br/>\r\n<br/>\r\n\\(q\'\'(x)r\'\'(x)\\) is a primitive polynomial and is a rational multiple of \\(p(x)\\).<br/>\r\n<br/>\r\nIf \\(p(x)\\) is primitive, write \\(p(x) = {ab\\over cd}q\'\'(x)r\'\'(x)\\), then \\(cd\\) is the content of the LHS and \\(ab\\) is the content of the RHS. So \\(cd = ab\\) and \\(p(x) = q\'\'(x)r\'\'(x)\\).<br/>\r\n<br/>\r\nIf \\(p(x)\\) is not primitive, say \\(p(x) = \\alpha p\'\'(x)\\) where \\(p\'\'(x)\\) is primitive.<br/>\r\nThen \\(p\'\'(x) = q\'\'(x)r\'\'(x)\\) and \\(p(x) = (\\alpha q\'\')(x)r\'\'(x)\\)<br/>\r\n<br/>\r\nso if \\(p(x)\\) is irreducible over \\(\\mathbb Q[x]\\) then it is irreducible over \\(\\mathbb Z[x]\\)',280),(128,'Induction','Suppose \\(p(x) = q(x)r(x)\\) where \\(q(x), r(x)\\) are not constant, without loss of generality assume \\(q(x), r(x) \\in \\mathbb Z[x]\\).<br/>\r\nSuppose \\(p(x) = a_0 + ... + a_nx^n\\), \\(s &nbsp;|&nbsp; a_0,...,a_{n-1}\\), \\(s^2 \\not|&nbsp;a_0\\),<br/>\r\nwrite \\(q(x) = b_0 + ... + b_mx^m\\), \\(r(x) = c_0 + ... + c_kx^k\\) where \\(m,k \\geq 1\\) and \\(m+k = n\\).<br/>\r\n<br/>\r\nWe will prove by induction on \\(i \\leq max(m,k)\\) that either \\(s&nbsp;|&nbsp;b_0,...,b_i\\) and \\(s\\not|&nbsp;c_0\\) or that \\(s&nbsp;|&nbsp;c_0,...,c_i\\) and \\(s\\not|&nbsp;b_0\\)<br/>\r\n<ul>\r\n<li>Base case: \\(i=0\\)<br/>\r\n\\(a_0 = b_0c_0\\)<br/>\r\n\\(s&nbsp;|&nbsp;a_0 \\Rightarrow s&nbsp;|&nbsp;b_0c_0\\Rightarrow s&nbsp;|&nbsp;b_0\\) or \\(s&nbsp;|&nbsp;c_0\\) as \\(s\\) is prime.<br/>\r\n\\(s^2\\not|&nbsp;a_0\\) so if \\(s&nbsp;|&nbsp;b_0\\) then \\(s\\not|&nbsp;c_0\\) and \\(s&nbsp;|&nbsp;c_0 \\Rightarrow s\\not|&nbsp;b_0\\)<br/><br/>\r\n</li>\r\n<li>Inductive step: \\(0 \\lt i \\leq max(m,k) \\lt n\\)<br/>\r\nSuppose \\(s&nbsp;|&nbsp;b_0,...,b_{i-1}\\), \\(s\\not|&nbsp;c_0\\),<br/>\r\n\\(a_i = b_0c_i + b_1c_{i-1} + ... + b_{i-1}c_1 + b_ic_0\\), \\(s&nbsp;|&nbsp;a_i\\) as \\(i\\lt n\\), \\(s&nbsp;|&nbsp;b_j\\) for \\(j\\lt i\\), so \\(s&nbsp;|&nbsp;b_ic_0\\)<br/>\r\n\\(s\\) is prime and by assumption, \\(s&nbsp;|&nbsp;b_i\\), now either \\(s&nbsp;|&nbsp;b_i\\) for all \\(i \\leq m\\) or \\(s&nbsp;|&nbsp;c_i\\) for all \\(i\\leq k\\),<br/>\r\nclearly \\(s&nbsp;|&nbsp;a_i\\) for all \\(i\\), so \\(s&nbsp;|&nbsp;a_n\\)\r\n</li>\r\n</ul>',281),(129,'','Write \\(q(x) = p(x + \\alpha)\\), \\(p(x) = r(x)s(x)\\), then \\(q(x) = r(x+\\alpha)s(x+\\alpha)\\) then \\(p(x) = r(x-\\alpha)s(r-\\alpha)\\)',282),(130,'','\\(\\langle v-\\lambda w,v-\\lambda w\\rangle\\geq0\\) by positive definiteness for any \\(\\lambda\\)<br/>\r\n\\[\\langle v-\\lambda w,v-\\lambda w\\rangle=\\langle v,v\\rangle-\\lambda\\langle w,v\\rangle-\\overline\\lambda\\langle v,w\\rangle+\\lambda\\overline\\lambda\\langle w,w\\rangle\\]\r\n\\[=\\langle v,v\\rangle-\\lambda\\overline{\\langle v,w\\rangle}-\\overline\\lambda\\langle v,w\\rangle+|\\lambda|^2\\langle w,w\\rangle\\]\r\nPut \\(\\lambda = {\\|v\\|\\over\\|w\\|}{\\langle v,w\\rangle\\over|\\langle v,w\\rangle|}\\), then\r\n\\[\\langle v-\\lambda w,v-\\lambda w\\rangle=2(\\|v\\|^2-{\\|v\\|\\over\\|w\\|}|\\langle v,w\\rangle|)\\geq0\\]\r\n\\[\\Rightarrow {\\|w\\|\\over2\\|v\\|}(2(\\|v\\|^2-{\\|v\\|\\over\\|w\\|}|\\langle v,w\\rangle|))=\\|v\\|\\|w\\|-|\\langle v,w\\rangle|\\geq0\\]\r\n\\[\\Rightarrow \\|v\\|\\|w\\| \\geq |\\langle v,w\\rangle|\\]\r\n<br/><br/>\r\nSuppose we have equality, then \\(\\langle v-\\lambda w,v-\\lambda w\\rangle=0\\), so \\(v-\\lambda w=0\\), so \\(v,w\\) are linearly dependent.<br/>\r\nSuppose \\(v,w\\) are linearly dependent, where \\(v=\\mu w\\), then it is easy to show to \\(|\\langle v,w\\rangle|=\\|v\\|\\|w\\|\\)',283),(131,'','<ul>\r\n<li>(Existence)<br/>\r\nIf \\(B\\) is any orthonormal basis, define \\(T^*\\) to be the linear transformation with matrix \\(\\overline{A^T}\\) where \\(A = M_B^B(T)\\)<br/>\r\nAgain writing \\([v]\\) to mean the representation of \\(v\\) in terms of elements of \\(B\\).<br/>\r\n\\[\\langle T(u),v\\rangle=[T(u)]^T\\overline{[v]}=(A[u])^T\\overline{[v]}=[u]^TA^T\\overline{[v]}=[u]^T\\overline{\\overline{A^T}}\\overline{[v]}\\]\r\n\\[=[u]^T\\overline{\\overline{A^T}[v]}=[u]^T\\overline{[T^*(v)]}=\\langle u,T^*(v)\\rangle\\]\r\n<br/><br/>\r\n</li>\r\n<li>(Uniqueness)<br/>\r\nSuppose \\(T^\\dagger\\) also satisfies \\(\\langle T(u),v\\rangle=\\langle u,T^\\dagger(v)\\rangle\\)<br/>\r\nThen \\(\\langle T(u),v\\rangle=\\langle u,T^*(v)\\rangle=\\langle u,T^\\dagger(v)\\rangle\\) for all \\(u,v\\in V\\)<br/>\r\nSo \\(\\langle u,T^*(v)\\rangle-\\langle u,T^\\dagger(v)\\rangle=0\\)<br/>\r\nLetting \\(u=T^*(v)-T^\\dagger(v)\\), \\(\\langle T^*(v)-T^\\dagger(v),T^*(v)-T^\\dagger(v)\\rangle=0\\), so \\(T^*(v)=T^\\dagger(v)\\) and \\(T^*=T^\\dagger\\)\r\n</li>\r\n</ul>',285),(132,'','\\[\\langle T^*(u),v\\rangle=\\overline{\\langle v,T^*(u)\\rangle}=\\overline{\\langle T(v),u\\rangle}=\\langle u,T(v)\\rangle\\]\r\nSo by the uniqueness of adjoints, \\(T^{**}=T\\)',286),(133,'','\\(m_T(T)=0\\), so \\(\\overline{m_T}(T^*)=0\\), so \\(m_{T^*}&nbsp;|&nbsp;\\overline{m_T}\\)<br/>\r\nSimilarly \\(m_T=m_{T^{**}}&nbsp;|&nbsp;\\overline{m_{T^*}}\\), so \\(m_T&nbsp;|&nbsp;\\overline{m_{T^*}}\\) iff \\(\\overline{m_T}&nbsp;|&nbsp;m_{T^*}\\)<br/>\r\nBoth \\(\\overline{m_T}\\) and \\(m_{T^*}\\) are monic, hence \\(\\overline{m_T}=m_{T^*}\\)',290),(134,'','Suppose \\(T(v) = \\lambda v\\), \\(v \\neq 0\\),\r\n\\[then&nbsp;\\langle T(v),v\\rangle=\\langle\\lambda v,v\\rangle=\\lambda\\langle v,v\\rangle\\]\r\n\\[But&nbsp;\\langle T(v),v\\rangle=\\langle v,T^*(v)\\rangle=\\langle v,T(v)\\rangle=\\langle v,\\lambda v\\rangle=\\overline\\lambda\\langle v,v\\rangle\\]\r\nTherefore \\(\\lambda = \\overline\\lambda\\), so \\(\\lambda\\in\\mathbb R\\)',293),(135,'','Suppose \\(T(v)=\\mu v\\), \\(T(u)=\\lambda u\\), where \\(\\mu\\neq\\lambda\\), \\(u,v\\neq0\\)<br/>\r\nBy the previous result, \\(\\mu,\\lambda\\in\\mathbb R\\)<br/>\r\n\\[Then&nbsp;\\langle T(u),v\\rangle=\\langle\\lambda u,v\\rangle=\\lambda\\langle u,v\\rangle\\]\r\n\\[And&nbsp;\\langle T(u),v\\rangle=\\langle u,T^*(v)\\rangle=\\langle u,T(v)\\rangle=\\langle u,\\mu v\\rangle=\\overline\\mu\\langle u,v\\rangle\\]\r\n\\[Then&nbsp;\\lambda\\langle u,v\\rangle=\\overline\\mu\\langle u,v\\rangle\\Rightarrow\\lambda\\langle u,v\\rangle=\\mu\\langle u,v\\rangle&nbsp;as&nbsp;\\mu,\\lambda\\in\\mathbb R\\]\r\nBut \\(\\mu\\neq\\lambda\\), so \\(\\langle u,v\\rangle=0\\), so \\(u,v\\) are orthogonal',294),(136,'','If \\(V\\) is a complex i.p.s., then \\(\\chi_T(x)\\) as a root so there is an eigenvalue. So if \\(A\\) is a hermitian matrix then \\(\\chi_A(x)\\) has a root which must be real.<br/>\r\nSo if \\(A\\) is a real symetric matrix, then \\(A\\) is hermitian, so \\(\\chi_A(x)\\) has a root.\r\nSo if \\(V\\) is a real i.p.s., then \\(\\chi_T(x)\\) has a root in \\(\\mathbb R\\)',295),(137,'Induction','We use induction on \\(dim V\\)\r\n<ul>\r\n<li>Base case: \\(dim V = 0\\)<br/>\r\nthe result is vacuously true<br/>\r\n<br/>\r\n</li>\r\n<li>Inductive step: \\(0\\lt dim V\\)<br/>\r\nLet \\(v_0\\) be an eigenvector, w.l.o.g. assume \\(\\|v_0\\|=1\\)<br/>\r\nLet \\(U=span\\{v_0\\}^\\perp\\), \\(v_0\\not\\in U\\), so \\(dim U\\lt dim V\\)<br/>\r\n\\(U\\) is \\(T\\) invariant, as if \\(u\\in U\\), then \\(\\langle v_0,u\\rangle=0\\), so\r\n\\[\\langle v_0,T(u)\\rangle=\\langle v_0,T^*(u)\\rangle=\\langle T(v_0),u\\rangle=\\langle\\lambda v_0,u\\rangle=\\lambda\\langle v_0,u\\rangle=0\\]\r\nSo \\(T|_U\\) is a self-adjoint map on \\(U\\), \\(dim U\\lt dim V\\) so by the inductive hypothesis there is an orthonormal basis \\{v_1,...,v_n\\}\\) of eigenvectors of \\(T|_U\\) for \\(U\\).<br/>\r\nClearly \\(\\{v_0,v_1,...,v_n\\}\\) is an orthonormal set/<br/>\r\n\\[span\\{v_0,v_1,...,v_n\\}=span\\{v_0\\}+U=span\\{v_0\\}+span\\{v_0\\}^\\perp=V\\]\r\nTherefore \\(\\{v_0,v_1,...,v_n\\}\\) is a basis of eigencevtors of \\(T\\) for \\(V\\)\r\n</li>\r\n</ul>',297),(138,'','First note that \\(v\\in(im T)^\\perp\\) iff \\(\\langle T(u),v\\rangle=0\\) for all \\(u\\in V\\) iff \\(\\langle u,T^*(v)\\rangle=0\\) for all \\(u\\in V\\)<br/><br/>\r\nIf \\(v\\in ker(T^*)\\), then \\(T^*(v)=0\\) so \\(\\langle u,T^*(v)\\rangle=0\\) for all \\(u\\in V\\).<br/>\r\nIf \\(\\langle u,T^*(v)\\rangle=0\\) for all \\(u\\in V\\), then \\(\\langle T^*(v),T^*(v)\\rangle=0\\) so \\(T^*(v)=0\\) so \\(v\\in ker(T^*)\\)',298),(139,'','Let \\(A\\) be the matrix of \\(T\\) w.r.t. some orthonormal basis.<br/>\r\nThen the matrix of \\(T^*\\) is a transposed complex conjugate.<br/>\r\n\\[\\chi_{\\overline{A^T}}(x)=det(xI-\\overline{A^T})=det(\\overline{xI-A^T})=\\overline{det(xI-A^T)}\\]\r\n\\[=\\overline{det((xI-A)^T)}=\\overline{det(xI-A)}=\\overline{\\chi_A(x)}\\]',299),(140,'','If \\(v \\in U\\cap U^\\perp\\) then \\(\\langle v,v\\rangle=0\\Rightarrow v=0\\)<br/>\r\n<br/>\r\nSuppose \\(V\\) is finite dimensional, let \\(\\{e_1,...,e_m\\}\\) be an orthonormal basis for \\(U\\), if \\(v \\in V\\) then\r\n\\[v=\\sum_{i=1}^m\\langle v,e_i\\rangle e_i+v-\\sum_{i=1}^m\\langle v,e_i\\rangle e_i\\]\r\n\\[Obviously&nbsp;\\sum_{i=1}^m\\langle v,e_i\\rangle e_i \\in U\\]\r\n\\[And&nbsp;\\langle v-\\sum_{i=1}^m\\langle v,e_i\\rangle,e_j\\rangle=\\langle v,e_j\\rangle-\\sum_{i=1}^m\\langle v,e_i\\rangle\\langle e_i,e_j\\rangle=\\langle v,e_j\\rangle-\\langle v,e_j\\rangle=0\\]\r\n\\[So&nbsp;v-\\sum_{i=1}^m\\langle v,e_i\\rangle e_i\\in U^\\perp\\]',301),(141,'','\\(\\forall v\\in U^\\perp, \\forall u\\in U, \\langle u,v\\rangle=0\\).<br/>\r\nSo if \\(u\\in U\\), then \\(u\\in\\{w\\in V: \\forall v\\in U^\\perp, \\langle w,v\\rangle=0\\}\\), hence \\(u\\in U^{\\perp\\perp}\\)<br/>\r\nSo \\(U\\leq U^{\\perp\\perp}\\)<br/>\r\n<br/>\r\nIf \\(V\\) is f.d. then \\(dim U^{\\perp\\perp} = dim V - dim U^\\perp = dim V - (dim V - dim U) = dim U\\).<br/>\r\nSo \\(U = U^{\\perp\\perp}\\)',302),(142,'','Diagonal matrices commute',303),(143,'','For each eigenvalue \\(\\lambda\\) of \\(S\\), let \\(V_\\lambda\\) be the corresponding eigenspace, \\(ker (S-\\lambda I)\\)<br/>\r\n\\(V_\\lambda\\) is T-invariant as if \\(v\\in V_\\lambda\\), then \\(ST(v)=TS(v)=T(\\lambda v)=\\lambda(T(v))\\), so \\(T(v)\\in V_\\lambda\\)<br/>\r\n\\(T|_{V_\\lambda}\\) is self-adjoint, so has an orthonormal basis of eigenvectors \\(B_\\lambda\\), let \\(B = \\cup_\\lambda B_\\lambda\\). \\(B\\) is orthonormal as the \\(V_\\lambda\\) are orthogonal to each other. \\(B\\) is a spanning set and hence is a basis as \\(S\\) is diagonalizable.',304),(144,'','For ease of notation and without loss of generality, assume \\(a=0\\)<br/>\r\nChoose \\(z\\in A\\) and \\(P,Q\\) s.t. \\(R\\lt P\\lt|z|\\lt Q\\lt S\\)<br/>\r\n<br/>\r\nLet \\(\\gamma_1\\) be a path that follows the upper semicircles with radii \\(P\\) and \\(Q\\), going in opposite directions, they are then joined by horizontal lines. Let \\(\\gamma_2\\) do the same but with lower semicircles. Together the connecting lines should cancel out and we should just have the two complete circles.<br/>\r\n<br/>\r\nThen\r\n\\[\\int_{\\gamma(0,Q)}{f(w)\\over w-z}dw-\\int_{\\gamma(0,P)}{f(w)\\over w-z}dw\\]\r\n\\[=\\int_{\\gamma_1}{f(w)\\over w-z}dw+\\int_{\\gamma_2}{f(w)\\over w-z}dw=2\\pi if(z)\\]\r\n\\[So f(z)={1\\over 2\\pi i}\\int_{\\gamma(0,Q)}{f(w)\\over w-z}dw-{1\\over 2\\pi i}\\int_{\\gamma(0,P)}{f(w)\\over w-z}dw\\]\r\n\\[={1\\over 2\\pi i}\\int_{\\gamma(0,Q)}{{f(w)\\over w}\\over1-{z\\over w}}+{1\\over 2\\pi i}\\int_{\\gamma(0,P)}{{f(w)\\over z}\\over1-{w\\over z}}dw\\]\r\n\\[={1\\over 2\\pi i}\\int_{\\gamma(0,Q)}\\sum_{n=0}^\\infty{f(w)z^n\\over w^{n+1}}dw+{1\\over 2\\pi i}\\int_{\\gamma(0,P)}\\sum_{n=0}^\\infty{f(w)w^n\\over z^{n+1}}dw\\]\r\nUsing the Wieierstrass M-Test to show uniform convergence, swap the integrals and sums to get...\r\n\\[=\\sum_{n=0}^\\infty({1\\over 2\\pi i}\\int_{\\gamma(0,Q)}{f(w)\\over w^{n+1}}dw)z^n+\\sum_{m=1}^\\infty({1\\over 2\\pi i}\\int_{\\gamma(0,P)}f(w)w^{m-1}dw)z^{-m}\\]\r\nWhich by the deformation theorem\r\n\\[=\\sum_{n=-\\infty}^\\infty({1\\over 2\\pi i}\\int_{\\gamma(0,r)}{f(w)\\over w^{n+1}}dw)z^n\\]\r\n<br/><br/>\r\n(Uniqueness)<br/>\r\n\\[Suppose f(z)=\\sum_{n=-\\infty}^\\infty c_nz^n=\\sum_{n=-\\infty}^\\infty d_nz^n\\]\r\n\\[where c_n={1\\over 2\\pi i}\\int_{\\gamma(0,r)}{f(w)\\over w^{n+1}}dw\\]\r\nWe know that\r\n\\[2\\pi ic_n=\\int_{\\gamma(0,r)}{f(w)\\over w^{n+1}}dw=\\int_{\\gamma(0,r)}\\sum_{k=-\\infty}^\\infty d_kw^{k-n-1}dw\\]\r\nAny power series is uniformly convergent on a compact subset of its disk of convergence, so\r\n\\[2\\pi ic_n=\\sum_{k=-\\infty}^\\infty d_k\\int_{\\gamma(0,r)}w^{k-n-1}dw=2\\pi id_n\\]',305),(145,'','We may write \\(f(z)=(z-a)^mh(z),g(z)=(z-a)^nk(z)\\) where \\(h,k\\) are holormorphic at \\(a\\) and \\(h(a),k(a)\\neq0\\).<br/>\r\n<br/>\r\nSo \\({f(z)\\over g(z)}=(z-a)^{m-n}{h(z)\\over k(z)}\\) where \\(h(z)\\over k(z)\\) is holormorphic at \\(a\\)<br/>\r\nIf \\(m\\geq n\\), then \\(f\\over g\\) is basically holormorphic at \\(a\\) and only lacks a sensible definition<br/>\r\nIf \\(m\\lt n\\), then we have a pole of order \\(m-n\\)',308),(146,'','The Laurent expansion of \\(f\\) at \\(a\\) is \\(f(z)={R\\over z-a}+k(z)\\) where \\(R=res(f;a)\\) and \\(k\\) is holomorphic at \\(a\\). Then \\(R=\\lim_{z\\to a}(z-a)f(z)\\)<br/>\r\nIf \\(f(z)={g(z)\\over h(z)}\\) then by L\'Hopital\'s rule \\(\\lim_{z\\to a}{(z-a)g(z)\\over h(z)}=\\lim_{z\\to a}{g(z)+(z-a)g\'(z)\\over h\'(z)}={g(a)\\over h\'(a)}\\)',310),(147,'','Note \\(g(z)=\\sum_{k=0}^\\infty{g^{(k)}(a)\\over k!}(z-a)^k\\) and then the coefficient of \\((z-a)^{-1}\\) is \\(g^{(n-1)}(a)\\over(n-1)!\\)',311),(148,'','At each point we ca write \\(f(z)\\) as its Laurent expansion, so we have\r\n\\[f(z)=g_k(z)+h_k(z)\\]\r\n\\[where&nbsp;g_k(z)=\\sum_{n=0}^\\infty c_n^{(k)}(z-a_k)^n&nbsp;and&nbsp;h_k(z)=\\sum_{n=-\\infty}^{-1}c_n^{(k)}(z-a_k)^n\\]\r\nNote that \\(h_k(z)\\) converges everywhere except \\(a_k\\)<br/>\r\nSo \\(F(z)=f(z)-\\sum_{k=1}^mh_k(z)\\) is holomorphic in and on \\(\\gamma\\), or rather that \\(F(z)\\) has only removable singularities at the \\(a_k\\).<br/>\r\nBy Cauchy\'s theorem,\r\n\\[\\int_\\gamma f(z)dz=\\sum_{k=1}^m\\int_\\gamma\\sum_{n=-\\infty}^{-1}c_n^{(k)}(z-a)^ndz\\]\r\nIn the proof of Laurent\'s theorem, we saw that the Laurent expansion converges uniformly on any \\(\\gamma(a_k,r_k)\\), so we can swap the integral and sum to get\r\n\\[\\int_\\gamma f(z)dz=\\sum_{k=1}^m\\sum_{n=-\\infty}^{-1}\\int_\\gamma c_n^{(k)}(z-a)^ndz=\\sum_{k=1}^m2\\pi ic_{-1}^{(k)}=2\\pi i\\sum_{k=1}^mres(f;a_k)\\]',312),(149,'','In each case we apply the \\(g(a)\\over h\'(a)\\) formula to get\r\n\\[res({f(z)\\pi\\over tan(\\pi z)};n)={\\pi f(n)\\over\\pi sec^2(\\pi n)}=f(z)\\]\r\n\\[res({f(z)\\pi\\over sin(\\pi z)};n)={\\pi f(n)\\over\\pi cos(\\pi n)}=(-1)^nf(z)\\]',313),(150,'','Say \\(\\gamma_1,\\gamma_2\\) are differentiable curves in \\(U\\) and they cross at \\(p\\). Parametrize both so that \\(\\gamma_1(0)=\\gamma_2(0)=p\\).<br/>\r\nThen the angle between them at \\(p\\) is \\[\\theta=arg(\\gamma_2\'(0))-arg(\\gamma_1\'(0))=arg({\\gamma_2\'(0)\\over\\gamma_1\'(0)})\\]\r\nThe images \\(f(\\gamma_1)\\) and \\(f(\\gamma_2)\\) meet at \\(f(p)\\) at an angle\r\n\\[\\phi=arg({(f\\gamma_2)\'(0)\\over(f\\gamma_1)\'(0)})\\]\r\nUsing the chain rule,\r\n\\[\\phi=arg({f\'(p)\\gamma_2\'(0)\\over f\'(p)\\gamma_1\'(0)})=arg({\\gamma_2\'(0)\\over\\gamma_1\'(0)})=\\theta\\]',315),(151,'','Suppose \\(f(x,y)=(u(x,y),v(x,y))\\), then we have\r\n\\[\\psi(x,y)=(\\phi\\circ f)(x,y)=\\phi(u(x,y),v(x,y))\\]\r\nFrom the chain rule, we get\r\n\\[\\psi_x=\\phi_uu_x+\\phi_vv_x,&nbsp;&nbsp;\\psi_y=\\phi_uu_y+\\phi_vv_y\\]\r\nContinuing with the product and chain rules\r\n\\[\\psi_{xx}=\\phi_uu_{xx}+\\phi_vv_{xx}+\\phi_{uu}u_x^2+2\\phi_{uv}u_xv_x+\\phi_{vv}v_x^2\\]\r\n\\[\\psi_{yy}=\\phi_uu_{yy}+\\phi_vv_{yy}+\\phi_{uu}u_y^2+2\\phi_{uv}u_yv_y+\\phi_{vv}v_y^2\\]\r\nSo finally\r\n\\[\\psi_{xx}+\\phi_{yy}=\\phi_u(u_{xx}+u_{yy})+\\phi_v(v_{xx}+v_{yy})+2\\phi_{uv}(u_xv_x+u_yv_y)\\]\r\n\\[+\\phi_{uu}(u_x^2+u_y^2)+\\phi_{vv}(v_x^2+v_y^2)\\]\r\nWhich by the Cauchy-Riemann equations,\r\n\\[=(\\phi_{uu}+\\phi_{vv})|f\'(z)|^2=0\\]',319),(152,'','Suppose \\(f:U\\to V\\) is a conformal equivalence, then \\(f^{-1}:V\\to U\\) is also. Suppose \\(\\phi\\in H(U),\\psi\\in H(V)\\). We can set up the maps \\(\\phi\\in H(U)\\to\\phi\\circ f^{-1}\\in H(V)\\) and \\(\\psi\\in H(V)\\to\\psi\\circ f\\in H(U)\\) and these are clearly linear and inverses of each other.',320),(153,'','<ol>\r\n<li>\r\nLet \\(z\\not\\in\\bar B(a,\\epsilon)\\), then \\(|z-a|\\gt\\epsilon\\), so \\(\\delta={|z-a|-\\epsilon\\over2}\\gt0\\). Then let \\(w\\) be s.t. \\(|z-w|\\lt\\delta\\), then \\(|w-a|\\gt|z-a|-|z-w|\\gt\\epsilon\\). So \\(B(w,\\delta\\)\\cap\\B(a,\\epsilon)=\\emptyset\\), so \\(B(z,\\epsilon)\\) is closed.\r\n<br/><br/><br/>\r\n</li>\r\n<li>\r\nLet \\(C_1,...,C_n\\) be closed sets, then \\(U_i=\\mathbb C\\setminus C_i\\) is an open set for all \\(i\\). Then the finite intersection of \\(U_i\\) is open, so by the law\r\n\\[\\bigcup_iC_i=\\mathbb C\\setminus(\\bigcap_i(\\mathbb C\\setminus C_i))\\]\r\n\\(\\bigcup_iC_i\\) is closed.\r\n<br/><br/><br/>\r\n</li>\r\n<li>\r\nLet \\(C_1,C_2,...\\) be closed sets, then \\(U_i=\\mathbb C\\setminus C_i\\) is an open set for all \\(i\\). Then the arbitrary union of \\(U_i\\) is open, so by the law\r\n\\[\\bigcap_iC_i=\\mathbb C\\setminus(\\bigcup_i(\\mathbb C\\setminus C_i))\\]\r\n\\(\\bigcap_iC_i\\) is closed.\r\n</li>\r\n</ol>',323),(154,'','Suppose \\(z\\in(S\\cup S\')\'\\), then\r\n\\[\\forall\\epsilon\\gt0,\\exists w\\in S\\cup S\'&nbsp;s.t.&nbsp;|z-w|\\lt\\epsilon\\]\r\nEither \\(w\\in S\\) or \\(w\\in S\'\\), suppose \\(w\\in S\'\\).<br/>\r\nThen \\(\\exists v\\in S&nbsp;s.t.&nbsp;|v-w|\\lt{\\epsilon-|z-w|\\over2}\\) as \\(w\\) is a limit point of \\(S\\). So\r\n\\[|z-w|\\lt|z-w|+|w-v|\\lt{\\epsilon+|z-w|\\over2}\\lt\\epsilon\\]\r\nSo \\(z\\in S\'\\), so \\((S\\cup S\')\'\\subset S\'\\subset S\\cup S\'\\)<br/>\r\nTherefore \\(S\\cup S\'\\) is closed as it contains all of its limit points.<br/>\r\n<br/><br/>\r\nSuppose \\(S\\subset A\\) where \\(A\\) is closed. \\(A\\) contains its limit points so \\(S\'\\subset A\\), so \\(A\\subset S\\cup S\'\\).<br/>\r\nTherefore \\(S\\cup S\'\\) is the smallest such set.',324),(155,'','Suppose \\(v\\) is a harmonic conjugate of \\(u\\), then \\(f=u+iv\\) is holomorphic, so it satisfies the Cauchy-Riemann equations. So \\(u_x=v_y\\) and \\(u_y=-v_x\\).<br/>\r\nLet \\(g=-v+iu\\), note that this still satisfies the Cauchy-Riemann equations and is continuous, so by Goursat it is holormorphic.<br/>\r\nTherefore \\(u\\) is a harmonic conjugate of \\(-v\\)<br/>\r\nThe rest of the argument is by symetry.',327),(156,'','Suppose \\(f=u+iv\\) and \\(g=u+iw\\) are holomorphic, where \\(u,v,w:U\\to\\mathbb R\\) are harmonic.<br/>\r\nBy the Cauchy-Riemann equations,\r\n\\[u_x=v_u=w_y\\]\r\n\\[u_y=-v_x=-w_x\\]\r\nIt follows that \\(v,w\\) are identical up to a constant.',328),(157,'','Suppose that the \\(f_i\\) are all holormorphic on some domain \\(U\\)<br/>\r\nWe know that a uniform limit preserves continuity, so \\(f\\) is continuous on \\(U\\).<br/>\r\nNow consider \\(\\gamma\\), a closed path in \\(U\\). Then\r\n\\[\\int_\\gamma f(z)dz=\\int_\\gamma\\lim_{n\\to\\infty}f_n(z)dz=\\lim_{n\\to\\infty}\\int_\\gamma f_n(z)dz=0\\]\r\nas all the \\(f_n\\) are holomorphic so Cauchy\'s theorem applies. Then by Morera\'s theorem, \\(f\\) is holomorphic on \\(U\\)',266),(158,'','All we need to prove is that \\(\\sin\\theta\\over\\theta\\) decreases as \\(\\theta\\) increases for \\(\\theta\\in(0,{1\\over2}\\pi]\\). This is the case if\r\n\\[{d\\over d\\theta}({sin\\theta\\over\\theta})\\leq0&nbsp;for&nbsp;0\\lt\\theta\\leq{1\\over2}\\pi\\]\r\nBut\r\n\\[{d\\over d\\theta}({sin\\theta\\over\\theta})={\\theta cos\\theta-sin\\theta\\over\\theta^2}\\leq0&nbsp;whenever&nbsp;\\theta cos\\theta-sin\\theta\\leq0\\]\r\nSince \\([\\theta cos\\theta-sin\\theta]_{\\theta=0}=0\\), it is now enough to note that, on \\((0,{1\\over2}\\pi]\\), the function \\(\\theta cos\\theta-sin\\theta\\) has a non-positive derivative and so decreases as \\(\\theta\\) increases.',330),(159,'Proof using DFAs','Let \\(M_1=(Q_1,\\Sigma,\\delta_1,q_1,F_1)\\) recognize \\(A_1\\), and \\(M_2=(Q_2,\\Sigma,\\delta_2,q_2,F_2)\\) recognize \\(A_2\\).<br/>\r\nConstruct \\(M=(Q,\\Sigma,\\delta,q_0,F)\\) to recognize \\(A_1\\cup A_2\\):\r\n<ul>\r\n<li>\\(Q=Q_1\\times Q_2=\\{(r_1,r_2):r_1\\in Q_1,r_2\\in Q_2\\}\\)</li>\r\n<li>\\(\\delta((r_1,r_2),a)=(\\delta_1(r_1,a),\\delta_2(r_2,a))\\)</li>\r\n<li>\\(q_0=(q_1,q_2)\\)</li>\r\n<li>\\(F=(F_1\\times Q_2)\\cup(Q_2\\times F_2)=\\{(r_1,r_2):r_1\\in F_1 or r_2\\in F_2\\}\\)</li>\r\n</ul>\r\n<br/><br/><br/><br/>\r\nWe first show that \\(L(M)\\subset L(M_1)\\cup L(M_2)\\):<br/>\r\nTake \\(w=a_1...a_n\\in L(M)\\). By definition, for some \\(q_1=q_0^1,q_1^1,...,q_n^1\\in Q_1\\), and some \\(q_2=q_0^2,q_1^2,...,q_n^2\\in Q_2\\), we have \\(M\\)-transitions\r\n\\[(q_0^1,q_0^2)\\to_{a_1}(q_1^1,q_1^2)\\to_{a_2}...\\to_{a_n}(q_n^1,q_n^2)\\]\r\nwhere \\(q_n^1\\in F_1\\) or \\(q_n^2\\in F_2\\). Without loss of generality suppose the former. Unpacking the above we have \\(M_1\\)-transition\r\n\\[q_0^1\\to_{a_1}q_1^1\\to_{a_2}...\\to_{a_n}q_n^1\\]\r\nHence \\(w\\in L(M_1)\\subset L(M_1)\\cup L(M_2)\\)<br/>\r\n<br/><br/><br/><br/>\r\nNext we show that \\(L(M_1)\\subset L(M)\\): (the argument for \\(L(M_2)\\) is identical)<br/>\r\nTake \\(w=a_1...a_n\\in L(M_1)\\). By definition, for some \\(q_1=q_0^1,q_1^1,...,q_n^1\\in Q_1\\), with \\(q_n^1\\in F_1\\), we have\r\n\\[q_0^1\\to_{a_1}q_1^1\\to_{a_2}...\\to_{a_n}q_n^1\\]\r\nNow since \\(\\delta_2\\) is a function, for any \\(q\\in Q_2\\), \\(a\\in\\Sigma\\), there is a \\(q\'\\) s.t. \\(q\\to_aq\'\\).<br/>\r\nHence there are \\(q_2=q_0^2,q_1^2,...,q_n^2\\in Q_2\\) s.t.\r\n\\[(q_0^1,q_0^2)\\to_{a_1}(q_1^1,q_1^2)\\to_{a_2}...\\to_{a_n}(q_n^1,q_n^2)\\]\r\nare \\(M\\)-transitions. Since \\((q_n^1,q_n^2)\\in F_1\\times Q_2\\subset F\\), we have \\(w\\in L(M)\\)',335),(160,'','The right hand direction is trivial, every DFA is clearly an NFA.<br/>\r\n<br/>\r\n<br/>\r\nFor the left hand direction, fix an NFA \\(N=(Q_N,\\Sigma_N,\\delta_N,q_N,F_N)\\), we construct an equivalent DFA \\(D=(Q_D,\\Sigma_D,\\delta_D,q_D,F_D)\\):\r\n<ul>\r\n<li>\\(Q_D=\\{S:S\\subset Q_N\\}\\)</li>\r\n<li>\\(\\Sigma_D=\\Sigma_N\\)</li>\r\n<li>\\(S\\to_aS\'\\) in \\(D\\) iff \\(S\'=\\{q\':\\exists q\\in S&nbsp;s.t.&nbsp;q\\to_aq\'&nbsp;in&nbsp;N\\}\\)</li>\r\n<li>\\(q_D=\\{q:q_n\\to_\\epsilon q\\}\\)</li>\r\n<li>\\(F_D=\\{S\\in S_D:F_N\\cap S\\neq\\emptyset\\}\\)</li>\r\n</ul>\r\n<br/><Br/><br/><Br/>\r\nProof that \\(L(N)\\subset L(D)\\)<br/>\r\nSuppose \\(\\epsilon\\in L(N)\\), then \\(q_N\\to_\\epsilon q\'\\) for some \\(q\'\\in F_N\\). Hence \\(q\'\\in q_D\\), and so \\(q_D=\\{q\'\':q_N\\to_\\epsilon q\'\'\\}\\in F_D\\) i.e. \\(\\epsilon\\in L(D)\\).<br/>\r\n<br/>\r\nNow take any non-empty \\(u=a_1...a_n\\in L(N)\\), then there is a sequence of \\(N\\)-transitions\r\n\\[q_N\\to_{a_1}q_1\\to_{a_2}...\\to_{a_n}q_n\\in F_N\\]\r\nSince \\(D\\) is deterministic, feeding \\(u\\) into it results in the sequence of \\(D\\) transitions\r\n\\[q_D\\to_{a_1}S_1\\to_{a_2}...\\to_{a_n}S_n\\]\r\nwhere\r\n\\[S_1=\\{q\':\\exists q\\in q_D&nbsp;s.t.&nbsp;q\\to_{a_1}q\'&nbsp;in&nbsp;N\\}\\]\r\n\\[S_2=\\{q\':\\exists q\\in S_1&nbsp;s.t.&nbsp;q\\to_{a_2}q\'&nbsp;in&nbsp;N\\}\\]\r\n\\[...\\]\r\n\\[S_n=\\{q\':\\exists q\\in S_{n-1}&nbsp;s.t.&nbsp;q\\to_{a_n}q\'&nbsp;in&nbsp;N\\}\\]\r\nBy definition of \\(\\delta_D\\), so we have \\(q_1\\in S_1\\), \\(q_2\\in S_2\\) and so \\(q_n\\in S_n\\). Hence \\(S_N\\in F_D\\) because \\(q_n\\in F_N\\). Thus \\(u\\in L(D)\\).\r\n<br/><Br/><br/><Br/>\r\nProof that \\(L(D)\\subset L(N)\\)<br/>\r\nSuppose \\(\\epsilon\\in L(D)\\), then \\(q_D\\in F_D\\) i.e. \\(F_N\\cap\\{q:q_N\\to_\\epsilon q\\}\\neq\\emptyset\\), or equivalently for some \\(q\'\\in F_N\\), \\(q_N\\to_\\epsilon q\'\\). Hence \\(\\epsilon\\in L(N)\\)<br/>\r\n<Br/>\r\nNow suppose some non-empty \\(u=a_1...a_n\\in L(D)\\), i.e. there is a sequence of \\(D\\)-transitions\r\n\\[q_D\\to_{a_1}S_1\\to_{a_2}...\\to_{a_n}S_n\\]\r\nwith \\(S_n\\in F_D\\), so \\(q_n\\in F_N\\). Now since \\(q_n\\in S_n\\), by definition of \\(\\delta_D\\) there is some \\(q_{n-1}\\in S_{n-1}\\) with \\(q_{n-1}\\to_{a_n}q_n\\) in \\(N\\). Working backwards in this way we can build up a sequence of \\(N\\)-transitions until we deduce that \\(q_N\\to_uq_n\\). Thus \\(u\\in L(N)\\)',339),(161,'Proof using NFAs','Given NFAs \\(N_1=(Q_1,\\Sigma,\\delta_1,q_1,F_1)\\) and \\(N_2=(Q_2,\\Sigma,\\delta_2,q_2,F_2)\\), we define \\(N=(Q,\\Sigma,\\delta,q,F)\\) by\r\n<ul>\r\n<li>\\(Q=(Q_1\\times\\{1\\})\\cup(Q_2\\times\\{2\\})\\cup\\{q\\}\\)</li>\r\n<li>\\(F=(F_1\\times\\{1\\})\\cup(F_2\\times\\{2\\})\\)</li>\r\n<li>\\(\\delta(q,\\epsilon)=\\{(q_1,1),(q_2,2)\\}\\)</li>\r\n<li>\\(\\delta((r,1),a)=\\{(r\',1):r\'\\in\\delta_1(r,a)\\}\\)</li>\r\n<li>\\(\\delta((r,2),a)=\\{(r\',2):r\'\\in\\delta_2(r,a)\\}\\)</li>\r\n</ul>\r\n<br/><br/><br/><br/>\r\nProof that \\(L(N_1)\\cup L(N_2)\\subset L(N)\\)<br/>\r\nSuppose \\(w=a_1...a_n\\in L(N_1)\\), then there exist \\(r_1,...,r_n\\in Q_1\\) such that\r\n\\[q_1\\to_{a_1}r_1\\to_{a_2}...\\to_{a_n}r_n\\]\r\nwith \\(r_n\\in F_1\\). Then in \\(N\\) we have the sequence\r\n\\[q\\to_\\epsilon(q_1,1)\\to_{a_1}(r_1,1)\\to_{a_2}...\\to_{a_n}(r_n,1)\\]\r\nwith \\((r_n,1)\\in F\\). Hence \\(w\\in L(N)\\).<br/>\r\nSimilarly \\(w\\in L(N_2\\)\\Rightarrow w\\in L(N)\\).\r\n<br/><br/><br/><br/>\r\nProof that \\(L(N)\\subset L(N_1)\\cup L(N_2)\\)<br/>\r\nSuppose \\(w=a_1...a_n\\in L(N)\\), then there exist \\(i\\in\\{1,2\\}\\) and \\(r_1,...,r_n\\in Q_i\\) such that\r\n\\[q\\to_\\epsilon(q_i,i)\\to_{a_1}(r_1,i)\\to_{a_2}...\\to_{a_n}(r_n,i)\\]\r\nwith \\((r_n,i)\\in F\\). But then, in \\(N_i\\) we have the sequence\r\n\\[q_i\\to_{a_1}r_1\\to_{a_2}...\\to_{a_n}r_n\\]\r\nwith \\(r_n\\in F_i\\). Hence \\(w\\in L(N_i)\\)',335),(162,'','Let \\(N_1=(Q_1,\\Sigma,\\delta_1,q_1,F_1)\\) and \\(N_2=(Q_2,\\Sigma,\\delta_2,q_2,F_2)\\) be NFAs. We want to construct an NFA that starts in the start state of \\(N_1\\), however whenever it enters an accept state of \\(N_1\\), it both carries on and takes an \\(\\epsilon\\) transition to the start state of \\(N_2\\). It then accepts iff it ends up in an accept state in \\(N_2\\).<br/>\r\nSo define \\(N=(Q,\\Sigma,\\delta,(q_1,1),F)\\) where:\r\n<ul>\r\n<li>\\(Q=(Q_1\\times\\{1\\})\\cup(Q_2\\times\\{2\\})\\)</li>\r\n<li>\\(F=F_2\\times\\{2\\}\\)</li>\r\n<li>\\(\\delta((r,1),a)=\\{(r\',1):r\'\\in\\delta_1(r,a)\\}\\) for \\(a\\neq\\epsilon\\) or \\(r\\not\\in F_1\\)</li>\r\n<li>\\(\\delta((r,1),\\epsilon)=\\{(r\',1):r\'\\in\\delta_1(r,\\epsilon)\\}\\cup\\{(q_2,2)\\}\\) for \\(r\\in F_1\\)</li>\r\n<li>\\(\\delta((r,2),a)=\\{(r\',2):r\'\\in\\delta_2(r,a)\\}\\)</li>\r\n</ul>\r\n<br/><br/><br/><br/>\r\nProof that \\(L(N_1)/cdot L(N_2)\\subset L(N)\\)<br/>\r\nSuppose \\(w\\in L(N_1)\\cdot L(N_2)\\), then there exist \\(u=a_1...a_n\\in L(N_1)\\) and \\(v=b1...b_m\\in L(N_2)\\) with \\(w=uv\\).<br/>\r\nTherefore there exist \\(r_1,...,r_n\\in Q_1\\) with \\(r_n\\in F_1\\) such that, in \\(N_1\\)\r\n\\[q_1\\to_{a_1}r_1\\to_{a_2}...\\to_{a_n}r_n\\]\r\nand \\(s_1,...,s_m\\in Q_2\\) with \\(s_m\\in F_2\\) such that, in \\(N_2\\)\r\n\\[q_2\\to_{b_1}s_1\\to_{b_2}...\\to_{b_m}s_m\\]\r\nThen in \\(N\\) we have the sequence\r\n\\[(q_1,1)\\to_{a_1}(r_1,1)\\to_{a_2}...\\to_{a_n}(r_n,1)\\to_\\epsilon\\]\r\n\\[(q_2,2)\\to_{b_1}(s_1,2)\\to_{b_2}...\\to_{b_m}(s_m,2)\\]\r\nwith \\((s_m,2)\\in F\\). Hence \\(w\\in L(N)\\)\r\n<br/><br/><br/><br/>\r\nProof that \\(L(N)\\subset L(N_1)/cdot L(N_2)\\)<br/>\r\nSuppose \\(w=a_1...a_k\\in L(N)\\), then there exist \\(r_1,...,r_k\\in Q\\) such that\r\n\\[(q_1,1)\\to_{a_1}r_1\\to_{a_2}...\\to_{a_k}r_k\\]\r\nwith \\(r_k\\in F\\). By definition of \\(F\\) there is an \\(s_k\\in F_2\\) such that \\(r_k=(s_k,2)\\).<br/>\r\nThe definition of \\(\\delta\\) implies that there is exactly one \\(\\epsilon\\)-transition to get from the first to the second component, i.e. there are states \\(s_1,...,s_n\\in Q_1\\) and \\(s_{n+1},...,s_{k-1}\\in Q_2\\) such that\r\n\\[(q_1,1)\\to_{a_1}(s_1,1)\\to_{a_2}...\\to_{a_n}(s_n,1)\\to_\\epsilon\\]\r\n\\[(q_2,2)\\to_{a_{n+1}}(s_{n+1},2)\\to_{a_{n+2}}...\\to_{a_k}(s_k,2)\\]\r\nThen, in \\(N_1\\) we have the sequence \\(q_1\\to_{a_1}s_1\\to_{a_2}...\\to_{a_n}s_n\\) with \\(s_n\\in F_1\\) and in \\(N_2\\) we have the sequence \\(q_2\\to_{a_{n+1}}s_{n+1}\\to_{a_{n+2}}...\\to_{a_k}s_k\\) with \\(s_k\\in F_2\\).<br/>\r\nHence \\(u=a_1...a_n\\in L(N_1)\\) and \\(v=a_{n+1}...a_k\\in L(N_2)\\) and therefore \\(w=uv\\in L(N_1)\\cdot L(N_2)\\)',340),(163,'','Let \\(N_1=(Q_1,\\Sigma,\\delta_1,q_1,F_1)\\) and \\(N_2=(Q_2,\\Sigma,\\delta_2,q_2,F_2)\\) be NFAs. We want to construct an NFA that starts in the start state of \\(N_1\\), however whenever it enters an accept state of \\(N_1\\), it both carries on and takes an \\(\\epsilon\\) transition back to the start state of \\(N_1\\). It then accepts iff it ends up in an accept state in \\(N_1\\) or at the start of \\(N_1\\).<br/>\r\nSo define \\(N=(Q_1\\cup\\{q_0\\},\\Sigma,\\delta,q_0,F_1\\cup\\{q_0\\})\\) where:\r\n\\[\\delta(q,a)=\r\n\\left\\{\r\n  \\begin{array}{lllll}\r\n    \\delta_1(q,a) & \\mbox{if } q\\in Q_1 and q\\not\\in F_1\\\\\r\n    \\delta_1(q,a) & \\mbox{if } q\\in F_1 and a\\neq\\epsilon\\\\\r\n    \\delta_1(q,a)\\cup\\{q_1\\} & \\mbox{if } q\\in F_1  and a=\\epsilon\\\\\r\n    \\{q_1\\} & \\mbox{if } q=q_0 and a=\\epsilon\\\\\r\n    \\emptyset & \\mbox{if } q=q_0 and a\\neq\\epsilon\r\n  \\end{array}\r\n\\right.\\]\r\n<br/><br/><br/><Br/>\r\nProof that \\(L(N_1)^*\\subset L(N)\\)<br/>\r\nObviously \\(\\epsilon\\in L(N)\\) because \\(q_0\\in F\\).<br/>\r\nSuppose some non-empty \\(q\\in L(N_1)^*\\), then there exist \\(k\\geq1\\) and \\(v_1,...,v_k\\) such that \\(w=v_1...v_k\\) and \\(v_i=a_{i1}...a_{in_i}\\in L(N_1)\\) for each \\(i\\). Then for each \\(i\\) there exist \\(r_{i1},...,r_{in_i}\\in Q_1\\) such that\r\n\\[q_1\\to_{a_{i1}}r_{i1}\\to_{a_{i2}}...\\to_{a_{in_i}}r_{in_i}\\]\r\nwith \\(r_{in_i}\\in F_1\\). Then in \\(N\\) we have the sequence\r\n\\[q_0\\to_\\epsilon q_1\\to_{a_{11}}r_{11}\\to_{a_{12}}...\\to_{a_{1n_1}}r_{1n_1}\\to_\\epsilon q_1\\to_{a_{21}}...\\to_{a_{kn_k}}r_{kn_k}\\]\r\nwith \\(r_{kn_k}\\in F\\). Hence \\(w\\in L(N)\\)\r\n<br/><br/><br/><Br/>\r\nProof that \\(L(N)\\subset L(N_1)^*\\)<br/>\r\nIf \\(w=\\epsilon\\), \\(w\\in L(N_1)^*\\) by definition of star.<br/>\r\nSuppose \\(w=a_1...a_n\\in L(N)\\), then there exist \\(r_1,...,r_n\\in Q\\) such that\r\n\\[q\\to_\\epsilon q_1\\to_{a_1}r_1\\to_{a_2}...\\to_{a_n}r_n\\]\r\nwith \\(r_N\\in F\\).<br/>\r\nLet \\(k-1\\) be the number of occurrences of the \"new\" \\(\\epsilon\\)-transitions \\(r_j\\to_\\epsilon q_1\\) with \\(r_j\\in F_1\\). If we split the transition sequence at these transitions, we get \\(k\\) transition sequences \\(q_1\\to_{v_i}r_i\\) such that \\(w=v_1...v_k\\) and for each \\(i\\), \\(v_i\\in L(N_1)\\).<br/>\r\nHence \\(w=v_1...v_k\\in L(N_1)^*\\)',341),(164,'','\\((\\Leftarrow)\\)<br/>\r\nWe will show that there is a systematic way to transform a regular expression \\(E\\) to an equivalent NFA \\(N_E\\) by recursion on the structure of \\(E\\).<br/>\r\n<br/>\r\n<b>Base cases:</b> For each of the three cases, namely \\(E=\\epsilon,\\emptyset\\) and \\(a\\) where \\(a\\in\\Sigma\\), there is an NFA \\(N_E\\) that accepts \\(L(E)\\).<br/>\r\n<br/>\r\n<b>Inductive cases:</b> Take regular expressions \\(E\\) and \\(F\\). Suppose \\(N_E\\) and \\(N_F\\) are NFAs that accept \\(L(E)\\) and \\(L(F)\\) respectively. We have proved that regular expressions are closed under union, concatenation and star by constructing NFAs that accept \\(L(N_E)\\cup L(N_F)\\), \\(L(N_E)\\cdot L(N_F)\\) and \\((L(N_E))^*\\) respectively. By definition, these NFAs are equivalent to \\(E+F\\), \\(E\\cdot F\\) and \\(E^*\\) respectively.\r\n<br/><br/><br/><br/>\r\n\\((\\Rightarrow)\\)<br/>\r\nGiven an NFA \\(M=(Q,\\Sigma,\\delta,q_0,F)\\), for \\(X\\subset Q\\) and \\(q,q\'\\in Q\\), we construct by induction on the size of \\(X\\), a regular expression \\(E^X_{q,q\'}\\) whose denotation is the set of all strings \\(w\\) such that there is a path from \\(q\\) to \\(q\'\\) in \\(M\\) labelled by \\(w\\) (i.e. \\(q\\to_wq\'\\)) such that all intermediate states along that path lie in \\(X\\).<br/>\r\nIf suffices to prove that for any \\(X\\subset Q\\), for any \\(q,q\'\\in Q\\), there is a regular expression \\(E^X_{q,q\'}\\) satisfying \\(L(E^X_{q,q\'})=\\{w\\in\\Sigma^*:q\\to_wq\'\\) in \\(M\\) with all intermediate states of sequence in \\(X\\}\\)<br/>\r\nWe will prove this by induction on the size of \\(X\\):<br/>\r\n<br/>\r\n<b>Basis:</b> \\(X=\\emptyset\\). Let \\(a_1,...,a_k\\) be all the symbols in \\(\\Sigma\\cup\\{\\epsilon\\}\\) such that \\(q\'\\in\\delta(q,a_i)\\). For \\(q\\neq q\'\\), take\r\n\\[E^\\emptyset_{q,q\'}=\r\n\\left\\{\r\n  \\begin{array}{ll}\r\n    a_1+...+a_k & \\mbox{if } k\\geq1\\\\\r\n    \\emptyset & \\mbox{if } k=0\r\n  \\end{array}\r\n\\right.\\]\r\nand for \\(q=q\'\\), take\r\n\\[E^\\emptyset_{q,q\'}=\r\n\\left\\{\r\n  \\begin{array}{ll}\r\n    a_1+...+a_k+\\epsilon & \\mbox{if } k\\geq1\\\\\r\n    \\epsilon & \\mbox{if } k=0\r\n  \\end{array}\r\n\\right.\\]\r\n<br/><br/>\r\n<b>Inductive step:</b> For a non-empty \\(X\\), choose an element \\(r\\in X\\), call it the separating state. Now any path from \\(q\\) to \\(q\'\\) with all intermediate states in \\(X\\), either\r\n<ol>\r\n<li>never visits \\(r\\), or</li>\r\n<li>visits \\(r\\) for the first time, followed by a finite number of loops from \\(r\\) back to itself without visiting \\(r\\) in between but staying in \\(X\\), and finally followed by a path from \\(r\\) to \\(q\'\\)</li>\r\n</ol>\r\nThus we take\r\n\\[E^X_{q,q\'}=E^{X-\\{r\\}}_{q,q\'}+E^{X-\\{r\\}}_{q,r}\\cdot(E^{X-\\{r\\}}_{r,r})^*\\cdot E^{X-\\{r\\}}_{r,q\'}\\]\r\nFinally the expression \\(\\Sigma_{f\\in F}E^Q_{q_0,f}\\) has denotation \\(L(M)\\)',344),(165,'','Let \\(M=(Q,\\Sigma,\\delta,q_{init},F)\\) be a DFA that accepts \\(A\\) and let \\(p=|Q|\\).<br/>\r\nSuppose \\(s=a_1...a_n\\in L(M)\\) where \\(n\\geq p\\), we have\r\n\\[q_0\\to_{a_1}q_1\\to_{a_2}...\\to_{a_p}q_p\\to_{a_{p+1}}...\\to_{a_n}q_n\\in F\\]\r\nwhere \\(q_0=q_{init}\\). By the pigeonhole principle, \\(q_0,...,q_p\\) cannot all be distinct. So \\(q_j = q_{j\'}\\) for some \\(0\\leq j\\lt j\'\\leq p\\). Thus the above transition sequence is\r\n\\[q_0\\to_x^*q_j\\to_y^*q_{j\'}\\to_z^*q_n\\in F\\]\r\nwhere \\(x=a_1...a_j\\), \\(y=a_{j+1}...a_{j\'}\\) and \\(z=a_{j\'+1}...a_n\\). We have \\(|xy|\\leq p\\) and \\(|y|\\gt0\\) and for every \\(i\\geq0\\), \\(xy^iz\\in L(M)\\) as\r\n\\[q_j\\to_y^*q_j\\]',345),(166,'','All follows from \"if and only if\" being an equivalence relation.',347),(167,'','It suffices to prove:\r\n<ol>\r\n<li><b>If \\(L\\) is accepted by a DFA with \\(k\\) states, then \\(L\\) has index at most \\(k\\)</b><br/>\r\n<br/>\r\nSuppose \\(L\\) is accepted by a DFA \\(M=(Q,\\Sigma,\\delta,q_0,F)\\). We check that\r\n\\[\\hat\\delta(q_0,x)=\\hat\\delta(q_0,y)\\Rightarrow x\\equiv_Ly\\]\r\n(Recall: for \\(x\\in\\Sigma^*\\), we have \\(\\hat\\delta(q,x)=q\'\\) iff \\(q\\to_x^*q\'\\).)<br/>\r\nTake \\(x_1,...,x_{k+1}\\in\\Sigma^*\\), all distinct. Since \\(M\\) has only \\(k\\) states, by the pigeonhole principle, for some \\(1\\leq i\\lt j\\leq k+1\\), we have \\(\\hat\\delta(q_0,x_i)=\\hat\\delta(q_0,x_j)\\) and so \\(x_i\\equiv_Lx_j\\). It follows that \\(\\equiv_L\\) has at most \\(k\\) equivalence classes.<br/>\r\n<br/><br/><br/>\r\n</li>\r\n<li><b>If \\(L\\) has finite index \\(k\\), then it is accepted by a DFA with \\(k\\) states</b><br/>\r\n<br/>\r\nAssume that \\(L\\) has a finite index. Define a structure \\(M=(\\Sigma,Q,q_0,\\delta,F)\\) as follows\r\n\\[Q=\\{[x]:x\\in\\Sigma^*\\}\\]\r\n\\[q_0=[\\epsilon]\\]\r\n\\[\\delta([x],a)=[xa]\\]\r\n\\[F=\\{[w]:w\\in L\\}\\]\r\nWe need to verify that \\(M\\) is a DFA and that \\(M\\) accepts \\(L\\)<br/>\r\nWell, \\(|Q|\\) is the index of \\(L\\) which is finite, and \\(\\delta\\) is a well-defined function because \\(x\\equiv_Ly\\) implies \\(xa\\equiv_lya\\) for any \\(a\\in\\Sigma\\). So \\(M\\) is a DFA.<br/>\r\nThen, for any \\(w\\in\\Sigma^*\\), \\(w\\in L(M)\\) iff \\([\\epsilon]\\to_w^*[w]\\in F\\) iff \\(w\\in L\\). So \\(M\\) accepts \\(L\\)<br/>\r\n<br/>\r\nSo, we have a DFA with \\(k\\) states that accepts \\(L\\).\r\n</li>\r\n</ol>',348),(168,'','Any rule of the form \\(R\\to wT\\) where \\(w=w_1...w_n\\) is equivalent to having all the rules\r\n\\[R\\to T_1\\]\r\n\\[T_i\\to w_iT_{i+1} for 1\\leq i\\lt n\\]\r\n\\[T_n\\to w_nT\\]',354),(169,'','\\((\\Rightarrow)\\)<br/>\r\nWe map a DFA \\(M=(Q,\\Sigma,\\delta,q_0,F)\\) to a strongly right-linear CFG \\(G_M=(Q,\\Sigma,R,q_0)\\) where\r\n\\[q\\to aq\'\\in R\\Leftrightarrow\\delta(q,a)=q\'\\]\r\n\\[q\\to\\epsilon\\in R\\Leftrightarrow q\\in F\\]\r\n<br/><br/>\r\n\\((\\Leftarrow)\\)<br/>\r\nWe map a strongly right-linear CFG \\(G=(V,\\Sigma,R,S)\\) to an NFA \\(N_G=(V,\\Sigma,\\delta,S,F)\\) where\r\n\\[Q\'\\in\\delta(Q,a)\\Leftrightarrow Q\\to aQ\'\\in R\\]\r\n\\[Q\'\\in\\delta(Q,\\epsilon)\\Leftrightarrow Q\\to Q\'\\in R\\]\r\n\\[Q\\in F\\Leftrightarrow Q\\to\\epsilon\\in R\\]',353),(170,'','Proof idea: \\(A=\\{ww:w\\in\\{0,1\\}^*\\}\\) is not context free, but its complement \\(B=\\{0,1\\}^*\\setminus A\\) is context free, as it is generated by the gammar\r\n\\[G=(\\{S,A,B,C\\},\\{0,1\\},R,S)\\]\r\nwith rule set\r\n\\[R=\\{S\\to AB|BA|A|B, A\\to CAC|0, B\\to CBC|1, C\\to 0|1\\}\\]\r\nThis grammar generates all strings of odd length starting with productions \\(S\\to A|B\\) or strings of the form \\(x0yu1v\\) or \\(u1vx0y\\) where \\(x,y,u,v\\in\\{0,1\\}^*\\), \\(|x|=|y|\\) and \\(|u|=|v|\\). None of these strings can be of the form \\(ww\\).',359),(171,'','We are breaking down the proof into the following steps\r\n<ol>\r\n<li><b>Given a CFG \\(G\\), there is an equivalent NPDA \\(P_G\\)</b><br/>\r\n<br/>\r\nThe stack alphabet of \\(P_G\\) consists of the terminal and variable symbols and \\(\\perp\\). We describe the action of \\(P_G\\) informally:\r\n<ol>\r\n<li>Place the start variable symbol on the stack.</li>\r\n<li>Repeat forever: Pop top-of-stack \\(x\\), cases of:\r\n<ol>\r\n<li>\\(x\\) is a variable \\(A\\): Nondeterministically select a rule for \\(A\\) and replace \\(A\\) by the string \\(w\\) on the rhs of the rule with the leftmost symbol of \\(w\\) being top of the stack.</li>\r\n<li>\\(x\\) is a terminal \\(a\\): Read the next input symbol and compare it with \\(a\\), if the do not match then exit the branch of nondeterminism.</li>\r\n<li>\\(x=\\perp\\): Enter the accept state.</li>\r\n</ol>\r\nClaim that \\(P_G\\) accepts \\(L(G)\\)\r\n</li>\r\n</ol>\r\n<br/><br/><br/>\r\n</li>\r\n<li><b>Given an NPDA \\(N\\), there is an equivalent CFG \\(G_N\\) generating \\(L(N)\\)</b><br/>\r\n<ol>\r\n<li><b>Every NPDA can be simulated by an NPDA with one state</b><br/>\r\n<br/>\r\nWe need to maintain all state information on the stack. W.L.O.G. assume \\(M\\) is of the form \\((Q,\\Sigma,\\Gamma,\\delta,s,\\perp,\\{t\\})\\) and \\(M\\) can empty its stack after entering the final state \\(t\\).<br/>\r\nSet \\(\\Gamma\'=Q\\times\\Gamma\\times Q\\) (elements written \\(\\langle p,A,q\\rangle\\)). We construct a new NPDA\r\n\\[M\'=(\\{*\\},\\Sigma,\\Gamma\',\\delta\',*,\\langle s,\\perp,t\\rangle,\\emptyset)\\]\r\nthat accepts by empty stack. For each transition\r\n\\[(q_0,B_1...B_k)\\in\\delta(p,c,A)\\]\r\nwhere \\(c\\in\\Sigma\\cup\\{\\epsilon\\}\\), include in \\(\\delta\'\\) the transition\r\n\\[(*,\\langle q_0,B_1,q_1\\rangle\\langle q_1,B_2,q_2\\rangle...\\langle q_{k-1},B_k,q_k\\rangle)\\in\\delta\'(*,c,\\langle p,A,q_k\\rangle)\\]\r\nfor all possible choices of \\(q_1,...,q_k\\)<br/>\r\n<br/>\r\nIntuitively \\(M\'\\) simulates \\(M\\), guessing nondeterministically what state \\(M\\) will be in at certain future points in the computation, saving those guesses on the stack and then verifying that the guesses were correct.<br/>\r\n<br/>\r\nNow, \\(M\'\\) can scan a string \\(x\\) staring with only \\(\\langle p,A,q\\rangle\\) on its stack and end up with an empty stack, if and only if \\(M\\) can scan a string \\(x\\) starting in state \\(p\\) with only \\(A\\) on its stack and end up in state \\(q\\) with an empty stack. So\r\n\\[(p,x,A)\\to^n_M(q,\\epsilon,\\epsilon)\\Leftrightarrow(*,x,\\langle p,A,q\\rangle)\\to^n_{M\'}(*,\\epsilon,\\epsilon)\\]\r\nIt then follows that \\(L(M)=L(M\')\\)<br/>\r\n<br/><br/><br/>\r\n</li>\r\n<li><b>Every NPDA with one state has an equivalent CFG</b><br/>\r\n<br/>\r\nTake a one-state NPDA \\(M=(\\{q\\},\\Sigma,\\Gamma,\\delta,q,\\perp,\\emptyset)\\) that accepts by empty stack. Define\r\n\\[G_M=(\\Gamma,\\Sigma,P,\\perp)\\]\r\nwhere \\(P\\) contains a rule\r\n\\[A\\to cB_1...B_k\\]\r\nfor every transition \\((q,B_1...B_k)\\in\\delta(q,c,A)\\) where \\(c\\in\\Sigma\\cup\\{\\epsilon\\}\\). Then we have \\(L(M)=L(G_M)\\)\r\n</li>\r\n</ol>\r\n</li>\r\n</ol>',364),(172,'','Let \\(G_1=(\\Gamma_1,\\Sigma,R_1,S_1)\\) and \\(G_2=(\\Gamma_2,\\Sigma,R_2,S_2)\\) be context free grammars with \\(\\Gamma_1\\cap\\Gamma_2=\\emptyset\\). Consider the following context free grammars:\r\n\\[\\begin{array}{lll}\r\nG_{union}&&\\mbox{=}&&(\\Gamma_1\\cup\\Gamma_2\\cup\\{S\\},\\Sigma,R_1\\cup R_2\\cup\\{S\\to S_1,S\\to S_2\\},S)\\\\\r\nG_{concat}&&\\mbox{=}&&(\\Gamma_1\\cup\\Gamma_2\\cup\\{S\\},\\Sigma,R_1\\cup R_2\\cup\\{S\\to S_1S_2\\},S)\\\\\r\nG_{star}&&\\mbox{=}&&(\\Gamma_1\\cup\\{S\\},\\Sigma,R_1\\cup\\{S\\to S_1S,S\\to\\epsilon\\},S)\r\n\\end{array}\\]\r\nwhere \\(S\\) is a fresh variable. Then\r\n\\[\\begin{array}{lll}\r\nL(G_{union})&&\\mbox{=}&&L(G_1)\\cup L(G_2)\\\\\r\nL(G_{concat})&&\\mbox{=}&&L(G_1)\\cdot L(G_2)\\\\\r\nL(G_{star})&&\\mbox{=}&&L(G_1)^*\r\n\\end{array}\\]',365),(173,'','<ol>\r\n<li>Both \\(A=\\{0^n1^n0^m:n,m\\geq0\\}\\) and \\(B=\\{0^n1^m0^m:n,m\\geq0\\}\\) are context free. But \\(A\\cap B=\\{0^n1^n0^n:n\\geq0\\}\\) is not context free.<br/>\r\n<br/><br/>\r\n</li>\r\n<li>Let \\(A\\) be a regular language accepted by an NFA \\(M=(Q_1,\\Sigma,\\delta_1,q_1,F_1)\\) and let \\(B\\) be a context free language accepted by an NPDA \\(N=(Q_2,\\Sigma,\\Gamma,\\delta_2,q_2,\\perp,F_2)\\).<br/>\r\nDefine the \"product\"-automaton\r\n\\[P=(Q_1\\times Q_2,\\Sigma,\\Gamma,\\delta,(q_1,q_2),\\perp,F_1\\times F_2)\\]\r\nwhere \\(\\delta\\) is given by\r\n\\[\\delta((r,t),a,A)=\\{((r\',t\'),\\alpha):r\'\\in\\delta_1(r,a),(t\',\\alpha)\\in\\delta_2(t,a,A)\\}\\]\r\nthen \\(P\\) is an NPDA that accepts \\(A\\cap B\\)\r\n</li>\r\n</ol>',366),(174,'','<b>There are only countably many TMs</b><br/>\r\nObserve that \\(\\Sigma^*\\) is countable, for any alphabet \\(\\Sigma\\). Write \\(\\langle M\\rangle\\) to mean the string representation of a TM, the exact format doesn\'t matter. Since \\(\\langle M\\rangle\\in\\Sigma^*\\), we can enumerate the set of TMs by simply omitting those strings that are not encodings of TMs.<br/>\r\n<br/>\r\n<b>The set of languages over \\(\\Sigma\\), \\(\\mathbb P(\\Sigma^*)\\), is uncountable</b><br/>\r\nSuppose there were an enumeration of \\(\\mathbb P(\\Sigma^*)\\), namely \\(L_1,L_2,...\\). Let \\(x_1,x_2,...\\) be an enumeration of \\(\\Sigma^*\\). Define a new language by:\r\n\\[\\forall i\\geq1,x_i\\in L\\Leftrightarrow x_i\\not\\in L_i\\]\r\nNow \\(L\\in\\mathbb P(\\Sigma^*)\\), but \\(L\\) is not equal to any of the \\(L_i\\)s.<br/>\r\n<br/>\r\nThus \\(\\mathbb P(\\Sigma^*)\\) is not in 1-1 correspondence with the set of Turing machines. It follows that there is some language that is not accepted by any Turing machine.',374),(175,'','We construct a TM \\(M\\) that decides \\(A_{DFA}\\):<br/>\r\nOn input \\(\\langle B,w\\rangle\\) where \\(B\\) is a DFA and \\(w\\) an input\r\n<ol>\r\n<li>Simulate \\(B\\) on input \\(w\\)</li>\r\n<li>If the simulation ends in an accepts state, accept. If if ends in a non-accepting state, reject.</li>\r\n</ol>',375),(176,'','We design a TM \\(T\\) that uses a marking algorithm. On input \\(\\langle A\\rangle\\) where \\(A\\) is a DFA:<br/>\r\n<ol>\r\n<li>Mark the start state of \\(A\\).</li>\r\n<li>Repeat until no new states get marked:<br/>\r\nMark any state that has a transition coming into it from any marked state.</li>\r\n<li>If no accept state is marked, accept; otherwise reject.</li>\r\n</ol>',376),(177,'','Key idea: For sets \\(P\\) and \\(Q\\), \\(P\\subset Q\\) iff \\(P\\cap Q^C=\\emptyset\\). We use \\(T\\), the algorithm for \\(E_{DFA}\\).<br/>\r\nOn input \\(\\langle A,B\\rangle\\), where \\(A\\) and \\(B\\) are DFAs:\r\n<ol>\r\n<li>Construct \\(C=(A\\cap B^C)\\cup(B\\cap A^C)\\)</li>\r\n<li>Run \\(T\\) on input \\(\\langle C\\rangle\\)</li>\r\n<li>If \\(T\\) accepts, accept; if \\(T\\) rejects, reject</li>\r\n</ol>',377),(178,'','The TM \\(S\\) for \\(A_{CFG}\\) is:<br/>\r\nOn input \\(\\langle G,w\\rangle\\), where \\(G\\) is a CFG and \\(w\\) is a string\r\n<ol>\r\n<li>Convert \\(G\\) to an equivalent one in Chomsky normal form</li>\r\n<li>List all derivations with \\(2n-1\\) steps, where \\(n\\) is the length of \\(w\\)</li>\r\n<li>If any of these derivations generate \\(w\\), accept; otherwise, reject</li>\r\n</ol>\r\nNote that this is of course extremely inefficient, but it shows that it\'s possible.',378),(179,'','The TM \\(R\\) for \\(E_{CFG}\\) is:<br/>\r\nOn input \\(\\langle G\\rangle\\), where \\(G=(V,\\Sigma,R,S)\\) is a CFG\r\n<ol>\r\n<li>Mark all terminals in \\(G\\)</li>\r\n<li>Repeat until no new variables get marked:<br/>\r\nMark any variable \\(A\\) where \\(G\\) contains a rule \\(A\\to U_1...U_k\\) and each symbol \\(U_i\\in\\Sigma\\cup V\\) has already been marked.</li>\r\n<li>If the start symbol is not marked, accept; otherwise, reject.</li>\r\n</ol>',379),(180,'','We define a TM \\(U\\) that accepts \\(A_{TM}\\):<br/>\r\nOn input \\(\\langle M,w\\rangle\\) where \\(M\\) is a TM and \\(w\\) is a string\r\n<ol>\r\n<li>Simulate \\(M\\) on input \\(w\\)</li>\r\n<li>If \\(M\\) ever enters its accept state, accept; if \\(M\\) ever enters its reject state, reject</li>\r\n</ol>\r\nThis shows that \\(A_{TM}\\) is RE.<br/>\r\n<br/><br/><br/>\r\nNow suppose for a contradiction that \\(U\\) is a decider for \\(A_{TM}\\). Construct a new TM \\(D\\) with \\(U\\) as a subroutine:<br/>\r\nOn input \\(\\langle M\\rangle\\), where \\(M\\) is a TM\r\n<ol>\r\n<li>Run \\(U\\) on input \\(\\langle M,\\langle M\\rangle\\rangle\\)</li>\r\n<li>Output the opposite of \\(U\\)</li>\r\n</ol>\r\nThus\r\n\\[D(\\langle M\\rangle)=\r\n\\left\\{\\begin{array}{ll}\r\nreject&&if&nbsp;M&nbsp;accepts&nbsp;\\langle M\\rangle\\\\\r\naccept&&if&nbsp;M&nbsp;does&nbsp;not&nbsp;accept&nbsp;\\langle M\\rangle\r\n\\end{array}\\right.\\]\r\nNow we run \\(D\\) on input \\(\\langle D\\rangle\\). So\r\n\\[D(\\langle D\\rangle)=\r\n\\left\\{\\begin{array}{ll}\r\nreject&&if&nbsp;D&nbsp;accepts&nbsp;\\langle D\\rangle\\\\\r\naccept&&if&nbsp;D&nbsp;does&nbsp;not&nbsp;accept&nbsp;\\langle D\\rangle\r\n\\end{array}\\right.\\]\r\nSo, \\(D\\) accepts \\(\\langle D\\rangle\\) iff \\(D\\) rejects \\(\\langle D\\rangle\\), which is a contradiction. Thus neither \\(D\\) nor \\(U\\) can exist.<br/>\r\n<br/>\r\nTherefore \\(A_{TM}\\) is undecidable.',381),(181,'','To show that \\(HALT_{TM}\\) is RE, just simulate the given TM and accept if it does.<br/>\r\n<br/>\r\nSuppose now, for a contradiction that \\(H\\) is a decider for \\(HALT_{TM}\\). We use \\(H\\) to construct a TM \\(S\\) to decide \\(A_{TM}\\) as follows:<br/>\r\nOn input \\(\\langle M,w\\rangle\\) where \\(M\\) is a TM and \\(w\\) is an input:\r\n<ol>\r\n<li>Run TM \\(H\\) on input \\(\\langle M,w\\rangle\\)</li>\r\n<li>If \\(H\\) rejects, reject</li>\r\n<li>If \\(H\\) accepts, run \\(M\\) on \\(w\\) until it halts</li>\r\n<li>If \\(M\\) has accepted, accept; if \\(M\\) has rejected, reject</li>\r\n</ol>\r\nSince \\(A_{TM}\\) is undecidable, \\(H\\) cannot be a decider for \\(HALT_{TM}\\)',382),(182,'','To show that \\(E_{TM}\\) is co-RE, simply simulate the given TM on all inputs until one is found that is accepted.<br/>\r\n<br/>\r\nNow suppose, for a contradiction that \\(E_{TM}\\) is decidable by a TM \\(E\\). We shall use \\(E\\) to construct a TM \\(S\\) that decides \\(A_{TM}\\):<br/>\r\nOn input \\(\\langle M,x\\rangle\\) where \\(M\\) is a TM and \\(x\\) an input\r\n<ol>\r\n<li>Construct a TM \\(M_x\\) defined as:<br/>\r\nOn input \\(y\\)\r\n<ol>\r\n<li>If \\(y\\neq x\\) then reject</li>\r\n<li>Run \\(M\\) on input \\(x\\) and accept iff \\(M\\) does</li>\r\n</ol>\r\n</li>\r\n<li>Run \\(E\\) on input \\(\\langle M_x\\rangle\\). If \\(E\\) accepts, reject; if \\(E\\) rejects, accept</li>\r\n</ol>\r\nNow we have\r\n<ul>\r\n<li>\\(M\\) accepts \\(x\\Rightarrow L(M_x)=\\{x\\}\\)</li>\r\n<li>\\(M\\) does not accept \\(x\\Rightarrow L(M_x)=\\emptyset\\)</li>\r\n</ul>\r\nThus \\(S\\) decides \\(A_{TM}\\), which is a contradiction.',383),(183,'','Suppose for a contradiction that \\(EQ_{TM}\\) is decided by a TM \\(Q\\). We define a TM that decides \\(E_{TM}\\) by:<br/>\r\nOn input \\(\\langle M\\rangle\\)\r\n<ol>\r\n<li>Run \\(Q\\) on input \\(\\langle M,M_1\\rangle\\) where \\(M_1\\) is a TM that accepts nothing</li>\r\n<li>If \\(Q\\) accepts, accept; if \\(Q\\) rejects, reject</li>\r\n</ol>\r\nThis gives a contradiction',384),(184,'','\\(HALT_{TM}\\) is not decidable, but it is RE. Hence \\(\\overline{HALT_{TM}}\\) is not RE. Therefore is suffices to reduce \\(\\overline{HALT_{TM}}\\) to (1) \\(TOTAL\\) and to (2) \\(\\overline{TOTAL}\\)\r\n<ol>\r\n<li>Given \\(\\langle M,x\\rangle\\) where \\(M\\) is a TM and \\(x\\) is an input, we set \\(N_{M,x}\\) to be the following TM:<br/>\r\nOn input y,\r\n<ol>\r\n<li>Run \\(M\\) on input \\(x\\) for up to \\(|y|\\) steps</li>\r\n<li>If \\(M\\) has halted, then loop; if \\(M\\) has not yet halted, accept</li>\r\n</ol>\r\nWe have that\r\n\\[\\langle M,x\\rangle\\in\\overline{HALT_{TM}}\\Leftrightarrow N_{M,x}&nbsp;halts&nbsp;on&nbsp;all&nbsp;input&nbsp;y\\Leftrightarrow N_{M,x}\\in TOTAL\\]\r\n<br/><Br/><br/>\r\n</li>\r\n<li>Given \\(\\langle M,x\\rangle\\) where \\(M\\) is a TM and \\(x\\) is an input, we construct \\(N_{M,x}\\) to be the following TM:<br/>\r\nOn input y,\r\n<ol>\r\n<li>Erase y</li>\r\n<li>Write \\(x\\) on input tape and run \\(M\\) on it</li>\r\n<li>If \\(M\\) accepts, accept; if \\(M\\) rejects, reject</li>\r\n</ol>\r\nNote that either \\(N_{M,x}\\) loops on all inputs, or it halts on all inputs. Now\r\n\\[\\langle M,x\\rangle\\in\\overline{HALT_{TM}}\\Leftrightarrow N_{M,x}&nbsp;loops&nbsp;on&nbsp;all&nbsp;inputs\\Leftrightarrow N_{M,x}\\not\\in TOTAL\\]\r\n</li>\r\n</ol>',385),(185,'','Take a property \\(P\\) that satisfies the conditions in the statement. Without loss of generality assume that for any TM \\(E\\), if \\(L(E)=\\emptyset\\), then \\(\\langle E\\rangle\\not\\in P\\). Take a TM \\(K\\) such that \\(\\langle K\\rangle\\in P\\). Given \\(\\langle M,x\\rangle\\) where \\(M\\) is a TM and \\(x\\) is an input, we construct \\(N_{M,x}\\) as follows:<br/>\r\nOn input \\(y\\),\r\n<ol>\r\n<li>Save \\(y\\) on a separate track somewhere</li>\r\n<li>Write \\(x\\) on the input tape and run \\(M\\) on input \\(x\\)</li>\r\n<li>If \\(M\\) halts on \\(x\\), run \\(K\\) on \\(y\\)</li>\r\n<li>If \\(K\\) accepts, accept</li>\r\n</ol>\r\nEither \\(M\\) halts on \\(x\\) or not.<br/>\r\n<ul>\r\n<li>If \\(M\\) does not halt on \\(x\\), the simulation in \\(3.\\) will not halt and the input \\(y\\) on \\(N_{M,x}\\) will not be accepted, so \\(L(N_{M,x})=\\emptyset\\), so \\(\\langle N_{M,x}\\rangle\\not\\in P\\)</li>\r\n<li>On the other hand, if \\(M\\) halts on \\(x\\), \\(y\\) is accepted by \\(N_{M,x}\\) iff \\(y\\) is accepted by \\(K\\), so \\(L(N_{M,x})=L(K)\\) and \\(\\langle N_{M,x}\\rangle\\in P\\)</li>\r\n</ul>\r\nThus\r\n\\[\\begin{array}{ll}\r\nM&nbsp;halts&nbsp;on&nbsp;x&&\\Rightarrow&&L(N_{M,x})=L(K)&&\\Rightarrow&&\\langle N_{M,x}\\rangle\\in P\\\\\r\nM&nbsp;does&nbsp;not&nbsp;accept&nbsp;x&&\\Rightarrow&&L(N_{M,x})=\\emptyset&&\\Rightarrow&&\\langle N_{M,x}\\rangle\\not\\in P\r\n\\end{array}\\]\r\nThus we have reduced \\(HALT_{TM}\\) to \\(P\\). Since \\(HALT_{TM}\\) is undecidable, so is \\(P\\).\r\n',386),(186,'','\\[\\begin{array}{}\r\n&&a+I=b+I\\\\\r\n\\Longleftrightarrow&&(a-b)+I=I\\\\\r\n\\Longleftrightarrow&&\\forall x\\in I,\\exists y\\in I&nbsp;s.t.&nbsp;(a-b)+x=y\\\\\r\n\\Longleftrightarrow&&a-b\\in I\r\n\\end{array}\\]',150),(187,'','All requirements for \\(R\\over I\\) follow directly from those for \\(R\\)',152),(188,'','Suppose \\(\\phi:F\\to R\\) is a homomorphism, where \\(F\\) is a field and \\(R\\) is a ring. Note that \\(ker\\phi\\) is an ideal of \\(F\\) but this is a field so it has no proper ideals, also it is a homomorphism to a non-trivial ring, hence \\(ker\\phi\\) is \\(\\{0\\}\\).<br/>\r\n<br/>\r\nTherefore, by the first isomorphism theorem\r\n\\[F\\cong{F\\over ker\\phi}\\cong im\\phi=R\\]',186),(189,'','Define \\(d(a+bi)=a^2+b^2\\) for all \\(a,b\\in\\mathbb Q\\)<br/>\r\nIf \\(a,b,c,d\\in\\mathbb Q\\), then\r\n\\[d((a+bi)(c+di))=d(ac-bd+i(bc+ad))=(ac-bd)^2+(bc+ad)^2\\]\r\n\\[=a^2c^2+b^2c^2+b^2d^2+a^2d^2=(a^2+b^2)(c^2+d^2)=d(a+bi)d(c+di)\\]\r\nThen using \\(d(a+bi)=a^2+b^2\\geq 1\\) for \\(a,b\\in\\mathbb Z\\). We have that\r\n\\[d(xy)\\geq d(x)&nbsp;for&nbsp;x,y\\in\\mathbb Z[i]\\setminus\\{0\\}\\]\r\n<br/><br/><br/>\r\nDivide \\(\\gamma+\\beta i\\) by \\(\\gamma+\\delta i\\), where \\(\\alpha,\\beta,\\gamma,\\delta\\in\\mathbb Z\\)<br/>\r\nIn \\(\\mathbb Q[i]\\), \\({\\alpha+\\beta i\\over\\gamma+\\delta i}=(\\epsilon+\\phi)+(\\eta+\\theta)i\\), where \\(\\epsilon,\\eta\\in\\mathbb Z\\) and \\(|\\phi|,|\\theta|\\leq{1\\over2}\\)<br/>\r\nSo\r\n\\[\\alpha+\\beta i=(\\gamma+\\delta i)(\\epsilon+\\eta i)+(\\phi+\\theta i)(\\gamma+\\delta i)\\]\r\n\\[\\Rightarrow(\\phi+\\theta i)(\\gamma+\\delta i)=(\\alpha+\\beta i)-(\\gamma+\\delta i)(\\epsilon+\\eta i)\\in\\mathbb Z[i]\\]\r\nNow\r\n\\[d((\\phi+\\theta i)(\\gamma+\\delta i))=d(\\phi+\\theta i)d(\\gamma+\\delta i)\\]\r\nwhere\r\n\\[d(\\phi+\\theta i)=\\phi^2+\\theta^2\\leq{1\\over4}+{1\\over4}\\lt1\\]\r\nSo \\(d((\\phi+\\theta i)(\\gamma+\\delta i))\\lt d(\\gamma+\\delta i)\\) or \\((\\phi+\\theta i)(\\gamma+\\delta i)=0\\)',387),(190,'','<ul>\r\n<li>\\(\\lnot(1)\\Rightarrow\\lnot(2)\\)<br/>\r\nIf \\(X\\subset S\\) is non-empty and both open and closed in \\(S\\), then \\(Y=S\\setminus X\\) is also non-empty and both open and closed in \\(S\\).<br/>\r\nHence \\(X,Y\\) are disjoint, non-empty and \\(S=X\\cup Y\\).<br/>\r\n<br/><Br/><BR/>\r\n</li>\r\n<li>\\(\\lnot(2)\\Rightarrow\\lnot(1)\\)<br/>\r\nSuppose \\(S=X\\cup Y\\) with \\(X,Y\\) being open, disjoint and non-empty. Then as \\(X=S\\setminus Y\\), \\(X\\) is closed also. So there is a proper subset of \\(S\\) that is both open and closed.<br/>\r\n<br/><Br/><BR/>\r\n</li>\r\n<li>\\((1)\\Rightarrow(3)\\)<br/>\r\nSuppose the only open and closed subsets of \\(S\\) are \\(\\emptyset\\) and \\(S\\). Suppose \\(f:S\\to\\mathbb Z\\) is continuous.<br/>\r\nTake some \\(x_0\\in S\\), let \\(y_0=f(x_0)\\). \\(\\{y_0\\}\\) is open in \\(\\mathbb Z\\), so \\(X=f^{-1}(\\{y_0\\})\\) is open in \\(S\\).<br/>\r\nNote that \\(\\mathbb Z\\setminus\\{y_0\\}\\) is also open in \\(Z\\), so \\(Y=f^{-1}(\\mathbb Z\\setminus\\{y_0\\})=S\\setminus X\\) is open in \\(S\\).<br/>\r\nSo \\(X\\) is both open and closed, so \\(X=\\emptyset\\) or \\(X=S\\). However we know \\(x_0\\in X\\), so \\(X=S\\) and so \\(f\\) is constant<br/>\r\n<br/><Br/><BR/>\r\n</li>\r\n<li>\\(\\lnot(2)\\Rightarrow\\lnot(3)\\)<br/>\r\nSuppose \\(X,Y\\subset S\\) are open, disjoint, non-empty and \\(S=X\\cup Y\\).<br/>\r\nDefine \\(f:S\\to\\mathbb Z\\) by\r\n\\[f(x)=\\left\\{\\begin{array}{ll}0&&if&nbsp;x\\in X\\\\1&&if&nbsp;x\\in Y\\end{array}\\right.\\]\r\nThen \\(\\forall U\\subset\\mathbb Z\\), \\(f^{-1}(U)\\in\\{\\emptyset,X,Y,S\\}\\) which are all open in \\(S\\), hence \\(f\\) is continuous.\r\n</li>\r\n</ul>',104),(191,'','Use induction on \\(j\\) to show that \\(span\\{u_1,...,u_j\\}=span\\{v_1,...,v_j\\}\\).<br/>\r\n<br/>\r\nThe base case of \\(j=1\\) is obvious<br/>\r\n<br/>\r\nNow suppose \\(span\\{u_1,...,u_j\\}=span\\{v_1,...,v_j\\}\\).<br/>\r\nWell, \\(u_{j+1}\\not\\in span\\{u_1,...,u_j\\}\\) since \\(\\{u_1,...,u_n\\}\\) is linearly independent, so \\(w_{j+1}\\not\\in span\\{u_1,...,u_j\\}\\).<br/>\r\nThen by mods work\r\n\\[span\\{u_1,...,u_{j+1}\\}=span\\{v_1,...,v_j,u_{j+1}\\}=span\\{v_1,...,v_j,w_{j+1}\\}=span\\{v_1,...,v_{j+1}\\}\\]\r\nIf \\(i\\lt j\\) then\r\n\\[\\langle w_j,v_i\\rangle=\\langle u_j-\\sum_{k=1}^{j-1}\\langle u_j,u_i\\rangle v_k,v_i\\rangle=\\langle u_j,v_i\\rangle-\\langle u_j,v_i\\rangle\\langle v_i,v_i\\rangle=\\langle u_j,v_i\\rangle-\\langle u_j,v_i\\rangle=0\\]\r\n\\[\\|v_j\\|=\\sqrt{\\langle v_j,v_j\\rangle}=\\sqrt{\\langle{w_j\\over\\|w_j\\|},{w_j\\over\\|w_j\\|}\\rangle}=\\sqrt{{1\\over\\|w_j\\|}\\overline{1\\over\\|w_j\\|}\\overline{\\langle w_j,w_j\\rangle}}=\\sqrt{\\langle w_j,w_j\\rangle\\over\\langle w_j,w_j\\rangle}=1\\]',250),(192,'','<ul>\r\n<li>\\((\\Rightarrow)\\)<br/>\r\nSuppose \\(I\\) is a prime ideal of \\(R\\), then for all \\(a,b\\in R\\), \\(ab\\in I\\) iff \\(a\\in I\\) or \\(b\\in I\\).<br/>\r\nThus if \\(a+I,b+I\\in {R\\over I}\\), then \\(a,b\\not\\in I\\), so we know \\(ab\\not\\in I\\), therefore \\((a+I)(b+I)\\neq0+I\\). So \\(R\\over I\\) is an integral domain.<br/>\r\n<br/><Br/><br/>\r\n</li>\r\n<li>\\((\\Leftarrow)\\)<br/>\r\nSuppose \\(I\\) is not a prime ideal of \\(R\\), then there exist \\(a,b\\in R\\) such that \\(a,b\\not\\in I\\) but \\(ab\\in I\\). Then \\(a+I,b+I\\neq0+I\\), but \\((a+I)(b+I)=(ab)+I=0+I\\). So \\(R\\over I\\) is not an integral domain.\r\n</li>\r\n</ul>',390),(193,'','\\((\\Rightarrow)\\)<br/>\r\nLet \\(J\'\\) be an ideal of \\(R\\over I\\), let \\(J=\\{a:a+I\\in J\'\\}\\). Then \\(I\\subset J\\) and \\(J\\) is an ideal, \\(I\\) is maximal, so \\(I=J\\) or \\(J=R\\). Thus \\(J\'=\\{0+I\\}\\), or \\(J\'={R\\over I}\\). So \\(R\\over I\\) has no proper ideals, so it is a field.<br/>\r\n<br/>\r\n\\((\\Leftarrow)\\)<br/>\r\nLet \\(I,J\\) be ideals of \\(R\\) s.t. \\(R\\over I\\) is a field, \\(I\\neq J\\) but \\(I\\subset J\\). Then \\(a\\in J\\setminus I\\Rightarrow a+I\\neq0+I\\Rightarrow(a+I)(b+I)=1+I\\) for some \\(b\\in R\\) \\(\\Rightarrow m=ab-1\\in I\\Rightarrow 1=ab-m\\in J\\Rightarrow J=R\\). Hence \\(I\\) is maximal.',187),(194,'','Writing \\(b=res(f(z); a)\\), we know that \\(b=\\lim_{z\\to a}(z-a)f(z)\\)<br/>\r\nGiven \\(\\eta\\gt0\\), there exists \\(\\delta\\gt0\\) such that \\(|(z-a)f(z)-b|\\lt\\eta\\) whenever \\(0\\lt|z-a|\\lt\\delta\\). Let \\(0\\lt\\epsilon\\lt min(r,\\delta)\\). When \\(z=\\gamma_\\epsilon(\\theta)\\) we have \\(\\gamma_\\epsilon\'(\\theta)=\\epsilon ie^{i\\theta}=i(z-a)\\) and so\r\n\\[|\\int_{\\gamma_\\epsilon}f(z)dz-ib(\\theta_2-\\theta_1)|=|\\int_{\\theta_1}^{\\theta_2}(f(\\gamma_\\epsilon(\\theta))\\gamma_\\epsilon\'(\\theta)-ib)d\\theta|\\]\r\n\\[=|\\int_{\\theta_1}^{\\theta_2}g(\\gamma_\\epsilon(\\theta))d\\theta|\\lt\\eta(\\theta_2-\\theta_1)\\]',391),(195,'','Suppose there are repetitions, choose minimal \\(k\\) such that \\(\\exists m\\gt0\\) with \\(k1=(k+m)1\\).<br/>\r\nIf \\(k\\gt0\\) then \\((k-1)1+1=(k+m-1)1+1\\), so \\((k-1)1=((k-1)+m)1\\), which contradicts \\(k\\) being minimal. Hence \\(k=0\\).',396),(196,'','\\((N1)\\Rightarrow(M1)\\) immediately.<br/>\r\n\\((N2)\\) with \\(\\lambda=-1,v=x-y\\Rightarrow(M2)\\)<br/>\r\n\\((N3)\\) with \\(v=x-y,w=y-z\\Rightarrow(M3)\\)',403),(197,'','<ol>\r\n<li>Obvious from standard results of \\(||\\)<br/><br/></li>\r\n<li>\\((M1),(M2)\\) come straight from definition.<br/>\r\nIf \\(x=z\\) then \\(d(x,z)=0\\), else \\(x\\neq z\\) and we can\'t have both \\(x=y\\) and \\(y=z\\), so either \\(d(x,y)=1\\) or \\(d(y,z)=1\\). \\((M3)\\) follows from these two cases.',404),(198,'','Let \\(x\\in B(x_0,r)\\), \\(\\epsilon_x=r-d(x_0,x)\\gt0\\). Then \\(\\forall y\\in B(x,\\epsilon_x)\\), \\(d(x_0,y)\\leq d(x_0,x)+d(x,y)\\lt d(x_0,x)+\\epsilon_x=r\\). So \\(B(x,\\epsilon_x)\\subset B(x,r)\\)',409),(199,'','Let \\(n=|E:F|\\), then \\(1,a,a^2,...,a^n\\) is a sequence of \\(n+1\\) elements, so they are linearly dependent. So \\(\\exists c_0,...,c_n\\in F\\) which are not all zero such that \\(c_0+c_1a+c_2a^2+...+c_na^n=0\\).<br/>\r\nDefine \\(f(x)=c_0+c_1x+...+c_nx^n\\in F[X]\\), then \\(f\\neq0\\) but \\(f(a)=0\\)',414),(200,'','\\((\\Rightarrow)\\)<br/>\r\nSuppose \\(L\\) is finite over \\(F\\). A finite spanning set for \\(L\\) over \\(F\\) is a finite spanning set for \\(L\\) over \\(K\\), so \\(L\\) is finite over \\(K\\). Also, \\(K\\) is a subspace of \\(L\\), so \\(K\\) is finite dimensional over \\(F\\).<br/>\r\n<br/><br/><Br/>\r\n\\((\\Leftarrow)\\)<br/>\r\nNow suppose \\(|K:F|\\) and \\(|L:K|\\) are finite. So let \\(a_1,...,a_m\\in F\\) be a basis for \\(K\\) over \\(F\\), \\(b_1,...,b_n\\in K\\) a basis for \\(L\\) over \\(K\\). Let\r\n\\[S=\\{a_ib_j:1\\leq i\\leq m,1\\leq j\\leq n\\}\\]\r\nneed to prove that \\(S\\) is a basis for \\(L\\) over \\(F\\).<br/>\r\n<br/>\r\n<b>Spanning</b>:<br/>\r\nLet \\(x\\in L\\).<br/>\r\nSince \\(b_1,...,b_n\\) form a spanning set for \\(L\\) over \\(K\\), there exist \\(y_1,...,y_n\\in K\\) s.t. \\(x=y_1b_1+...+y_nb_n\\).<br/>\r\nSince \\(a_1,...,a_m\\) form a spanning set for \\(K\\) over \\(F\\) and \\(y_j\\in K\\), \\(\\exists\\delta_{ij}\\in F\\) s.t. \\(y_i=\\delta_{1j}a_1+...+\\delta_{mj}a_m\\). Then\r\n\\[x=\\sum_{i=1}^ny_ib_i=\\sum_{i=1}^n\\sum_{j=1}^m\\delta_{ij}a_jb_i=\\sum_{i,j}\\delta_{ij}(a_jb_i)\\in span S\\]\r\n<br/>\r\n<b>Linear independence</b>:<br/>\r\nSuppose that \\(u_{ij}\\in F\\) and \\(\\sum_{ij}u_{ij}a_ib_j=0\\), then\r\n\\[\\sum_{j=1}^n(\\sum_{i=1}^mu_{ij}a_i)b_j=0\\]\r\nSince \\(b_1,...,b_n\\) are linearly independent over \\(K\\) and for each \\(j\\), \\(\\sum_{i=1}^mu_{ij}a_i\\in K\\), then\r\n\\[\\sum_{i=1}^mu_{ij}a_i=0\\]\r\nNow, as \\(a_1,...,a_m\\) are linearly independent, \\(u_{ij}=0\\) for all \\(i,j\\).<br/>\r\n<br/>\r\nSo \\(S\\) is a basis for \\(L\\) over \\(F\\) and \\(|L:F|=|S|=mn\\)',412),(201,'','\\((\\Rightarrow)\\)<br/>\r\nFor all \\(x\\in U\\), \\(\\exists\\epsilon_x\\gt0\\) s.t. \\(B(x,\\epsilon_x)\\subset U\\). Therefore \\(U=\\bigcup_{x\\in U}B(x,\\epsilon_x)\\).<br/>\r\n<br/>\r\n\\((\\Leftarrow)\\)<br/>\r\nAll open balls are open, and an arbitrary union of open sets is open, therefore \\(U\\) is open.',418),(202,'','Suppose \\(f(x_1)=f(x_2)\\), then \\(d(x_1,x_2)=d(f(x_1),f(x_2))=0\\), so \\(x_1=x_2\\)',422),(203,'','Suppose \\(x_n\\to a\\) and \\(x_n\\to b\\) as \\(n\\to\\infty\\).<br/>\r\nLet \\(\\epsilon\\gt0\\), then \\(\\exists N_1,N_2\\in\\mathbb N\\) s.t.\r\n\\[\\forall n\\geq N_1,d(a,x_n)\\lt{\\epsilon\\over2}\\]\r\n\\[\\forall n\\geq N_2,d(b,x_n)\\lt{\\epsilon\\over2}\\]\r\nSo, \\(\\forall n\\geq max(N_1,N_2)\\), \\(d(a,x_n)\\lt{\\epsilon\\over2}\\) and \\(d(a,x_n)\\lt{\\epsilon\\over2}\\).<br/>\r\nThen \\(d(a,b)\\leq d(a,x_n)+d(b,x_n)\\lt\\epsilon\\).<br/>\r\nBut this is for any \\(\\epsilon\\gt0\\), hence \\(d(a,b)=0\\Longrightarrow a=b\\)',429),(204,'','<ol>\r\n<li>\\(a\\) is algebraic, so there is at least one such polynomial, therefore there must be one of least degree.<br/>\r\n<br/>\r\nSuppose \\(m_1,m_2\\) both satisfy the conditions of being a minimum polynomial. \\(\\deg(m_1)=\\deg(m_2)\\) and they\'re both monic, so \\(m_1-m_2\\) is a polynomial of less degree and \\((m_1-m_2)(a)=m_1(a)-m_2(a)=0\\), but the previous polynomials were of least degree, so we must have \\(m_1-m_2=0\\). Therefore \\(m_1=m_2\\).<br/>\r\n<br/><br/><br/>\r\n</li>\r\n<li>Suppose that \\(f(a)=0\\) where \\(f(x)\\in F[X]\\). Use the division algorithm to find \\(q(x),r(x)\\in F[X]\\) such that \\(f(x)=m(x)q(x)+r(x)\\) and \\(\\deg(r)\\lt\\deg(m)\\) or \\(r=0\\). Now, \\(r(a)=f(a)-m(a)q(a)=0\\), but \\(\\deg(m)\\) is minimal, so \\(r=0\\).<br/>\r\n<br/><br/><br/>\r\n</li>\r\n<li>Suppose \\(m(x)=p(x)q(x)\\), w.l.o.g. assume that \\(p(x),q(x)\\) are monic. Because \\(m(a)=0\\), either \\(p(a)=0\\) or \\(q(a)=0\\), w.l.o.g. assume \\(p(a)=0\\). But \\(\\deg(m)\\) is minimal, so \\(\\deg(m)=\\deg(p)\\). Therefore \\(q(x)=1\\), so \\(q\\) is a unit.\r\n</li>\r\n</ol>',438),(205,'','Define \\(\\phi:F[X]\\to E\\) by \\(\\phi(f(x))=f(a)\\), \\(\\phi\\) is a ring homomorphism.\r\n\\[ker(\\phi)=\\{f(x):f(a)=0\\}=A\\]\r\n\\[im(\\phi)=F[a]\\leq E\\]\r\nSo by the first isomorphism theorem, \\(im(\\phi)\\cong{F[X]\\over ker(\\phi)}\\Longrightarrow F[a]\\cong{F[X]\\over A}\\).<br/>\r\n<br/>\r\nSince \\(m(x)\\) is irreducible and \\(F[X]\\) is a principle ideal domain, \\(A\\) is maximal amongst proper ideals of \\(F[X]\\). Therefore \\(F[X]\\over A\\) is a field.<br/>\r\n<br/>\r\nHence \\(im(\\phi)=F[a]=F(a)\\leq E\\).<br/>\r\nThen \\(1,a,a^2,...,a^{n-1}\\) is a basis for \\(F(a)\\) over \\(F\\), where \\(n=\\deg(m(x))=\\deg(a)\\). So \\(|F(a):F]=n\\)',439),(206,'','By the Tower theorem, since \\(F\\leq F(a)\\leq E\\), \\(|E:F|=|E:F(a)|\\times|F(a):F|=|E:F(a)|\\times\\deg(a)\\)',440),(207,'','Let \\(a,b\\in K\\), then \\(F(a,b)=F(a)(b)\\). But \\(|F(a):F|\\) is finite and \\(b\\) is algebraic over \\(F\\) and therefore algebraic over \\(F(a)\\), so \\(|F(a,b):F(a)|\\) is finite. Now by the Tower theorem, \\(|F(a,b):F|\\) is finite.<br/>\r\n<br/>\r\nBut \\(F(a,b)\\) contains \\(a\\pm b, ab, {a\\over b}\\). So being memebers of a finite extension these are algebraic.<br/>\r\nHence \\(F\\leq K\\leq E\\).',441),(208,'','The minimum polynomial of \\(\\root n\\of2\\) is \\(x^n-2\\) over \\(\\mathbb Q\\), because \\(m(x)\\) divides \\(x^n-2\\) but this is irreducible by Eisenstein\'s criterion. So \\(|A:\\mathbb Q|\\geq n\\), but this is unbounded.',442),(209,'','The proof is by induction on the structure of \\(H\\):\r\n<ul>\r\n<li>\\(F\\) is identical to \\(H\\), then \\(H\'\\) is identical to \\(G\\), so \\(H\\equiv H\'\\)<br/>\r\n<br/></li>\r\n<li>\\(H\\) has the form \\(\\lnot H_1\\). Then \\(H\'=\\lnot H_1\'\\) where \\(H_1\'\\) arises from substituting \\(G\\) for one of the occurrence of \\(F\\) in \\(H_1\\). By the induction hypothesis we have \\(H_1\\equiv H_1\'\\) and thus \\(H\\equiv H\'\\).<br/>\r\n<br/></li>\r\n<li>\\(H\\) has the form \\(H_1\\land H_2\\), without loss of generality assume the substitution occurrence of \\(F\\) occurs in \\(H_1\\). Then \\(H\'=H_1\'\\land H_2\'\\) where \\(H_1\'\\) arises by substituting \\(G\\) for \\(F\\) and \\(H_2\'=H_2\\). By the induction hypothesis we have \\(H_1\\equiv H_1\'\\), thus \\(H\\equiv H\'\\).<br/>\r\n<br/></li>\r\n<li>\\(H\\) has the form \\(H_1\\lor H_2\\), without loss of generality assume the substitution occurrence of \\(F\\) occurs in \\(H_1\\). Then \\(H\'=H_1\'\\lor H_2\'\\) where \\(H_1\'\\) arises by substituting \\(G\\) for \\(F\\) and \\(H_2\'=H_2\\). By the induction hypothesis we have \\(H_1\\equiv H_1\'\\), thus \\(H\\equiv H\'\\).</li>\r\n</ul>',451),(210,'','\\((1\\Rightarrow2)\\)<br/>\r\nSuppose \\((x_n)\\) converges to \\(a\\in X\\), let \\(U\\) be an open set containing \\(a\\). As \\(U\\) is open, \\(\\exists\\epsilon\\gt0\\) s.t. \\(B(a,\\epsilon)\\subset U\\). So as \\((x_n)\\) is convergent, \\(\\exists N\\in\\mathbb N\\) s.t. \\(\\forall n\\geq N\\), \\(d(x_n,a)\\lt\\epsilon\\), so \\(x_n\\in B(a,\\epsilon)\\subset U\\).<br/>\r\n<br/>\r\n\\((2\\Rightarrow1)\\)<br/>\r\nFor any \\(\\epsilon\\gt0\\), \\(B(a,\\epsilon)\\) is open, so \\(\\exists N\\in\\mathbb N\\) s.t. \\(\\forall n\\geq N\\), \\(x_n\\in B(a,\\epsilon)\\), so \\(d(x_n,a)\\lt\\epsilon\\). So \\((x_n)\\) is convergent to \\(a\\in X\\).',453),(211,'','\\((\\Rightarrow)\\)<br/>\r\nSuppose \\(f\\) is continuous, let \\((x_n)\\) be a sequence converging to \\(x_0\\). Let \\(\\epsilon\\gt0\\), then \\(\\exists\\delta\\gt0\\) s.t. \\(d(x,x_0)\\lt\\delta\\Longrightarrow d(f(x),f(x_0))\\lt\\epsilon\\), then \\(\\exists N\\in\\mathbb N\\) s.t. \\(n\\geq N\\Longrightarrow d(x_n,x_0)\\lt\\delta\\).<br/>\r\nSo \\(\\forall n\\geq N\\), \\(d(f(x),f(x_0))\\lt\\epsilon\\), so \\((f(x_n))\\) converges to \\(f(x_0)\\).<br/>\r\n<br/>\r\n\\((\\Leftarrow)\\)<br/>\r\nSuppose that \\(f\\) is not continuous at some point \\(x_0\\in X\\), then \\(\\exists\\epsilon\\gt0\\) s.t. \\(\\forall\\delta\\gt0\\), \\(\\exists x\\in X\\) s.t. \\(d(x,x_0)\\lt\\delta\\) but \\(d(f(x),f(x_0))\\geq\\epsilon\\). So \\(\\forall n\\in\\mathbb N\\), \\(\\exists x_n\\in B(x_0,{1\\over n})\\) s.t. \\(f(x_n)\\not\\in B(f(x_0),\\epsilon)\\).<br/>\r\nThen \\((x_n)\\) as above converges to \\(x_0\\) while \\((f(x_n))\\) does not converge to \\(f(x_0)\\).',454),(212,'','\\((\\Rightarrow)\\)<br/>\r\nLet \\(F\\subset X\\) be closed, \\((x_n)\\in F\\) converges to \\(x_0\\in X\\). Suppose \\(x_0\\not\\in F\\), then \\(x_0\\in X\\setminus F\\) which is open, so \\(\\exists\\epsilon\\gt0\\) s.t. \\(B(x_0,\\epsilon)\\subset X\\setminus F\\). But \\(\\exists N\\in\\mathbb N\\) s.t. \\(\\forall n\\geq N\\), \\(x_n\\in B(x_0,\\epsilon)\\), this is a contradiction as \\(x_n\\in F\\).<br/>\r\n<br/>\r\nSuppose \\(F\\) is not closed, then \\(X\\setminus F\\) is not open, so \\(\\exists x_0\\in X\\setminus F\\) s.t. \\(\\forall\\epsilon\\gt0\\), \\(B(x_0,\\epsilon)\\not\\subset X\\setminus F\\). So \\(\\forall n\\in\\mathbb N\\), \\(\\exists x_n\\in F\\) s.t. \\(d(x_0,x_n)\\lt{1\\over n}\\). Then \\((x_n)\\) converges to \\(x_0\\) and \\(x_0\\not\\in F\\).',455),(213,'','\\((\\Rightarrow)\\)<br/>\r\nSuppose \\((A,d)\\) is complete, \\((x_n)\\in A\\) converges to \\(x_0\\in X\\). Since it converges, it\'s Cauchy, so as \\(A\\) is complete, \\((x_n)\\) converges to a point in \\(A\\). Hence by uniqueness of limits, \\(x_0\\in A\\). So \\(A\\) contains its limit points, so it is closed.<br/>\r\n<br/>\r\n\\((\\Leftarrow)\\)<br/>\r\nSuppose \\(A\\) is closed, let \\((x_n)\\) be a Cauchy sequence in \\(A\\). Since \\(X\\) is complete, \\((x_n)\\) converges to some \\(x_0\\in X\\), but \\(A\\) contains its limit points, so \\(x_0\\in A\\). So \\(A\\) is complete.',460),(214,'','It suffices to show that if \\((f_n)\\) is a sequence in \\(C_b(X,\\mathbb R)\\) that converges to \\(f\\in\\mathbb B(X,\\mathbb R)\\), then \\(f\\in C_b(X,\\mathbb R)\\). So we want to show that \\(f\\) is continuous at all \\(x_0\\in X\\).<br/>\r\nBy definition of convergence\r\n\\[\\forall\\epsilon\\gt0, \\exists N\\in\\mathbb N s.t. \\forall n\\gt N, \\|f_n-f\\|_\\infty=\\sup_{x\\in X}|f_n(x)-f(x)|\\lt{\\epsilon\\over3}\\]\r\nIn particular, \\(\\sup_{x\\in X}|f_N(x)-f(x)|\\lt{\\epsilon\\over3}\\). Since \\(f_N\\) is continuous at \\(x_0\\), we know\r\n\\[\\exists\\delta\\gt0 s.t. \\forall x\\in X s.t. d(x,x_0)\\lt\\delta, |f_N(x)-f_N(x_0)|\\lt{\\epsilon\\over3}\\]\r\nSo, putting these together, \\(\\forall x\\in X\\) s.t. \\(d(x,x_0)\\lt\\delta\\),\r\n\\[|f(x)-f(x_0)|\\leq|f(x)-f(x_0)|+|f_N(x)-f_X(x_0)|+|f_X(x_0)-f(x_0)|\\lt\\epsilon\\]',465),(215,'','Follows from:\r\n<ul>\r\n<li>\\((\\mathbb B(X,\\mathbb R),d_\\infty)\\) is complete</li>\r\n<li>\\(C_b(X,\\mathbb R)\\) is a closed subset of \\(\\mathbb B(X,\\mathbb R)\\)</li>\r\n<li>A closed subset of a complete space is complete</li>\r\n</ul>',466),(216,'','Let \\(\\epsilon\\gt0\\), set \\(\\delta={\\epsilon\\over K}\\) in the definition.',469),(217,'','\\((\\Rightarrow)\\)<br/>\r\nLet \\(a,b\\in I\\), with \\(a\\lt b\\), then by  the mean value theorem, \\(\\exists c\\in(a,b)\\) s.t. \\(f\'(c)={f(b)-f(a)\\over b-a}\\), so \\(|{f(b)-f(a)\\over b-a}|\\leq M\\), so \\(|f(b)-f(a)|\\leq M|b-a|\\).<br/>\r\n<br/><br/>\r\n\\((\\Leftarrow)\\)<br/>\r\nSuppose \\(|f\'(x)|\\) is not bounded, so \\(forall M\\gt0\\), \\(\\exists x\\in I\\) s.t. \\(|f\'(x)|\\geq2M\\), but \\(f\'(x)=\\lim_{h\\to0}{f(x+h)-f(x)\\over h}\\). So \\(f\\) is not \\(M\\)-Lipschitz for any \\(M\\gt0\\)',470),(218,'','<ol>\r\n<li>Straight from the definition that \\(A\\subset B\\Longrightarrow m^*(A)\\leq m^*(B)\\)<br/><br/></li>\r\n<li>Since \\(E_n\\) is null, with \\(\\epsilon\\gt0\\), there exist countably many intervals \\(I_{r,n}\\) such that \\(E_n\\subset\\bigcup_{r=1}^\\infty I_{r,n}\\) and \\(\\sum_{r=1}^\\infty m(I_{r,n})\\lt 2^{-n}\\epsilon\\). Now \\(\\bigcup_{n=1}^\\infty E_n\\subset\\bigcup_{n,r=1}^\\infty I_{r,n}\\) and \\(\\{I_{r,n}:r,n\\in\\mathbb N\\}\\) is countable, so \\(m^*(\\bigcup_{n=1}^\\infty E_n)\\leq\\sum_{n,r=1}^\\infty m^*(I_{r,n})\\lt\\sum_{n=1}^\\infty 2^{-n}\\epsilon=\\epsilon\\). Hence \\(m^*(\\bigcup_{n=1}^\\infty E_n)=0\\)<br/><br/></li>\r\n<li>A single point is null, and a countable union of null sets is null.</li>\r\n</ol>',476),(219,'','Any open set is a countable union of open intervals.',480),(220,'','<ol>\r\n<li>\\(B=A\\cup(B\\setminus A)\\) and it\'s a disjoint union, so \\(\\mu(B)=\\mu(A)+\\mu(B\\setminus A)\\geq\\mu(A)\\)<br/><br/></li>\r\n<li>Let \\(A\'_1=A_1\\), \\(A\'_n=A_n\\setminus A_{n-1}\\) for \\(n\\geq2\\). Then \\(A_n\'\\cap A_m\'=\\emptyset\\) for \\(n\\neq m\\), \\(A_n=\\bigcup_{r=1}^n A_r\'\\) and hence \\(\\bigcup_{n=1}^\\infty A_n\'=\\bigcup_{n=1}^\\infty A_n\\). So \\(\\mu(A_n)=\\sum_{r=1}^n\\mu(A_r\')\\) and \\(\\mu(\\bigcup_{n=1}^\\infty A_n)=\\sum_{n=1}^\\infty\\mu(A_n\')=\\lim_{n\\to\\infty}\\sum_{r=1}^n\\mu(A_r\')=\\lim_{n\\to\\infty}\\mu(A_n)\\)</li>\r\n</ol>',483),(221,'','We use induction on \\(n=\\deg(f(x))\\).<br/>\r\n<ul>\r\n<li><b>Base case</b>: \\(n=1\\) is trivial</li>\r\n<li><b>Inductive case</b>: Suppose it is true for all \\(f\\in F[X]\\) such that \\(\\deg(f)\\lt n\\) over any field.<br/>\r\nFactorize \\(f(x)\\) as \\(g(x)h(x)\\) where \\(g(x)\\) is irreducible in \\(F[X]\\). Now let \\(A=(g(x))\\) be the ideal of \\(F[X]\\) generated by \\(g(x)\\). Since \\(g(x)\\) is irreducible, \\(A\\) is a maximal ideal in \\(F[X]\\), so \\(E={F[X]\\over A}\\) is a field. In \\(E\\), let \\(a_1=x+A\\), then \\(g(a_1)=0\\). Now in \\(E[X]\\), \\(f(x)=(x-a_1)f_1(x)\\) where \\(f_1(x)\\in E[X]\\) has degree \\(n-1\\). By the inductive hypothesis, there exists \\(K\\), a splitting field of \\(f_1(x)\\) over \\(E\\). Then \\(K\\) is a splitting field of \\(f(x)\\) over \\(F\\).</li>\r\n</ul>\r\n<br/>\r\nTo prove that \\(|K:F|\\) divides \\(n!\\), again inducting on \\(n\\), there are two cases:\r\n<ul>\r\n<li>\\(f(x)\\) is irreducible in \\(F[X]\\), then \\(|E:F|=n\\), \\(|K:E|\\) divides \\((n-1)!\\) by the inductive hypothesis, so by the Tower theorem, \\(|K:F|\\) divides \\(n!\\).<br/></li>\r\n<li>\\(f(x)\\) is reducible, \\(f(x)=g(x)h(x)\\) in \\(F[X]\\), \\(m=\\deg(g(x))\\) so \\(m\\lt n\\). Now let \\(L\\) be the splitting field of \\(g(x)\\) over \\(F\\), \\(K\\) be the splitting field of \\(h(x)\\) over \\(L\\). So \\(K\\) is the splitting field of \\(f(x)\\) over \\(F\\). Then \\(|K:F|=|K:L|\\times|L:F|\\). By the inductive hypothesis, \\(|K:L|\\) divides \\((n-m)!\\), \\(|L:F|\\) divides \\(m!\\). Then \\(|K:F|\\) divides \\(m!(n-m)!\\), but as we know \\({n!\\over m!(n-m)!}={n\\choose m}\\in\\mathbb N\\), \\(|K:F|\\) divides \\(n!\\).</li>\r\n</ul>',490),(222,'','Let \\((f_n)\\) be a Cauchy sequence in \\(\\mathbb B(S,\\mathbb R)\\), then\r\n\\[\\forall\\epsilon\\gt0,\\exists N\\in\\mathbb N&nbsp;s.t.&nbsp;\\forall n,m\\geq N, d_\\infty(f_n,f_m)\\lt\\epsilon\\]\r\n\\[and&nbsp;d_\\infty(f_n,f_m)=\\|f_n-f_m\\|_\\infty=\\sup_{s\\in S}|f_n(s)-f_m(s)|\\lt\\epsilon\\]\r\nFor \\(s\\in S\\), \\((f_n(s))\\) is a Cauchy sequence in \\(\\mathbb R\\), since \\(\\mathbb R\\) is complete this sequence converges to a limit as \\(n\\to\\infty\\), call this limit \\(f(s)\\), this gives a function \\(f:S\\to\\mathbb R\\).<br/>\r\n<br/>\r\nWe want that \\(f\\in\\mathbb B(S,\\mathbb R)\\). Fix some \\(\\epsilon\\gt0\\), \\(n\\geq N\\) so that\r\n\\[\\forall m\\geq N,\\forall s\\in S,|f_n(s)-f_m(s)|\\lt\\epsilon\\]\r\nThen letting \\(m\\to\\infty\\), for all \\(s\\in S\\),\r\n\\[|f_n(s)-f_m(s)|\\leq\\epsilon\\Longrightarrow|f(s)|\\leq|f_n(s)-f(s)|+|f_n(s)|\\leq\\epsilon+\\|f_n\\|\\]\r\nso \\(f\\) is bounded.<br/>\r\n<br/>\r\nNow we want that \\((f_n)\\) actually converges to \\(f\\). We know that\r\n\\[\\forall\\epsilon\\gt0,\\exists N\\in\\mathbb N&nbsp;s.t.&nbsp;\\forall n\\geq N,\\forall s\\in S,|f_n(s)-f(s)|\\lt\\epsilon\\]\r\nTherefore \\(n\\geq N\\Longrightarrow\\|f_n-f\\|_\\infty\\lt\\epsilon\\), so \\((f_n)\\to f\\).',461),(223,'','First we\'ll prove the existence of a fixed point.<br/>\r\nLet \\(x_0\\in X\\), define \\((x_n)\\) by \\(x_n=f(x_{n-1})\\) for \\(n\\gt0\\). Use the inductive hypothesis that \\(d(x_{n+1},x_n)\\leq K^nd(x_1,x_0)\\).\r\n<ul>\r\n<li><b>Base case:</b> clearly true for \\(n=0\\)</li>\r\n<li><b>Inductive step:</b> Assume true for \\(n\\), then\r\n\\[d(x_{n+2},x_{n+1})=d(f(x_{n+1}),f(x_n))\\leq Kd(x_{n+1},x_n)\\leq K^{n+1}d(x_1,x_0)\\]\r\nSo for \\(m\\geq n\\geq N\\),\r\n\\[d(x_n,x_m)\\leq d(x_n,d_{n+1})+d(x_{n+1},x_{n+2})+...+d(x_{m-1},d_m)\\]\r\n\\[\\leq(K^n+K^{n+1}+...+K^{m-1})d(x_1,x_0)={K^n-K^m\\over1-K}d(x_1,x_0)\\leq{K^N\\over1-K}d(x_1,x_0)\\]\r\nSo for any \\(\\epsilon\\gt0\\), \\(\\exists N\\in\\mathbb N\\) s.t. \\({K^N\\over1-K}d(x_1,x_0)\\lt\\epsilon\\), so \\((x_n)\\) is Cauchy and hence converges to some point \\(p\\in X\\).<br/>\r\n<br/>\r\nFrom the equality \\(x_n=f(x_{n-1})\\) and by taking limits as \\(n\\to\\infty\\), \\(p=f(p)\\).</li>\r\n</ul>\r\n<br/><br/>\r\nTo show that \\(p\\) is unique, suppose \\(q\\) is another fixed point, then\r\n\\[d(p,q)=d(f(p),f(q))\\leq Kd(p,q)\\]\r\nso \\(d(p,q)=0\\), so \\(p=q\\).<br/>\r\n<br/>\r\nFinally, \\(d(x_n,x_m)\\leq{K^n\\over1-K}d(x_1,x_0)\\), letting \\(m\\to\\infty\\), \\(d(x_n,p)\\leq{K^n\\over1-K}d(x_1,x_0)\\).',473),(224,'','<ul>\r\n<li>Satisfies the axioms as everything is in \\(T\\)</li>\r\n<li>Vacuously satisfies the axioms</li>\r\n<li>\\(\\emptyset\\in T\\) and \\(X\\in T\\) clearly.<br/>\r\n\\(A_i\\in T\\) for \\(i\\in I\\Longrightarrow\\bigcup_{i\\in I}A_i\\in T\\) as \\(X\\setminus\\bigcup_{i\\in I}A_i=\\bigcap_{i\\in I}(X\\setminus A_i)\\) which must be finite as it\'s the intersection of finite sets.<br/>\r\n\\(A,B\\in T\\Longrightarrow A\\cap B\\in T\\) as \\(X\\setminus(A\\cap B)=(X\\setminus A)\\cup(X\\setminus B)\\) is finite as it\'s the union of two finite sets.</li>\r\n</ul>',495),(225,'','Suppose not, then \\(s\\in X\\setminus F\\) which is open, so \\(\\exists N\\in\\mathbb N\\) s.t. \\(\\forall n\\geq N\\), \\(x_n\\in X\\setminus S\\). But \\((x_n)\\in F\\), so this is a contradiction.',499),(226,'','\\((a)\\Rightarrow(b)\\) is trivial, just set \\(U_x=U\\)</br/>\r\n<br/>\r\nFor \\((b)\\Rightarrow(a)\\), suppose \\(\\forall x\\in U\\), there exists an open set \\(U_x\\) s.t. \\(x\\in U_x\\subset U\\). Then \\(\\bigcup_{x\\in U}U_x=U\\) and an arbitrary union of open sets is open, hence \\(U\\) is open.',500),(227,'','Let \\(n=|G|\\), Lagrange\'s theorem states that \\(a^n=1\\) for all \\(a\\in G\\).<br/>\r\n<br/>\r\nFactorize \\(n=p_1^{r_1}p_2^{r_2}...p_k^{r_k}\\) where \\(p_1,...,p_k\\) are distinct primes and all \\(r_1,...,r_k\\gt0\\). Define \\(n_i={n\\over p_i}\\), then the equation \\(x^{n_i}-1\\) has at most \\(n_i\\) roots in \\(K\\). So there exists \\(a_i\\in G\\), \\(a_i^{n_i}\\neq1\\), so \\(ord(a_i)\\) is divisible by \\(p_i^{r_i}\\).<br/>\r\n<br/>\r\nLet \\(ord(a_i)=p_i^{r_i}m_i\\), define \\(b_i=a_i^{m_i}\\), then \\(ord(b_i)=p_i^{r_i}\\). Now let \\(b=b_1b_2...b_k\\), want to show that \\(ord(b)=n\\). Certainly it divides \\(n\\)<br/>\r\n<br/>\r\nLet \\(q_i={n\\over p_i^{r_i}}=\\prod_{j\\neq i}p_j^{r_j}\\), then \\(hcf(p_i^{r_i},q_i)=1\\), so \\(\\exists u_i,v_i\\in\\mathbb Z\\) s.t. \\(u_ip_i^{r_i}+v_iq_i=1\\). Then \\(b^{v_iq_i}=b_1{v_iq_i}...b_k^{v_iq_i}=b_i^{v_iq_i}=b_i^{1-u_ip_i^{r_i}}=b_i\\). So \\(b_i=b^{v_iq_i}\\) so \\(ord(b)\\) is divisible by \\(p_i^{r_i}\\).<br/>\r\n<br/>\r\nAs that was for all \\(i\\), \\(\\prod_{i=1}^kp_i^{r_i}\\) divides \\(ord(b)\\), so \\(n\\) divides \\(ord(b)\\). Therefore \\(n=ord(b)\\), so \\(b\\) is a generator for \\(G\\), so \\(G\\) is cyclic.',503),(228,'','Let \\(U\\) be an arbitrary open set in \\(Y\\) containing \\(f(x)\\), then \\(f^{-1}(U)\\) is an open set in \\(X\\) containing \\(x\\). So \\(\\exists N\\in\\mathbb N\\) s.t. \\(\\forall n\\geq N\\), \\(x_n\\in f^{-1}(U)\\), so \\(\\forall n\\geq N\\), \\(f(x)\\in U\\). So \\((f(x_n))\\) converges to \\(f(x)\\).',509),(229,'','<ol>\r\n<li>\\(A\\subset B\\subset\\overline B\\), so \\(\\overline B\\) is a closed set containing \\(A\\), so \\(\\overline A\\subset\\overline B\\) as \\(\\overline A\\) is minimal.<br/>\r\n<br/>\r\n</li>\r\n<li>Suppose \\(A\\) is closed, then \\(A\\subset\\overline A\\), but \\(A\\) is a closed set containing \\(A\\), so \\(\\overline A\\subset A\\), hence \\(A=\\overline A\\).<br/>\r\n<br/>\r\nSuppose \\(A=\\overline A\\), then trivially \\(A\\) is closed as \\(\\overline A\\) is closed.<br/>\r\n<br/>\r\n</li>\r\n<li>\\(\\overline A\\) is closed, so \\(\\overline{(\\overline A)}=\\overline A\\)</li>\r\n</ol>',510),(230,'','Let \\(A_1=\\{x\\in X:x\\in U\\ and\\ U\\ is\\ open\\Longrightarrow A\\cap U\\neq\\emptyset\\}\\).<br/>\r\n<br/>\r\nClearly \\(A\\subset A_1\\). So consider \\(X\\setminus A_1=\\{x\\in X:\\exists U\\subset X s.t. U is open, x\\in U and A\\cap U=\\emptyset\\}\\). So if \\(U_x\\) is such an open set, then \\(\\forall y\\in U_x\\), \\(y\\in X\\setminus A_1\\), so \\(U_x\\subset X\\setminus A_1\\), so \\(A_1\\) is closed. Therefore \\(\\overline A\\subset A_1\\) as \\(\\overline A\\) is minimal.<br/>\r\n<br/>\r\nSuppose that \\(A_1\\not\\subset\\overline A\\), so \\(\\exists x\\in A_1\\setminus\\overline A\\), so \\(x\\in X\\setminus\\overline A\\). Then \\(X\\setminus\\overline A\\) is an open set containing \\(x\\) s.t. \\((X\\setminus\\overline A)\\cap A=\\emptyset\\). So this contradicts \\(x\\in A_1\\). Therefore \\(A_1\\subset\\overline A\\).',511),(231,'','Let \\(\\mathbb G=\\{G\\subset\\mathbb R:f^{-1}(G)\\in F\\}\\), then \\(\\mathbb G\\) is a \\(\\sigma\\)-algebra, since \\(f^{-1}(\\mathbb R\\setminus G)=\\Omega\\setminus f^{-1}(G)\\), \\(f^{-1}(\\bigcup_{n=1}^\\infty G_n)=\\bigcup_{n=1}^\\infty f^{-1}(G_n)\\). Hence if \\(\\mathbb B\\subset\\mathbb G\\), then \\(F_B\\subset\\mathbb G\\). Then the proposition about generating \\(M_{Bor}\\) applies.',488),(232,'','<ol>\r\n<li>\\((\\sup_{n\\geq1}f_n)^{-1}(a,\\infty)=\\bigcup_{n=1}^\\infty f_n^{-1}(a,\\infty)\\), a countable union of measurable sets.</li>\r\n<li>\\(\\inf_{n\\geq1}f_n=-\\sup_{n\\geq1}(-f_n)\\)</li>\r\n<li>\\(\\limsup_{n\\to\\infty}f_n=\\inf_{m\\geq1}g_m\\) where \\(g_m=\\sup_{n\\geq m}f_n\\), hence \\(\\limsup_{n\\to\\infty}f_n\\) is measurable.</li>\r\n<li>\\(\\liminf_{n\\to\\infty}f_n=-\\limsup_{n\\to\\infty}(-f_n)\\)</li>\r\n</ol>',519),(233,'','For \\(n=1,2,3,...\\), \\(k=0,1,2,...,4^n-1\\), let\r\n\\[B_{n,k}=\\{x\\in\\mathbb R:k2^{-n}\\leq f(x)\\lt(k+1)2^{-n}\\}\\]\r\nthen define\r\n\\[\\phi_n(x)=\\left\\{\\begin{array}{ll}k2^{-n}&&if x\\in B_{n,k} for k=0,...,4^n-1\\\\2^n&&if f(x)\\geq2^n\\end{array}\\right.\\]\r\nThen \\(\\phi_n(x)\\leq\\phi_{n+1}(x)\\) for all \\(x\\in\\mathbb R\\), \\(\\phi_n\\leq f\\) but \\(\\phi_n(x)\\gt f(x)-2^{-n}\\) for sufficiently large \\(n\\), if \\(f(x)\\lt\\infty\\), \\(\\phi_n(x)=2^n\\) if \\(f(x)=\\infty\\).<br/>\r\n<br/>\r\nTherefore \\(\\lim_{n\\to\\infty}\\phi_n(x)=f(x)\\) for all \\(x\\in\\mathbb R\\).',523),(234,'','Apply the MCT to \\(f_n=f\\cdot\\chi_{E_n}\\), so \\(f_n\\leq f_{n+1}\\) and \\(\\lim_{n\\to\\infty}\\chi_{E_n}(x)=\\chi_E(x)\\), so \\(\\lim_{n\\to\\infty}f_n(x)=(f\\cdot\\chi_E)(x)\\).',530),(235,'','Let \\(n=|F:\\mathbb F_p|\\) where \\(\\mathbb F_p\\) is the prime subfield of \\(F\\). Then as a vector space \\(F\\) is isomorphic to \\((\\mathbb F_p)^n\\), so we know \\(|F|=p^n\\).',532),(236,'','In the multiplicative group \\(F^\\times\\) which has \\(q-1\\) elements, \\(a^{q-1}=1\\) by Lagrange\'s theorem. Therefore \\(a^q=a\\) for all \\(a\\neq0\\) and \\(0^q=0\\) trivially.',533),(237,'','First, \r\n\\[(x+y)^p=x^p+y^p+\\sum_{m=1}^{p-1}{p\\choose m}x^{p-m}y^m\\]\r\nnote that \\({p\\choose m}={p!\\over m!(p-m)!}\\in\\mathbb Z\\) and there is no factor of \\(p\\) on the bottom, so \\(p\\choose m\\) is divisible by \\(p\\). Therefore \\((x+y)^p=x^p+y^p\\) as any multiple of \\(p\\) ie equal to \\(0\\) in the ring.<br/>\r\n<br/>\r\nNow, if \\((x+y)^{p^{r-1}}=x^{p^{r-1}}+y^{p^{r-1}}\\), then\r\n\\[(x+y)^{p^r}=((x+y)^{p^{r-1}})^p=(x^{p^{r-1}}+y^{p^{r-1}})^p=x^{p^r}+y^{p^r}\\]',534),(238,'','Let \\(K\\) be a splitting field for \\(x^q-x\\) over \\(\\mathbb F_p\\). Let \\(F=\\{a\\in K:a^q=a\\}\\).<br/>\r\n<br/>\r\nNow, we know that\r\n<ul>\r\n<li>\\(0,1\\in F\\)</li>\r\n<li>If \\(a,b\\in F\\), then \\((a+b)^q=a^q+b^q=a+b\\) by the previous proposition, so \\(a+b\\in F\\)</li>\r\n<li>If \\(a,b\\in F\\), then \\((ab)^q=a^qb^q=ab\\), so \\(ab\\in F\\)</li>\r\n<li>If \\(a\\neq0\\), then \\((a^{-1})^q=(a^q)^{-1}=a^{-1}\\), so \\(a^{-1}\\in F\\)</li>\r\n</ul>\r\nHence \\(F\\) is a subfield of \\(K\\), therefore \\(F=K\\).<br/>\r\n<br/>\r\nClearly \\(|F|\\leq q\\).<br/>\r\nLet \\(D:\\mathbb F_p[X]\\to\\mathbb F_p[X]\\) be the formal derivative. Since \\(D(x^q-x)=qx^{q-1}-1=-1\\), \\(hcf(x^q-x,D(x^q-x))=1\\). Therefore the roots of \\(x^q-x\\) in its splitting field are distinct. So \\(|F|=q\\).',535),(239,'','We know that \\(F^\\times\\) is cyclic, let \\(a\\) be the generator, then \\(F=\\mathbb F_p(a)\\).<br/>\r\n<br/>\r\nLet \\(f(x)\\in\\mathbb F_p[X]\\) be the minimum polynomial of \\(a\\) over \\(\\mathbb F_p\\). But we know that \\(a^q-a=0\\), so \\(f(x)\\) divides \\(x^q-x\\) as a polynomial in \\(\\mathbb F_p[X]\\).<br/>\r\n<br/>\r\nIn \\(K\\), the polynomial \\(x^q-x\\) splits, but \\(f(x)\\) divides \\(x^q-x\\), so \\(K\\) is a splitting field for \\(K\\).<br/>\r\n<br/>\r\nChoose \\(b\\in K\\) s.t. \\(f(b)=0\\), then \\(\\mathbb F_p(b)\\leq K\\) with \\(|\\mathbb F_p(b):\\mathbb F_p|=deg(f(x))=n\\). Hence \\(K=\\mathbb F_p(b)\\).<br/>\r\n<br/>\r\nSo now \\(K\\cong{\\mathbb F_p[X]\\over(f(x))}\\) and by symetry \\(F\\cong{\\mathbb F_p[X]\\over(f(x))}\\), so \\(F\\cong K\\).',536),(240,'','Let \\(\\mathbb F_p\\leq K\\leq F\\) where \\(|F|=p^n\\) and \\(|K|=p^m\\) for some \\(m\\). By the tower theorem, \\(|F:\\mathbb F_p|=|F:K|\\times|K:\\mathbb F_p|\\), so \\(n=|F:K|\\times m\\), so \\(m\\) divides \\(n\\).<br/>\r\n<br/>\r\nLet \\(m|n\\), say \\(n=mk\\), then \\(p^n=(p^m)^k\\) so \\(p^{m-1}|p^{n-1}\\).<br/>\r\nTherefore \\(x^{p^m-1}-1\\) as a polynomial divides \\(x^{p^n-1}-1\\). So \\(x^{p^m}-x\\) divides \\(x^{p^n}-x\\) in \\(\\mathbb F_p[X]\\).<br/>\r\nLet \\(F=\\{a\\in\\mathbb F_q:a^{p^m}=a\\}\\), then \\(|F|=p^m\\) since \\(x^{p^n}-x\\) splits in \\(\\mathbb F_q\\).<br/>\r\nTherefore \\(x^{p^m}-x\\) splits in \\(\\mathbb F_q\\), so \\(F\\) is a subfield of \\(\\mathbb F_q\\) and \\(F\\cong\\mathbb F_{p^m}\\).',537),(241,'','<b>(Proof of 2)</b><br/>\r\nLet \\(B_l\\) be the set of limits of pairwise distinct sequences.<br/>\r\n<br/>\r\nLet \\(x\\in B_l\\), \\((a_n)\\) be the appropriate sequence converging to \\(x\\). At most one of these points is \\(x\\) as they\'re all distinct, without loss of generality remove this term from the sequence if necessary.<br/>\r\nLet \\(U\\subset X\\) be an open set containing \\(x\\), then \\(\\exists N\\in\\mathbb N\\) s.t. \\(\\forall n\\geq N\\), \\(a_n\\in U\\). But \\(a_n\\neq x\\), so \\(a_n\\in U\\setminus\\{x\\}\\), so \\((U\\setminus\\{x\\})\\cap A\\neq\\emptyset\\), so \\(x\\in A\'\\).<br/>\r\nTherefore \\(B_l\\subset A\'\\).<br/>\r\n<br/>\r\nNow, let \\(x\\in A\'\\), construct a sequence \\((a_n)\\) s.t. \\(d(x,a_{n+1})\\lt d(x,a_n)\\), \\(d(x,a_n)\\lt{1\\over n}\\) and for all \\(n\\), \\(a_n\\neq x\\). Hence \\((a_n)\\) converges to \\(x\\) and \\(n\\neq m\\Rightarrow a_n\\neq a_m\\).<br/>\r\nSince \\(x\\in A\'\\), \\(\\exists a_1\\in(B(x,1)\\setminus\\{x\\})\\cap A\\). Then, assuming we\'ve found \\(a_1,...,a_n\\), let \\(r_{n+1}=\\min\\{d(x,a_n),{1\\over n+1}\\}\\), since \\(x\\in A\'\\), \\(\\exists a_{n+1}\\in(B(x,r_{n+1})\\setminus\\{x\\})\\cap A\\). So \\(x\\in B_l\\).<br/>\r\nTherefore \\(A\'\\subset B_l\\).',515),(242,'','\\((\\Rightarrow)\\)<br/>\r\nSuppose \\(f\\) is continuous, let \\(A\\subset X\\). Since \\(\\overline{f(A)}\\) is closed, so is \\(f^{-1}(\\overline{f(A)})\\), and since \\(A\\subset f^{-1}(\\overline{f(A)})\\), we have \\(\\overline A\\subset f^{-1}(\\overline{f(A)})\\). Therefore \\(f(\\overline A)\\subset\\overline{f(A)}\\).<br/>\r\n<br/>\r\n\\((\\Leftarrow)\\)<br/>\r\nSuppose that \\(f(\\overline A)\\subset\\overline{f(A)}\\) for all \\(A\\subset X\\). Let \\(F\\subset Y\\) be closed, let \\(A=f^{-1}(F)\\). Since \\(f(A)=F\\), \\(\\overline{f(A)}=\\overline F=F\\), so \\(f(\\overline A)\\subset\\overline{f(A)}=F\\). So \\(\\overline A\\subset f^{-1}(F)=A\\), so \\(A=\\overline A\\), so \\(A\\) is closed. Therefore \\(f\\) is continuous.',538),(243,'','\\((\\leftarrow)\\)<br/>\r\nSuppose all singleton sets are closed, \\(a,b\\in X\\) with \\(a\\neq b\\), then \\(X\\setminus\\{b\\}\\) is open and contains \\(a\\) but not \\(b\\).<br/>\r\n<br/>\r\n\\((\\Rightarrow)\\)<br/>\r\nSuppose \\(X\\) satisfies the 1st separation axiom, \\(x\\in X\\). Let \\(A=\\bigcup_{a\\in X\\setminus\\{x\\}}U_a\\) where each \\(U_a\\) is open and contains \\(a\\) but not \\(x\\). Then \\(A\\) is the union of open sets, so \\(A=X\\setminus\\{x\\}\\) is open, so \\(\\{x\\}\\) is closed.',545),(244,'','Suppose not, say \\((x_n)\\) converges to both \\(a\\) and to \\(b\\) where \\(a\\neq b\\). Then, there exist disjoint open subsets \\(U,V\\) of \\(X\\) s.t. \\(a\\in U\\) and \\(b\\in V\\). Then\r\n\\[\\exists N_1\\in\\mathbb N,&nbsp;s.t.&nbsp;\\forall n\\geq N_1,&nbsp;x_n\\in U\\]\r\n\\[\\exists N_2\\in\\mathbb N,&nbsp;s.t.&nbsp;\\forall n\\geq N_2,&nbsp;x_n\\in V\\]\r\nThen \\(\\forall n\\geq\\max(N_1,N_2)\\), \\(x\\in U\\cap V=\\emptyset\\) which is contradiction.',548),(245,'','\\[\\Phi(a,b)=(ab)^p=a^pb^p=\\Phi(a)\\Phi(b)\\]\r\n\\[\\Phi(a+b)=(a+b)^p=a^p+b^p=\\Phi(a)+\\Phi(b)\\]\r\n\\[ker(\\Phi)=\\{a\\in F:ap=0\\}=\\{0\\}\\]',550),(246,'','Note that \\(S=\\{a\\in\\mathbb F_{p^n}:\\mathbb F_{p^n}=\\mathbb F_p(a)\\}\\) and that for every one of these the minimal polynomial is irreducible and of degree \\(n\\) over \\(\\mathbb F_p\\). But each one has \\(n\\) roots in \\(S\\). So the number of irreducible polynomials of degree \\(n\\) over \\(\\mathbb F_p\\) is \\({1\\over n}|S|\\).',551),(247,'','Since \\(f_n\\leq f_{n+1}\\leq f\\), \\(\\int f_n\\leq\\int f_{n+1}\\leq\\int f\\), it is immediate that\r\n\\[\\lim_{n\\to\\infty}\\sup_{n\\geq1}\\int f_n\\leq\\int f\\]\r\nFor the reverse inequality, let \\(\\phi\\) be a simple function such that \\(0\\leq\\phi\\leq f\\). We shall show that \\(\\int\\phi\\leq\\lim_{n\\to\\infty}\\int f_n\\), it then follows by definition that \\(\\int f\\leq\\lim_{n\\to\\infty}\\int f_n\\).<br/>\r\n<br/>\r\nTake \\(\\alpha\\in(0,1)\\), let \\(B_n=\\{x\\in\\mathbb R:f_n(x)\\geq\\alpha\\phi(x)\\}\\), then \\(B_n\\) is measurable as \\(B_n=(f_n-\\alpha\\phi)^{-1}[0,\\infty)\\) and \\(f_n-\\alpha\\phi\\) is measurable. \\(B_n\\subset B_{n+1}\\) since \\(f_n\\leq f_{n+1}\\) and \\(\\bigcup_{n=1}^\\infty B_n=\\mathbb R\\), so either \\(\\phi(x)=0\\) so \\(x\\in B_n\\) for all \\(n\\geq1\\), or \\(f(x)\\geq\\alpha\\phi(x)\\), since \\(f(x)\\geq\\phi(x)\\). So for all \\(x\\), \\(f_n(x)\\geq\\alpha\\phi(x)\\) for large enough \\(n\\).<br/>\r\n<br/>\r\nSince for large enough \\(n\\), \\(\\alpha\\phi\\chi_{B_n}\\leq f_n\\chi_{B_n}\\leq f_n\\), \\(\\alpha\\int_{B_n}\\phi\\leq\\int_{\\mathbb R}f_n\\). If \\(\\phi=\\sum_{i=1}^k\\alpha_i\\chi_{E_i}\\) is in standard form, then\r\n\\[\\int_{B_n}\\phi=\\int_{\\mathbb R}\\phi\\chi_{B_n}=\\sum_{i=1}^k\\alpha_im(E_i\\cap B_n)\\to\\sum_{i=1}^k\\alpha_im(E_i)=\\int_{\\mathbb R}\\phi\\]\r\nas \\(n\\to\\infty\\) by an earlier proposition.<br/>\r\n<br/>\r\nTaking limits in \\(\\alpha\\int_{B_n}\\phi\\leq\\int_{\\mathbb R}f_n\\) as \\(n\\to\\infty\\), \\(\\alpha\\int\\phi\\leq\\lim_{n\\to\\infty}\\int f_n\\). Letting \\(\\alpha\\to1\\), we get that \\(\\int\\phi\\leq\\lim_{n\\to\\infty} f_n\\) as required.',529),(248,'','Let \\((\\phi_n)\\) and \\((\\psi_n)\\) be increasing sequences of simple functions such that \\(\\lim_{n\\to\\infty}\\phi_n(x)=f(x)\\) and \\(\\lim_{n\\to\\infty}\\psi_n(x)=g(x)\\) for all \\(x\\in\\mathbb R\\). Then \\((\\phi_n+\\psi_n)\\) is an increasing sequence of simple functions such that \\(\\lim_{n\\to\\infty}(\\phi_n(x)+\\psi_n(x))=f(x)+g(x)\\).<br/>\r\n<br/>\r\nBy the M.C.T.\r\n\\[\\int(f+g)=\\lim_{n\\to\\infty}\\int(\\phi_n+\\psi_n)=\\lim_{n\\to\\infty}(\\int\\phi_n+\\int\\psi_n)=\\lim_{n\\to\\infty}\\int\\phi_n+\\lim_{n\\to\\infty}\\int\\psi_n=\\int f+\\int g\\]',552),(249,'','Apply M.C.T. to \\(g_n=\\sum_{r=1}^n f_r\\). Then \\(\\int g_n=\\sum_{r=1}^n\\int f_n\\to\\sum_{n=1}^\\infty\\int f_n\\), so \\(\\int g_n\\to\\int f\\).',553),(250,'','By mods theory, there exists an increasing sequence \\((\\phi_n)\\) of step functions such that \\(\\lim_{n\\to\\infty}\\phi_n(x)=f(x)\\) for each \\(x\\) and \\(\\lim_{n\\to\\infty}\\int_a^b\\phi_n=\\int_a^bf\\). By the M.C.T. \\(\\lim_{n\\to\\infty}\\int_a^b\\phi_n=\\int_{[a,b]}f\\).',554),(251,'','<ol>\r\n<li>\\(|gh|\\leq c|g|\\) where \\(|h|\\leq c\\)</li>\r\n<li>\\(|g\\chi_E|\\leq|g|\\) almost everywhere</li>\r\n<li>\\(|h\\chi_E|\\leq e\\chi_E\\) where \\(|h|\\leq c\\)</li>\r\n</ol>',557),(252,'','For any open subset \\(U\\) of \\(X\\), \\(i^{-1}(U)=U\\cap A\\) which is open in \\(A\\).',558),(253,'','By construction \\(X\\) is a union of sets in \\(\\mathcal B\\), so \\(X\\in T_{\\mathcal B}\\), also \\(\\emptyset\\in T_{\\mathcal B}\\) as it\'s the union of no sets.<br/>\r\n<br/>\r\nSuppose \\(U,V\\in T_{\\mathcal B}\\), then \\(U=\\bigcup_{i\\in I}B_i\\) and \\(V=\\bigcup_{j\\in J}B\'_j\\) for \\(B_i,B\'_j\\in\\mathcal B\\). So\r\n\\[U\\cap V=(\\bigcup_{i\\in I}B_i)\\cap(\\bigcup_{j\\in J}B\'_j)=\\bigcup_{i\\in I}\\bigcup_{j\\in J}(B_i\\cap B\'_j)=\\bigcup_{i\\in I}\\bigcup_{j\\in J}\\bigcup_{k\\in K}B\'\'_k\\in T_{\\mathcal B}\\]',562),(254,'','\\(X\\in T_X,Y\\in T_Y\\), so \\(X\\times Y\\in\\mathcal B_{X,Y}\\).<br/>\r\nLet \\(U\\times V,U\'\\times V\'\\in\\mathcal B_{X,Y}\\), where \\(U,U\'\\in T_X\\) and \\(V,V\'\\in T_Y\\), then \\((U\\times V)\\cap(U\'\\times V\')=(U\\cap U\')\\times(V\\cap V\')\\in\\mathcal B_{X,Y}\\).',563),(255,'','We proved earlier that they all give the same topology, so without loss of generality focus on \\(d_\\infty\\) on \\(X\\times Y\\).<br/>\r\nLet \\(T_{d_\\infty}\\) be the topology it generates.<br/>\r\n<br/>\r\nLet \\(U\\in T_X,V\\in T_Y\\), then for each \\((x,y)\\in U\\times V\\), \\(\\exists\\epsilon_1,\\epsilon_2\\gt0\\) s.t. \\(B_X(x,\\epsilon_1)\\subset U\\) and \\(B_Y(y,\\epsilon_2)\\subset V\\), so \\(B_{X\\times Y}((x,y),\\min\\{\\epsilon_1,\\epsilon_2\\})\\subset U\\times V\\), so \\(U\\times V\\) is open with respect to \\(d_\\infty\\).<br/>\r\nSo as anything in the product topology is a union of things of the form \\(U\\times V\\), we\'ve shown that \\(T_{X\\times Y}\\subset T_{d_\\infty}\\).<br/>\r\n<br/>\r\nIn the other direction, any ball in \\((X\\times Y),d_\\infty)\\) is of the form \\(B_{X\\times Y}((x,y),\\epsilon)=B_X(x,\\epsilon)\\times B_Y(y,\\epsilon)\\) which is open with respect to \\(T_{X\\times Y}\\). Any open set is a union of balls, so we\'ve shown that \\(T_{d_\\infty}\\subset T_{X\\times Y}\\).',566),(256,'','Let \\(U\\) be an open set in \\(X\\), then \\(P_X^{-1}(U)=U\\times Y\\) which is open in \\(X\\times Y\\). Hence \\(P_X\\) and by symmetry \\(P_Y\\) are continuous.',568),(257,'','\\(f=P_X\\circ(f,g)\\) so if \\((f,g)\\) is continuous, then \\(f\\) and \\(g\\) are continuous.<br/>\r\n<br/>\r\nAn open set \\(W\\) in \\(X\\times Y\\) is a union of open sets of the form \\(U\\times V\\) where \\(U,V\\) are open in \\(X\\) and \\(Y\\) respectively. \\((f,g)^{-1}(U\\times V)=f^{-1}(U)\\cup g^{-1}(V)\\) which is open. So if \\(f\\) and \\(g\\) are continuous, then \\((f,g)\\) is continuous.',569),(258,'','\\((2\\Rightarrow1)\\): Let \\(U,V\\) be open, disjoint subsets of \\(X\\) s.t. \\(X=U\\cup V\\), then \\(U\\) is open and closed, so \\(U=\\emptyset\\) or \\(U=X\\), so they can\'t be both non-empty, so \\(X\\) is connected.<br/>\r\n<br/>\r\n\\((1\\Rightarrow3)\\): Let \\(f:X\\to\\{0,1\\}\\) be a continuous map, then \\(f^{-1}(\\{0\\})\\) and \\(f^{-1}(\\{1\\})\\) are both open and closed in \\(X\\) and cover \\(X\\), therefore they can\'t both the non-empty, so \\(f\\) is constant.<br/>\r\n<br/>\r\n\\((3\\Rightarrow2)\\): Suppose \\(A\\subset X\\) is both open and closed, define \\(f:X\\to\\{0,1\\}\\) by \\(f(x)=1\\) is \\(x\\in A\\) and \\(f(x)=0\\) if \\(x\\not\\in A\\). Then any preimage is one of \\(\\emptyset,A,X\\setminus A,X\\), so \\(f\\) is continuous. But then \\(f\\) must be constant, therefore \\(A=\\emptyset\\) or \\(A=X\\).',571),(259,'','Let \\(U,V\\) be open subsets of \\(Y\\) s.t. \\(f(A)\\subset U\\cup V\\) and \\(f(A)\\cap U\\cap V=\\emptyset\\). Then \\(f^{-1}(U)\\) and \\(f^{-1}(V)\\) are open in \\(X\\) by continuity of \\(f\\), so \\(f^{-1}(U)\\cap A\\) and \\(f^{-1}(V)\\cap A\\) are open in \\(A\\) and disjoint, therefore one of them is empty as \\(A\\) is connected. Therefore one of \\(f(A)\\cap U\\) or \\(f(A)\\cap V\\) is empty.',574),(260,'','Let \\(f:\\bigcup_{i\\in I}\\to\\{0,1\\}\\) be continuous, since each \\(A_i\\) is connected, \\(f|_{A_i}\\) is constant. Say \\(f(x)=c_i\\) for all \\(x\\in A_i\\), but as \\(A_i\\cap A_j\\neq\\emptyset\\), \\(f\\) is constant.',575),(261,'','Note \\(B\\cup C_i\\) is connected for each \\(i\\in I\\) and that \\(B\\cup\\bigcup_{i\\in I}C_i=\\bigcup_{i\\in I}(B\\cup C_i)\\), so by the previous proposition, \\(B\\cup\\bigcup_{i\\in I}C_i\\) is connected.',576),(262,'','\\((\\Rightarrow)\\): Note that \\(X=P_X(X\\times Y)\\), so \\(X\\) is connected as \\(P_X\\) is continuous. Similarly for \\(Y\\).<br/>\r\n<br/>\r\n\\((\\Leftarrow)\\): Suppose \\(X\\) and \\(Y\\) are connected, fix some \\(y_0\\in Y\\), then \\(X\\times\\{y_0\\}\\) is homeomorphic to \\(X\\) and hence is connected. Similarly for each \\(x\\in X\\), \\(\\{x\\}\\times Y\\) is connected. Then note that\r\n\\[(X\\times\\{y_0\\})\\cap(\\{x\\}\\times Y)=\\{(x,y_0)\\}\\neq\\emptyset\\]\r\nand that\r\n\\[(X\\times\\{y_0\\})\\cup\\bigcup_{x\\in X}(\\{x\\}\\times Y)=X\\times Y\\]\r\nTherefore \\(X\\times Y\\) is connected.',577),(263,'','\\(\\mathbb R\\) is connected. So by induction, \\(\\mathbb R^n=\\mathbb R\\times\\mathbb R^{n-1}\\) is connected.',578),(264,'','Let \\(U,V\\subset X\\) be open s.t. \\(B\\subset U\\cup V\\) and \\(B\\cup U\\cup V=\\emptyset\\).<br/>\r\n<br/>\r\nNote that \\(A\\subset U\\cup V\\) and \\(A\\cap U\\cap V=\\emptyset\\), so as \\(A\\) is connected one of \\(A\\cap U\\) or \\(A\\cap V\\) is empty, w.l.o.g. assume \\(A\\cap U=\\emptyset\\).<br/>\r\n<br/>\r\nSo \\(A\\subset X\\setminus U\\) which is closed, so \\(\\overline A\\subset X\\setminus U\\), so \\(\\overline A\\cap U=\\emptyset\\), so \\(B\\cap U=\\emptyset\\).',579),(265,'','Let \\(X\\) be a path connected topological space, let \\(a\\in X\\). For every \\(x\\in X\\), there is a path \\(p_x:[0,1]\\to X\\) joining \\(a\\) to \\(x\\), let \\(A_x=p_x([0,1])\\subset X\\). Then as each \\(A_x\\) is connected and \\(A_x\\cap A_y\\supset\\{a\\}\\neq\\emptyset\\), \\(\\bigcup_{x\\in X}A_x=X\\) is connected.',582),(266,'','By redefining all \\(f_n\\) on a countable union of null sets, which is still null, we can assume \\(f_n\\leq f_{n+1}\\) for all \\(n\\) and \\(f_n(x)\\in\\mathbb R\\) almost everywhere.<br/>\r\n<br/>\r\nApply the M.C.T. V1 to \\((f_n-f_1)\\) which is non-negative and increasing, so\r\n\\[\\int(f-f_1)=\\lim_{n\\to\\infty}\\int(f_n-f_1)=\\lim_{n\\to\\infty}\\int f_n-\\int f_1\\]\r\nwhich is finite, so \\((f-f_1)\\) is integrable, so \\(f\\) is integrable and \\(\\int f=\\lim_{n\\to\\infty}\\int f_n\\)',586),(267,'','Let \\(g_m=\\inf_{n\\geq m}f_n\\), then \\((g_m)_{m\\geq1}\\) is increasing, \\(\\lim_{m\\to\\infty}g_m=\\liminf_{n\\to\\infty}f_n\\) and \\(g_m\\leq f_m\\). By the M.C.T.\r\n\\[\\int\\liminf_{n\\to\\infty}f_n=\\int\\lim_{m\\to\\infty}g_m=\\lim_{m\\to\\infty}\\int g_m\\leq\\liminf_{m\\to\\infty}\\int f_m\\]',587),(268,'','\\(f\\) is measurable and \\(|f|\\leq g\\) almost everywhere, so \\(f\\) is integrable by comparison. Apply Fatou\'s lemma to \\(g+f_n\\) and \\(g-f_n\\). These are both non-negative almost everywhere, so\r\n\\[\\int(g+\\liminf_{n\\to\\infty}f_n)\\leq\\int g+\\liminf_{n\\to\\infty}\\int f_n\\]\r\n\\[\\int(g-\\limsup_{n\\to\\infty}f_n)\\leq\\int g-\\limsup_{n\\to\\infty}\\int f_n\\]\r\nHence \\(\\limsup_{n\\to\\infty}\\int f_n\\leq\\int\\lim_{n\\to\\infty}f_n\\leq\\liminf_{n\\to\\infty}\\int f_n\\), so \\(\\lim_{n\\to\\infty}\\int f_n=\\int f\\)',588),(269,'','\\(\\theta((A,a)\\circ(B,b))=\\theta((AB,Ba+b))=AB=\\theta(A,a)\\theta(B,b)\\)',608),(270,'','\\(f(v)=Av+a\\) is already the composition \\(t_ag\\) where \\(g(v)=Av\\). Now \\(g\\) can be written as either \\(\\rho_\\theta\\) or as \\(\\rho_\\theta r\\).',610),(271,'','Let \\(G=\\{g_1=e,g_2,...,g_n\\}\\), \\(v_1\\in\\mathbb R^n\\), \\(v_i=g_i(v_1)\\) for \\(1\\lt i\\leq n\\). Let \\(v={1\\over n}\\sum_{i=1}^nv_i\\), this is called the centre of mass of the points.<br/>\r\n<br/>\r\nClaim that \\(\\forall g\\in G,\\ g(v)=v\\).<br/>\r\nTake \\(g\\in G\\), then it has the form \\(g(u)=\\phi(u)+a\\) where \\(\\phi\\in O_n\\) and \\(a\\in\\mathbb R^n\\). Then\r\n\\[g(v)=\\phi(v)+a=\\phi({1\\over n}\\sum_{i=1}^nv_i)+a={1\\over n}\\sum_{i=1}^n\\phi(v_i)+a\\]\r\n\\[={1\\over n}(\\sum_{i=1}^n(\\phi(v_i)+a))={1\\over n}\\sum_{i=1}^ng(v_i)={1\\over n}\\sum_{h\\in G}gh(v_i)={1\\over n}\\sum_{h\\in G}h(v_i)=v\\]',614),(272,'','Let \\(G\\leq M_2\\) be finite, then there is some \\(v\\in\\mathbb R^n\\) that is a fixed point, so w.l.o.g. choose coordinates such that the fixed point is at the origin. Now we know \\(G\\leq O_n\\).<br/>\r\n<br/>\r\nAll elements of \\(G\\) must be either a rotation around the origin or a reflection in a line passing through the origin.<br/>\r\n<br/>\r\nLook at the rotations subgroup, \\(H\\leq G\\), write each \\(h_i\\in H\\) as \\(h_i=\\rho_{\\theta_i}\\) where \\({\\theta_i\\over2\\pi}\\in\\mathbb Q\\). Let \\(I=\\{q\\in\\mathbb Q:\\rho{2\\pi q}\\in H\\}\\subset\\mathbb Q\\). Then \\(I\\) has the following properties:\r\n<ol>\r\n<li>\\(\\mathbb Z\\subset I\\)</li>\r\n<li>\\(I+1=I\\)</li>\r\n<li>\\(I\\pm I\\subset I\\)</li>\r\n<li>\\(\\mathbb ZI\\subset I\\)</li>\r\n</ol>\r\nThen claim, \\(\\exists q_0\\gt0,\\ q\\in\\mathbb Q,\\ s.t.\\ I=\\mathbb Zq_0\\).<br/>\r\n<br/>\r\nBecause \\(H\\) is finite, there must be a smallest distance between different elements of \\(I\\). Let \\(q_0\\) be this distance. Then by (3) and (4) above, \\(q_0\\in I\\) and \\(\\mathbb Z\\subset I\\), so if \\(\\mathbb Zq_0\\neq I\\) then I would get a smaller distance which would be a contradiction. Hence \\(I=\\mathbb Zq_0\\), so \\(H=\\mathbb Z\\rho_{2\\pi q_0}\\). Also note that \\(q_0={1\\over m}\\) for some \\(m\\in\\mathbb N\\).<br/>\r\n<br/>\r\nIf \\(G=H\\) then we\'re done as \\(H\\cong C_n\\). Otherwise, pick \\(r\\in G\\setminus H\\), so \\(G\\supset\\langle\\rho_{2\\pi\\over m},r\\rangle=D_{2m}\\). Then any \\(r_2\\not\\in D_{2m}\\) would generate new rotations, so \\(G\\cong D_{2m}\\).',615),(273,'','Since \\(s_1,s_2\\) are in the same orbit, \\(\\exists g\\in G\\ s.t.\\ gs_2=s_1\\). Then\r\n\\[h\\in stab_G(s_2)\\Longleftrightarrow hs_2=s_2\\Longleftrightarrow hg^{-1}s_1=g^{-1}s_1\\]\r\n\\[\\Longleftrightarrow ghg^{-1}s_1=s_1\\Longleftrightarrow ghg^{-1}\\in stab_G(s_1)\\Longleftrightarrow h\\in g^{-1}stab_G(s_1)g\\]',620),(274,'','Apply MCT for series to \\(g_n^+\\) and \\(g_n^-\\).',623),(275,'','For each \\(k\\),\r\n\\[\\sum_{n=1}^k\\int|g_n|=\\int\\sum_{n=1}^k|g_n|\\lt\\int\\sum_{n=1}^\\infty|g_n|\\lt\\infty\\]\r\nso letting \\(k\\to\\infty\\), \\(\\sum_{n=1}^\\infty\\int|g_n|\\lt\\infty\\), so by Lebesgue series theorem, we\'re done.',624),(276,'','Let \\((y_n)\\) be a sequence converging to a limit \\(y\\in J\\), let \\(f_n(x)=f(x,y_n)\\). Then \\(f_n\\in\\mathcal L\'(I),\\ f_n(x)\\to f(x,y)\\) almost everywhere and \\(|f_n(x)|\\leq g(x)\\) almost everywhere for each \\(n\\). By the DCT for sequences, \\(\\int_If_n(x)dx\\to\\int_if(x,y)dx\\) as \\(n\\to\\infty\\). So \\(F(y_n)\\to F(y)\\) as \\(n\\to\\infty\\), thus \\(F\\) is continuous on \\(J\\).',625),(277,'','Fix \\(y\\in J\\), let \\((y_n)\\) be any sequence in \\(J\\) such that \\(y_n\\to y\\) as \\(n\\to\\infty\\), and \\(y_n\\neq y\\) for all \\(n\\geq 1\\). Let \\(g_n(x)={f(x,y_n)-f(x,y)\\over y_n-y}\\), then \\(g_n\\in\\mathcal L\'(I)\\), and \\(g_n(x)\\to{\\partial f\\over\\partial y}(x,y)\\) as \\(n\\to\\infty\\).<br/>\r\n<br/>\r\nBy the mean value theorem, \\(g_n(x)={\\partial f\\over\\partial y}(x,\\xi_n)\\) for some \\(\\xi_n\\) between \\(y\\) and \\(y_n\\). So \\(|g_n(x)|\\leq g(x)\\) for all \\(n\\geq1\\) almost everywhere, by the DCT \\(\\int_Ig_n(x)dx\\to\\int_I{\\partial f\\over\\partial y}(x,y)dx\\) as \\(n\\to\\infty\\).<br/>\r\n<br/>\r\nTherefore \\({F(y_n)-F(y)\\over y_n-y}\\to\\int_I{\\partial f\\over\\partial y}(x,y)dx\\) as \\(n\\to\\infty\\). As this holds for every sequence we have\r\n\\[\\lim_{y\'\\to y}{F(y\')-F(y)\\over y\'-y}=\\lim_{n\\to\\infty}{F(y_n)-F(y)\\over y_n-y}\\]\r\nso \\(F\'(y)=\\int_I{\\partial f\\over\\partial y}(x,y)dx\\)',627),(278,'','Assume \\(U\\subset X\\) is open, connected and non-empty. Pick some \\(a\\in U\\), let \\(C\\) be the set of points in \\(U\\) path connected to \\(a\\). We\'ll show \\(C\\) is non-empty, open and closed, hence \\(C=U\\).<br/>\r\n<br/>\r\n\\(a\\in C\\) as \\(a\\) is trivially path connected to itself, so \\(C\\neq\\emptyset\\).<br/>\r\n<br/>\r\nLet \\(x\\in C\\), then there exists a path \\(p\\) from \\(a\\) to\\(x\\). Since \\(U\\) is open, \\(\\exists\\epsilon\\gt0\\ s.t\\ B(x,\\epsilon)\\subset U\\), note this ball is path connected, so by joining the two paths we can get anywhere in \\(B(x,\\epsilon)\\). So \\(C\\) is open.<br/>\r\n<br/>\r\nLet \\(x\\in U\\setminus C\\), then \\(\\exists\\epsilon\\gt0\\ s.t\\ B(x,\\epsilon)\\subset U\\setminus C\\), again this ball is path connected. So if we had a path to anywhere in \\(B(x,\\epsilon)\\) we\'d have one to \\(x\\), so \\(B(x,\\epsilon)\\subset U\\setminus C\\). So \\(C\\) is closed.<br/>\r\n<br/>\r\nTherefore by connectedness of \\(U\\), \\(C=U\\), so \\(U\\) is path connected.',629),(279,'','Let \\(y_1,y_2\\in f(A)\\), then \\(\\exists x_1,x_2\\in A\\ s.t.\\ f(x_1)=y_1,\\ f(x_2)=y_2\\). But \\(x_1,x_2\\) are joined by a path \\(p\\) is \\(A\\), so \\(f\\circ p\\) is a path in \\(f(A)\\) connecting \\(y_1\\) and \\(y_2\\).',630),(280,'','Let \\(X\\) be compact and \\(A\\subset X\\) is closed. Suppose \\(U=\\{U_i:i\\in I\\}\\) is an open cover for \\(A\\), then \\(U\\cup(X\\setminus A)\\) is an open cover for \\(X\\), which therefore has a finite subcover of the form \\(\\{U_j:j\\in J\\}\\cup(X\\setminus A)\\) for some \\(J\\subset I\\). Thus \\(\\{U_j:j\\in J\\}\\) is a finite subcover for \\(A\\), so \\(A\\) is compact.',636),(281,'','For every \\(y\\in K\\), there exist open and disjoint \\(U_y,V_y\\) s.t. \\(y\\in U_y,\\ x\\in V_y\\). Then \\(\\{U_y:y\\in K\\}\\) forms an open cover for \\(K\\), so it has a finite subcover \\(\\{U_{y_1},U_{y_2},...,U_{y_n}\\}\\). Let \\(U=\\bigcup_{i=1}^nU_{y_i},\\ V=\\bigcap_{i=1}^nV_{y_i}\\). Then \\(K\\subset U\\), \\(x\\in V\\) and \\(U,V\\) are open and disjoint.',637),(282,'','\\(\\forall x\\in X\\setminus K,\\ \\exists U\\) open s.t. \\(x\\in U\\subset X\\setminus K\\). So \\(X\\setminus K\\) is open, so \\(K\\) is closed.',638),(283,'','<ol>\r\n<li>Let \\(\\{U_i:i\\in I\\}\\) be an open cover for \\(\\bigcup_{j=1}^nK_j\\), so it an open cover for each \\(K_j\\). So \\(\\exists I_j\\subset I\\) with \\(I_j\\) finite s.t. \\(K_j\\subset\\bigcup_{i\\in I_j}U_i\\) for each \\(j\\). Then writing \\(J=\\bigcup_{j=1}^nI_j\\), \\(\\{U_j:j\\in J\\}\\) is a finite subcover for \\(\\bigcup_{j=1}^nK_j\\).<br/>\r\n<br/><br/>\r\n</li>\r\n<li>FIx some \\(K_i\\), some \\(i\\in I\\). This is a compact Hausdorff spac, hence the compact sets of \\(K_i\\) are precisely the closed subsets of \\(K_i\\). So, for each \\(j\\in I\\), \\(K_j\\) is compact and \\(K_j\\cap K_i\\) is closed, so \\(\\bigcap_{j\\in J}K_j\\cap K_i\\) is closed and hence compact. So \\(\\bigcap_{j\\in J}K_j\\) is compact.</li>\r\n</ol>',639),(284,'','Let \\(K\\subset X\\), where \\(X\\) is a metric space and \\(K\\) is compact. Pick some \\(x\\in X\\), then \\(\\{B(x,n):n\\in\\mathbb N\\}\\) is an open cover for \\(K\\), thus it has a finite subcover \\(\\{B(x,n_i):i\\in I\\}\\), so \\(\\exists N=max\\{n_i:i\\in I\\}\\), so \\(K\\subset B(x,N)\\), so \\(K\\) is bounded.',640),(285,'','All metric spaces are Hausdorff',641),(286,'','Let \\(\\{U_i:i\\in I\\}\\) be an open cover for \\(f(A)\\), then with \\(V_i=f^{-1}(U_i)\\), \\(\\{V_i:i\\in I\\}\\) is an open cover for \\(A\\). So \\(\\exists J\\subset I\\) with \\(J\\) finite and \\(\\{V_j:j\\in J\\}\\) is a finite subcover of \\(A\\). Then \\(\\{U_j:j\\in J\\}\\) is a finite subcover for \\(f(A)\\). So \\(f(A)\\) is compact.',642),(287,'','\\((\\Rightarrow)\\): Suppose \\(X\\times Y\\) is compact, then \\(X = P_X(X\\times Y)\\) so \\(X\\) is compact, similarly for \\(Y\\).<br/>\r\n<br/>\r\n\\((\\Leftarrow)\\): Suppose \\(X\\) and \\(Y\\) are compact, let \\(\\{w_i:i\\in I\\}\\) be an open cover for \\(X\\times Y\\). Each \\(w_i\\) can be expressed as \\(\\bigcup_{j\\in J_i}(U_j\\times V_j)\\) where \\(J_i\\) is some indexing set and \\(U_j,V_j\\) are open in \\(X,Y\\) respectively.<br/>\r\n<br/>\r\nSo \\(\\{U_j\\times V_j:j\\in J_i,\\ i\\in I\\}\\) is an open cover for \\(X\\times Y\\), it suffices to find a finite subcover of this.<br/>\r\n<br/>\r\nSo, for each \\(y\\in Y\\), \\(X\\times\\{y\\}\\) is homeomorphic to \\(X\\) and hence compact, it\'s covered by the open sets \\(U_j\\times V_j:j\\in J_i,\\ i\\in I\\}\\), so there is a finite set \\(F_y\\) such that \\(X\\times\\{y\\}\\subset\\bigcup_{j\\in F_y}(U_j\\times V_j)\\).<br/>\r\n<br/>\r\nLet \\(V_y=\\bigcup_{j\\in F_y}V_j\\), this is an open set in \\(Y\\) containing \\(y\\). Then \\(\\{V_y:y\\in Y\\}\\) is an open cover for \\(Y\\), so there exists a finite subcover \\(\\{V_{y_1},...,V_{y_m}\\}\\) for some \\(y_1,...,y_m\\in Y\\).<br/>\r\n<br/>\r\nThen for all \\((x,y)\\in X\\times Y\\), \\(\\exists k\\in\\{1,...,m\\}\\ s.t.\\ y\\in V_{y_k}\\), so \\(y\\in V_j\\) for each \\(j\\in F_{y_k}\\). On the other hand, \\(X\\times\\{y\\}\\subset\\bigcup_{j\\in F_{y_k}}(U_j\\times V_j)\\), so \\(x\\in U_{j_0}\\) for some \\(j_0\\in F_{y_k}\\). Then \\((x,y)\\in U_{j_0}\\times V_{j_0}\\). Therefore \\(X\\times Y\\subset\\bigcup_{k=1}^m\\bigcup_{j\\in F_{y_k}}(U_j\\times V_j)\\).',645),(288,'','Let \\(A\\subset\\mathbb R^n\\) be closed and bounded, then \\(A\\) lives inside some hypercube, so \\(\\exists r\\gt0\\ s.t.\\ A\\subset[-r,r]^n\\). But \\([-r,r]\\) is compact and hence \\([-r,r]^n\\) is compact, so as \\(A\\) is a closed subset, \\(A\\) is compact.',646),(289,'','Consider a closed subset \\(V\\) of \\(X\\), then \\(V\\) is compact so \\(f(V)\\) is compact, hence \\(f(V)\\) is closed as \\(Y\\) is Hausdorff. Therefore \\(f^{-1}\\) is continuous so \\(f\\) is a homeomorphism.',647),(290,'','Let \\(\\epsilon\\gt0\\), then \\(\\forall x\\in X,\\ \\exists\\delta_x\\gt0\\ s.t.\\ \\forall x\'\\in X,\\ d(x,x\')\\lt\\delta_x\\Rightarrow d(f(x),f(x\'))\\lt{\\epsilon\\over2}\\)<br/>\r\n<br/>\r\nSo \\(\\{B(x,{\\delta_x\\over2}):x\\in X\\}\\) forms an open cover of \\(X\\), so we have a finite subcover \\(\\{B(x_1,{\\delta_{x_1}\\over2}),...,B(x_n,{\\delta_{x_n}\\over2})\\}\\), let \\(\\delta=min\\{{\\delta_{x_1}\\over2},...,{\\delta_{x_n}\\over2}\\}\\).<br/>\r\n<br/>\r\nLet \\(y,z\\in X\\ s.t.\\ d(y,z)\\lt\\delta\\), say \\(y\\in B(x_i,{\\delta_{x_i}\\over2})\\), so \\(d(y,x_i)\\lt{\\delta_{x_i}\\over2}\\), then \\(d(z,x_i)\\leq d(z,y)+d(y,x_i)\\lt\\delta_{x_i}\\). Therefore \\(d(f(y),f(x_i))\\lt{\\epsilon\\over2}\\) and \\(d(f(z),f(x_i))\\lt{\\epsilon\\over2}\\), so \\(d(f(y),f(z))\\lt\\epsilon\\)',649),(291,'','<ol>\r\n<li>Let \\(A\\subset X\\), \\(A\'=\\emptyset\\), we\'ll show that \\(A\\) must be finite.<br/>\r\nSince \\(A\'=\\emptyset\\), every point of \\(A\\) is isolated, so for each \\(a\\in A\\), there is an open set \\(U_a\\) with \\(U_a\\cap A=\\{a\\}\\). So \\(\\{U_a:a\\in A\\}\\) forms an open cover of \\(A\\). Also \\(\\overline A=A\\cup A\'=A\\), so \\(A\\) is closed and hence compact. So there exists a finite subcover \\(\\{U_{a_1},...,U_{a_n}\\}\\), then \\(A=(\\bigcup_{i=1}^nU_{a_i})\\cap A=\\bigcup_{i=1}^n(U_{a_i}\\cap A)=\\bigcup_{i=1}^n\\{a_i\\}\\), so \\(A\\) is finite.<br/>\r\n<br/>\r\n</li>\r\n<li>Let \\((x_n)\\) be a sequence in the compact metric space \\(X\\), let \\(A=\\{x_n:n\\in\\mathbb N\\}\\subset X\\).<br/>\r\n<ul>\r\n<li>Case 1: Suppose \\(A\\) is finite, say \\(A=\\{a_1,...,a_n\\}\\), then for some \\(i\\), \\(x_n\\) takes the value \\(a_i\\) infinitely many times ,so it gives a constant and hence convergent subsequence.</li>\r\n<li>Case 2: Suppose \\(A\\) is infinite, then by the above \\(\\exists a\\in A\'\\). Construct the subsequence \\(x_{n_k}\\) of \\(x_n\\) that converges to \\(a\\) as follows: We know \\((B(a,1)\\cap A)\\setminus\\{a\\}\\neq\\emptyset\\), let \\(x_{n_1}\\) be in this set. Now suppose we have constructed the first \\(k\\) terms, let \\(r=min\\{d(x_i,a):1\\leq i\\leq n_k,\\ x_i\\neq a\\}\\), then \\((B(a,r)\\cap A)\\setminus\\{a\\}\\neq\\emptyset\\), so pick \\(x_{n_{k+1}}\\) in this set. This subsequence converges to \\(a\\)</li>\r\n</ul>\r\n</li>\r\n</ol>',652),(292,'','Let \\((x_n)\\) be a Cauchy sequence in a compact metric space \\(X\\), we know some subsequence of it converges, thus the whole sequence converges. So\\(X\\) is complete.',654),(293,'','Suppose \\(\\{U_i:i\\in I\\}\\) is an open cover for \\(X\\) with no Lebesgue number. So \\(\\forall\\epsilon\\gt0,\\ \\exists x\\in X\\ s.t.\\ B(x,\\epsilon)\\) is not wholly contained in any \\(U_i\\).<br/>\r\n<br/>\r\nSetting \\(\\epsilon={1\\over n}\\), let \\(x_n\\) be such that \\(B(x_n,{1\\over n})\\subset U_i\\) for all \\(i\\in I\\). Then \\((x_n)\\) has a convergent subsequence \\((x_{n_k})\\), converging to some \\(a\\in X\\). Now \\(a\\in U_i\\) for some \\(i\\in I\\) and since \\(U_i\\) is open, \\(\\exists\\epsilon\\gt0\\ s.t. B(a,2\\epsilon)\\subset U_i\\), then \\(\\exists K\\ s.t.\\ \\forall k\\geq K,\\ d(x_n,a)\\lt\\epsilon\\), so \\(B(x_{n_k},\\epsilon)\\subset B(a,2\\epsilon)\\subset U_i\\). Choose \\(k\\geq K\\ s.t.\\ {1\\over n_k}\\lt\\epsilon\\), so \\(B(x_{n_k},{1\\over n_k})\\subset B(x_{n_k},\\epsilon)\\subset U_i\\). This is a contradiction, hence a Lebesgue number exists.',656),(294,'','Suppose \\(X\\) has no \\(\\epsilon\\)-net. Let \\(x_1\\in X\\), then \\(\\{x_1\\}\\) is not an \\(\\epsilon\\)-net. So \\(\\exists x_2\\in X\\ s.t.\\ x_2\\not\\in B(x_1,\\epsilon)\\), now \\(\\{x_1,x_2\\}\\) is no an \\(\\epsilon\\)-net. So \\(\\exists x_3\\not\\in B(x_1,\\epsilon)\\cup B(x_2,\\epsilon)\\). Carry this on.<br/>\r\n<br/>\r\nSo we\'ve constructed a sequence s.t. \\(\\forall n\\neq m,\\ d(x_n,x_m)\\geq\\epsilon\\). So \\((x_n)\\) has no convergent subsequence which contradicts \\(X\\) being sequentially compact.',658),(295,'','Let \\(X\\) be a sequentially compact metric space. Let \\(\\{U_i:i\\in I\\}\\) be an open cover for \\(X\\), then this has a Lebesgue number \\(\\epsilon\\gt0\\). So there is a finite \\(\\epsilon\\)-net \\(\\{x_1,...,x_n\\}\\). Then each \\(B(x_i,\\epsilon)\\subset U_j\\) for some  \\(j\\in I\\), so \\(\\{U_1,...,U_n\\}\\) is a finite subcover.',659),(296,'','<ol>\r\n<li>\\(\\emptyset\\) and \\(X\\over R\\) are open as \\(p^{-1}(\\emptyset)=\\emptyset\\) and \\(p^{-1}({X\\over R})=X\\) are open in \\(X\\)</li>\r\n<li>If \\(\\tilde U_1,...,\\tilde U_n\\in\\tilde T\\), then \\(p^{-1}(\\tilde U_1\\cap...\\cap\\tilde U_n)=p^{-1}(\\tilde U_1)\\cap...\\cap p^{-1}(\\tilde U_n)\\in T\\)</li>\r\n<li>If \\(\\tilde U_i\\in \\tilde T\\) for \\(i\\in I\\), then \\(p^{-1}(\\bigcup_{i\\in I}\\tilde U_i)=\\bigcup_{i\\in I}p^{-1}(\\tilde U_i)\\)</li>\r\n</ol>',661),(297,'','Suppose \\(g_1,g_2\\) are in the same coset, write \\(H=stab_G(s)\\), so \\(g_1H=g_2H\\), therefore \\(g_2^{-1}g_1\\in H\\), so \\(g_2^{-1}g_1s=s\\), so \\(g_1s=g_2s\\). So \\(\\phi\\) is well defined.<br/>\r\n<br/>\r\n\\(\\phi\\) is surjective by definition.<br/>\r\n<br/>\r\nSuppose \\(g_1s=g_2s\\), then \\(g_2^{-1}g_1s=s\\), so \\(g_2^{-1}g_2\\in H\\), so \\(g_1H=g_2H\\). So \\(\\phi\\) is injective.',662),(298,'','<ol>\r\n<li>This is the orbit stabiliser theorem<br/><br/></li>\r\n<li>Given conjugate subgroups \\(H_1,H_2\\lt G\\) where \\(H_2=g^{-1}H_1g\\), define \\(\\phi:{G\\over H_1}\\to{G\\over H_2}\\) by \\(kH_1\\mapsto(g^{-1}kg)H_2\\) which satisfies \\(h\\phi(kH_1)=\\phi((hk)H_1)\\).<br/>\r\n<br/>\r\nGiven equivalent coset actions \\(H_1,H_2\\) become stabilisers of different elements \\(s_1\\in {G\\over H_1},\\ s_2\\in{G\\over H_2}\\). But then, in transitive actions, stabilisers of different elements are conjugate.</li>\r\n</ol>',665),(299,'','Suppose \\(G\\) acts on \\(S\\) of size \\(n\\), label the elements of \\(S\\) as \\(\\{1,...,n\\}\\). Then, every element \\(g\\in G\\) permutes the elements of \\(S\\), so maps \\(gi=j\\), gives an element of \\(S_n\\) which we\'ll call \\(\\phi(g)\\).<br/>\r\n<br/>\r\nThis is a group homomorphism by the axioms of  a group action.\r\n<ul>\r\n<li>\\(ei=i\\), so \\(\\phi(e)=e\\in S_n\\)</li>\r\n<li>If \\(gi=j,\\ hj=k,\\ i,j,k\\in\\{1,...,n\\},\\ g,h\\in G\\), then \\((hg)i=k\\), so \\(\\phi(h)\\phi(g)=\\phi)hg)\\)</li>\r\n</ul>\r\nHence, we have a group homomorphism \\(\\phi:G\\to S_n\\)<br/>\r\n<br/>\r\nConversely, if I have \\(\\phi:G\\to S_n\\), then \\(S_n\\) acts on \\(\\{1,...,n\\]\\), so \\(G\\) will act on \\(\\{1,...,n\\}\\) by \\(gi=\\phi(g)(i)\\). Reverse the argument, then this is a group action.<br/>\r\n<br/>\r\nFinally, \\(G\\) acts faithfully<br/>\r\n\\(\\Longleftrightarrow\\) the only element of \\(G\\) mapping as \\(id_S\\) is \\(e\\)<br/>\r\n\\(\\Longleftrightarrow\\) the only element \\(g\\in G\\) s.t. \\(\\phi(g)=e\\) if \\(g=e\\)<br/>\r\n\\(\\Longleftrightarrow\\) \\(ker(\\phi)=\\{e\\}\\)<br/>\r\n\\(\\Longleftrightarrow\\) \\(\\phi\\) is injective',666),(300,'','Consider the left-regular action of \\(G\\) on \\(S=G\\) of size \\(N\\). We know there is a homomorphism \\(G=S_N\\) from earlier work, this is injective as the kernel is trivial.',668),(301,'','Firstly \\(g\\in Z(G)\\Longleftrightarrow Z_G(g)=G\\Longleftrightarrow stab_{G,*}(g)=G\\Longleftrightarrow O_g=\\{g\\}\\Longleftrightarrow\\{g\\}\\) is a one-element conjugacy class.<br/>\r\n<br/>\r\nThen suppose \\(G\\) has trivial centre, then in its class equation, \\(|G|=1+\\sum|C_\\alpha|\\), then \\(|G|=0\\ (mod\\ p)\\) but \\(1+\\sum|C_\\alpha|=1\\ (mod\\ p)\\). This is a contradiction.',670),(302,'','Let \\(N=|G|\\), every element of \\(G\\setminus\\{e\\}\\) is a rotation around some axis, so it has two poles, points that don\'t move. Let \\(P\\) be the set of poles of elements of \\(G\\setminus\\{e\\}\\).<br/>\r\n<br/>\r\nNow, \\(G\\) acts on \\(P\\). Because if \\(h\\in G,\\ p\\in G\\), then \\(\\exists p\\in G\\setminus\\{e\\}\\ s.t.\\ g(p)=p\\), so \\((hgh^{-1})(hp)=hp\\), so \\(hp\\in P\\).<br/>\r\n<br/>\r\n\\(p\\in P\\) has a stabiliser \\(stab_G(p)=\\langle Rot(L,{2\\pi\\over r_p})\\rangle\\) where \\(\\theta={2\\pi\\over r_p}\\) for some \\(r_p\\in\\mathbb N\\). So \\(|stab_G(p)|=r_p\\), so we have \\(N=r_pn_p\\) where \\(n_p\\) is the size of the orbit of \\(p\\).<br/>\r\n<br/>\r\nHow many poles do we have, \\(\\sum_{p\\in P}(r_p-1)=2N-2\\) as every \\(g\\in G\\setminus\\{e\\}\\) has two poles.<br/>\r\n<br/>\r\nLet \\(P=P_1\\cup P_2\\cup...\\cup P_k\\) be the decomposition of \\(P\\) into disjoint \\(G\\)-orbits, \\(|P_i|=n_i\\). Each orbit \\(P_i\\) has a number \\(r_i\\) associated with it, namely the size of the stabiliser. So \\(r_in_i=N\\), then \\(\\sum_{i=1}^kn_i(r_i-1)=2N-2\\). By dividing by \\(N\\), \\(\\sum_{i=1}^k(1-{1\\over r_i})=2-{2\\over N}\\). Note \\(1-{1\\over r_i}\\geq{1\\over2}\\) and \\(2-{2\\over N}\\lt2\\), so we know \\(k\\leq3\\).<br/>\r\n<br/>\r\nConsider \\(k=1\\), then \\(1-{1\\over r}=2-{2\\over N}\\) which has no solutions.<br/>\r\n<br/>\r\nConsider \\(k=2\\), then \\(2-{1\\over r_1}-{1\\over r_2}=2-{2\\over N}\\), so \\({1\\over r_1}+{1\\over r_2}={2\\over N}\\), but each \\(r_i\\leq N\\) as it\'s the size of the stabiliser, hence \\(r_1=r_2=N\\). Therefore \\(G\\cong C_n\\).<br/>\r\n<br/>\r\nConsider \\(k=3\\), then \\({2\\over N}={1\\over r_1}+{1\\over r_2}+{1\\over r_3}-1\\), so \\({1\\over r_1}+{1\\over r_2}+{1\\over r_3}\\gt1\\), \\(r_i\\geq2\\). This has no solutions for all \\(r_i\\geq3\\), so say \\(r_1=2\\), then \\({1\\over r_2}+{1\\over r_3}\\geq{1\\over2}\\), so can\\t have both \\(r_i\\geq4\\), so either \\(r_2=2\\) or \\(r_2=3\\).\r\n\\[\\begin{array}{llll}\r\nIf\\ r_2=2&&r_3=r&&\\Rightarrow G\\cong D_{2r}\\\\\r\nIf\\ r_2=3&&r_3=3&&\\Rightarrow G\\cong Rot(tetrahedron)\\\\\r\n&&r_3=4&&\\Rightarrow G\\cong Rot(cube)\\\\\r\n&&r_3=5&&\\Rightarrow G\\cong Rot(dodecahedron)\r\n\\end{array}\\]',671),(303,'','Apply previous proposition to \\(f^+\\) and to \\(f^-\\), observing that \\(\\int_{\\mathbb R}f(x,y)dx\\lt\\infty\\) for almost all \\(y\\), so \\(x\\mapsto f(x,y)\\) is integrable for almost all \\(y\\).',674),(304,'','Apply the above proposition to obtain that \\(\\int_{\\mathbb R^2}|f|\\lt\\infty\\). Then \\(|f|\\) is integrable and \\(f\\) is measurable, so \\(f\\) is integrable.',675),(305,'','If \\(\\|f\\|_p=0\\) or \\(\\|g\\|_p=0\\) then the inequality is trivial.<br/>\r\n<br/>\r\nOtherwise, write \\(\\alpha=\\|f\\|_p\\), \\(\\beta=\\|g\\|_p\\), so \\(\\alpha,\\beta\\gt0\\).<br/>\r\nNow, the the function \\(t\\mapsto t^p\\) is continuous on \\([0,\\infty)\\) and has second derivative \\(t\\mapsto p(p-1)t^{p-2}\\geq0\\) on \\([0,\\infty)\\). So \\(t^p\\) is convex.\r\n\\[0\\leq\\lambda\\leq1,\\ st\\geq0,\\ \\Longrightarrow(\\lambda s+(1-\\lambda)t)^p\\leq\\lambda s^p+(1-\\lambda)t^p\\]\r\nApply this with \\(\\lambda={\\alpha\\over\\alpha+\\beta},\\ s={|f(x)|\\over\\alpha},\\ t={|g(x)|\\over\\beta}\\), to get\r\n\\[({\\alpha{|f(x)|\\over\\alpha}+\\beta{|g(x)|\\over\\beta}\\over\\alpha+\\beta})^p\\leq{\\alpha\\over\\alpha+\\beta}{|f(x)|^p\\over\\alpha^p}+{\\beta\\over\\alpha+\\beta}{|g(x)|^p\\over\\beta^p}\\]\r\nintegrate the above to get\r\n\\[(\\|f+g\\|_p)^p\\leq(\\alpha+\\beta)^p({\\alpha\\over\\alpha+\\beta}\\cdot1+{\\beta\\over\\alpha+\\beta}\\cdot1)=(\\|f\\|_p+\\|g\\|_p)^p\\]',679),(306,'','The function \\(t\\mapsto\\log t\\) is concave on \\((0,\\infty)\\) because its second derivative \\({-1\\over t^2}\\lt0\\). So\r\n\\[s,t\\gt0\\ \\Longrightarrow\\ {1\\over p}\\log s+{1\\over q}t\\leq\\log({s\\over p}+{t\\over q})\\]\r\nExponentiating,\r\n\\[s^{1\\over p}t^{1\\over q}\\leq{s\\over p}+{t\\over q}\\]\r\nTaking \\(s=({|f(x)|\\over\\|f\\|_p})^p\\) and \\(t=({|g(x)|\\over\\|g\\|_p})^q\\) we get\r\n\\[{|f(x)g(x)|\\over\\|f\\|_p\\|g\\|_q}\\leq{|f(x)|^p\\over p(\\|f\\|_p)^p}+{|g(x)|^q\\over q(\\|g\\|_q)^q}\\]\r\nIntegrating this gives the result.',680),(307,'','Apply Holder\'s inequality with \\(|f|^{p_1}\\) and \\(\\chi_{(a,b)}\\), with \\(p={p_2\\over p_1}\\) and \\(q={p_2\\over p_2-p_1}\\)',681),(308,'','<ol>\r\n<li>Consider \\(f_n(x)=n^2x^n(1-x)\\) on \\([0,1]\\), then \\(f_n(x)\\to0\\) everywhere but \\(\\|f_n\\|_1\\to1\\)<br/>\r\n<br/>\r\n</li>\r\n<li>For \\(n=2^r+k\\) where \\(k=0,1,2,...,2^r-1\\), \\(r=0,1,2,...\\). Let \\(f_n=\\chi_[k2^{-r},(k+1)2^{r-1}]\\)<br/>\r\nThen this enumerates regions from \\([0,1]\\), where every point appears in infinitely many regions and also not in infinitely many regions. Hence \\(\\|f_n\\|_1=2^{-r}\\to0\\) but for each \\(x\\in[0,1]\\) the limit does not exist.\r\n</li>\r\n</ol>',682),(309,'','Make a truth table for each one.',687),(310,'','The proof is by induction on the length of the derivation of \\(F\\doteq G\\). If the derivation has length one then \\(F\\doteq G\\) is either an instance of the identity rule or an axiom. In the first case we clearly have \\(F\\equiv G\\) and in the second case we use the earlier proposition. If \\(F\\doteq G\\) follows from previous equations by either symmetry or transitivity, then we have \\(F\\equiv G\\) by the induction hypothesis and the fact that logical equivalence is both a symmetric and transitive relation on formulae. Finally, if \\(F\\doteq G\\) follows from a previous equation by the substitution rule, then \\(F\\equiv G\\) by the induction hypothesis and the substitution theorem.',688),(311,'','We can transform a formula \\(F\\) into an equivalent CNF formula using equational reasoning as follows:\r\n<ol>\r\n<li>Substitute in \\(F\\) every occurrence of a sub formula of the form\r\n\\[\\begin{array}{rcl}\r\n\\lnot\\lnot G&&by&&G\\\\\r\n\\lnot(G\\land H)&&by&&(\\lnot G\\lor\\lnot H)\\\\\r\n\\lnot(G\\lor H)&&by&&(\\lnot G\\land\\lnot H)\\\\\r\n\\lnot true&&by&&false\\\\\r\n\\lnot false&&by&&true\r\n\\end{array}\\]\r\nuntil no such formulae occur. So we have pushed all negations inwards so negation is only applied to propositional variables.\r\n<br/><br/></li>\r\n<li>Substitute in \\(F\\) every occurrence of a sub formula of the form\r\n\\[\\begin{array}{rcl}\r\nF\\lor(G\\land H)&&by&&(F\\lor G)\\land(F\\lor H)\\\\\r\n(F\\land G)\\lor H&&by&&(F\\lor H)\\land(G\\lor H)\r\n\\end{array}\\]\r\nuntil no such formulae occur. So we have pushed all disjunctions inwards.\r\n<br/><br/></li>\r\n<li>Use the identity and zero laws to remove \\(false\\) from any clause and the delete all clauses containing \\(true\\)</li>\r\n</ol>\r\nThe resulting formula is then in CNF.<br/>\r\n<br/>\r\nThe translation to DNF has the same first step but then use\r\n\\[\\begin{array}{rcl}\r\nF\\land(G\\lor H)&&by&&(F\\land G)\\lor(F\\land H)\\\\\r\n(F\\lor G)\\land H&&by&&(F\\land H)\\lor(G\\land H)\r\n\\end{array}\\]\r\nand then use the identity and zero laws to remove \\(true\\) from any clause and the delete all clauses containing \\(false\\).',690),(312,'','It can be seen from the previous proposition that there is an equational derivation of \\(F\\doteq G\\) for some \\(G\\) in CNF. Thus it is enough to prove that there is an equational derivation of \\(G\\doteq true\\). In fact, using the identity law for conjugation, it is enough to show that there is an equational derivation of \\(C\\doteq true\\) for each clause \\(C\\) of \\(G\\).<br/>\r\n<br/>\r\nSince \\(F\\) is valid we know that the CNF formula \\(G\\) is also valid, so each clause of \\(G\\) is valid. Clearly a valid clause \\(C\\) must contain two complementary literals. But in this case we can find a derivation of \\(C\\doteq true\\) using the complementation law and the zero law for disjunction.',691),(313,'','Notice that \\(G\\lor\\lnot F\\) is valid. Thus by the previous proposition there is an equational derivation of \\(G\\lor\\lnot F\\doteq true\\). Then we have the following derivation\r\n\\[\\begin{array}{rcl}\r\nF&&\\doteq&&F\\land true\\\\\r\n&&\\doteq&&F\\land(G\\lor\\lnot F)\\\\\r\n&&\\doteq&&(F\\land G)\\lor(F\\land\\lnot F)\\\\\r\n&&\\doteq&&(F\\land G)\\lor false\\\\\r\n&&\\doteq&&F\\land G\r\n\\end{array}\\]\r\nWe can similarly obtain a derivation of \\(G\\doteq F\\land G\\). Combining the two, we get a derivation of \\(F\\doteq G\\).',692),(314,'','The algorithm certainly terminates as each iteration of the loop adds a new element to \\(T\\). This observation also shows that the algorithm runs in polynomial time in the size of the input formula.<br/>\r\n<br/>\r\nIf the algorithm returns an assignment \\(T\\), then \\(T\\) must satisfy \\(F\\) since the termination condition of the while loop is that all clauses are satisfied by \\(T\\). It remains to show that if the algorithm returns \\(UNSAT\\) then the input formula \\(F\\) really is unsatisfiable. To show this, suppose that \\(T\'\\) is an assignment that satisfies \\(F\\). We claim that the statement \\(T\\subset T\'\\) is a loop invariant. The initialisation \\(T=\\emptyset\\) establishes the invariant. To see that the invariant is maintained by an iteration of the main loop, consider an implication \\(F_1\\land...\\land F_k\\to G\\) that is not satisfied by \\(T\\). Then \\(T\\) must satisfy \\(F_1,F_2,...,F_k\\). Since \\(T\\subset T\'\\), \\(T\'\\) also satisfies \\(F_1,F_2,...,F_k\\) and hence \\(T\'\\) satisfies \\(G\\). We conclude that \\(G\\) cannot be the formula \\(false\\) and therefore the algorithm does not return \\(UNSAT\\). Moreover \\(G\\in T\'\\), so the assignment \\(T=T\\cup\\{G\\}\\) preserves the invariant.<br/>\r\n<br/>\r\nThe last argument shows that given a satisfiable Horn formula \\(F\\), the algorithm returns the minimum model of \\(F\\).',694),(315,'','Consider the following algorithm:<br/>\r\n<br/>\r\n<b>Input:</b> 2-CNF formula \\(F\\)<br/>\r\n\\(A=empty\\ valuation\\)<br/>\r\n<b>while</b> there is some unassigned variable <b>do</b><br/>\r\n&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;pick a literal \\(L\\) for which there is no path from \\(L\\) to \\(\\overline L\\), set \\(A(L)=1\\)<br/>\r\n&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;<b>while</b> there is an edge \\((M,N)\\) with \\(A(M)=1\\) and \\(A(N)\\) undefined <b>do</b><br/>\r\n&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;set \\(A(N)=1\\)<br/>\r\n<b>return</b> \\(A\\)<br/>\r\n<br/><br/><br/>\r\nSuppose that \\(G\\) is not consistent, so there exists \\(P\\) such that there\'s a path from \\(P\\) to \\(\\lnot P\\) and from \\(\\lnot P\\) to \\(P\\). Then for any assignment \\(A\\) that satisfies \\(F\\) we must have \\(A(P)\\leq A(\\lnot P)\\) and \\(A(\\lnot P)\\leq A(P)\\), byt then \\(A(P)=A(\\lnot P)\\) which is a contradiction. Thus \\(F\\) must be unsatisfiable.<br/>\r\n<br/>\r\nConversely, suppose that \\(G\\) is consistent. We construct a satisfying truth assignment incrementally, starting with the empty assignment and maintaining the invariant that the successor of any true node is also true. To do this we repeat the following step until all variables are assigned. Pick an unassigned literal \\(L\\) such that there is no path from \\(L\\) to \\(\\overline L\\) and assign \\(1\\) to all literals that are reachable from \\(L\\). Note that this step is well-defined since if there were a pair of complementary literals \\(M\\) and \\(\\overline M\\) reachable from \\(L\\), then there would be paths from \\(L\\) to \\(M\\) and from \\(M\\) to \\(\\overline L\\), contradicting the assumption that there is no path from \\(L\\) to \\(\\overline L\\). This step, is also consistent with previous assignments since if there were a path from \\(L\\) to any node already assigned \\(false\\) then \\(L\\) would also already have been \\(false\\), contradicting the assumption that \\(L\\) is unassigned. Finally the step clearly preserves the invariant. Since we assume that \\(G\\) is consistent, we can perform the above step until all literals are assigned, in which case we have a satisfying valuation.',697),(316,'','Let \\(F\\) be an arbitrary formula, we\'ll construct a 3-CNF formula \\(G\\) that is equisatisfiable to \\(F\\).<br/>\r\n<br/>\r\nLet \\(F_1,F_2,...,F_n\\) be a list of the subformulae of \\(F\\), with \\(F_n\\) being \\(F\\) itself. Corresponding to each subformula \\(F_i\\) we introduce a propositional variable \\(Q_i\\), where \\(Q_i\\) does no already appear in \\(F\\). Then for each \\(1\\leq i\\leq n\\) we include a clause \\(G_i\\) in \\(G\\) whose job is to ensure that the variable \\(Q_i\\) has the same truth value as the subformula \\(F_i\\). We define\r\n\\[G=G_1\\land G_2\\land...\\land G_n\\land Q_n\\]\r\nwhere the 3-CNF formulae \\(G_i\\) are defined according to the outermost connective of \\(F_i\\) as follows.\r\n<ul>\r\n<li><b>Disjunction:</b> If \\(F_i=F_j\\lor F_k\\) then we define \\(G_i\\) to be a 3-CNF formula that is logically equivalent to \\(Q_i\\leftrightarrow Q_j\\lor Q_k\\). This is achieved by writing\r\n\\[G_i=(\\lnot Q_i\\lor Q_j\\lor Q_k)\\land(\\lnot Q_j\\lor Q_i)\\land(\\lnot Q_k\\lor Q_i)\\]\r\n</li>\r\n<li><b>Conjunction:</b> If \\(F_i=F_j\\land F_k\\) then we define \\(G_i\\) to be a 3-CNF formula that is logically equivalent to \\(Q_i\\leftrightarrow Q_j\\land Q_k\\). This is achieved by writing\r\n\\[G_i=(\\lnot Q_i\\lor Q_j)\\land(\\lnot Q_i\\lor Q_k)\\land(\\lnot Q_j\\lor\\lnot Q_k\\lor Q_i)\\]\r\n</li>\r\n<li><b>Negation:</b> If \\(F_i=\\not F_j\\) the we define \\(G_i\\) to be a 3-CNF formula logically equivalent to \\(Q_i\\leftrightarrow\\lnot Q_j\\). This is achieved by writing\r\n\\[G_i=(\\lnot Q_i\\lor\\lnot Q_j)\\land(Q_j\\lor Q_i)\\]\r\n</li>\r\n<li><b>Propositional variable:</b> If \\(F_i=P\\) is a propositional variable then we define \\(G_i\\) to be a 3-CNF logically equivalent to \\(Q_i\\leftrightarrow P\\). This is achieved by writing\r\n\\[G_i=(\\lnot P\\lor Q_i)\\land(\\lnot Q_i\\lor P)\\]\r\n</li>\r\n</ul>\r\n<br/><br/>\r\nIt only remains to note that if we could solve any 3-CNF in polynomial time, then we can solve any arbitrary formula. Therefore 3-CNFs cannot be solved quickly.',698),(317,'','One direction of the theorem is obvious: if \\(S\\) is satisfiable then every finite subset is certainly satisfiable. The non-trivial part of the proof is the converse.<br/>\r\n<br/>\r\nGiven a set of formulae \\(S\\), we say that a partial assignment \\(A\\) is good if it satisfies any formula \\(F\\in S\\) that only mentions propositional variables in the domain of \\(A\\). We first observe that for each \\(n\\in\\mathbb N\\) there is a partial assignment \\(A\\) with \\(dom(A)=\\{P_1,...,P_n\\}\\) that is good. To see this, consider the subset \\(S\'\\subset S\\) containing all formulas that mention only propositional variables \\(P_1,...,P_n\\). Now \\(S\'\\) may be an infinite set, but it only contains finitely many formulae up to logical equivalence. Since all finite subsets of \\(S\\) are satisfiable we conclude that \\(S\'\\) is satisfiable by some partial assignment \\(A\\) with \\(dom(A)=\\{P_1,...,P_n\\}\\). By construction such an assignment is good.<br/>\r\n<br/>\r\nThe central idea of the proof is to construct a sequence of good partial assignments \\(A_0,A_1,A_2,...\\) such that \\(dom(A_n)=\\{P_1,...,P_n\\}\\) and \\(A_{n+1}\\) extends \\(A_n\\) for each \\(n\\). We construct the \\(A_n\\) in sequence, starting with \\(A_0\\) and maintaining the condition that there are infinitely many good partial assignments that extend \\(A_n\\).<br/>\r\n<br/>\r\nFor the base step we define \\(A_0\\) to be the assignment with empty domain. Since for every \\(n\\) there is a good assignment with domain \\(\\{P_1,...,P_n\\}\\), there are infinitely many good assignments that extend \\(A_0\\).<br/>\r\n<br/>\r\nFor the inductive step, suppose that we have constructed assignments \\(A_0,...,A_n\\) such that \\(A_n\\) satisfies the invariant. Consider the two assignments \\(B,B\'\\) that extend \\(A_n\\) with \\(dom(B)=dom(B\')=\\{P_1,...,P_n,P_{n+1}\\}\\) where \\(B(P_{n+1})=0\\) and \\(B(P_{n+1})=1\\). Since any proper extension of \\(A_n\\) is an extension of either \\(B\\) or \\(B\'\\), it follows that at least one has of \\(B\\) and \\(B\'\\) has infinitely many good extensions. Define \\(A_{n+1}\\) to be the one that does.<br/>\r\n<br/>\r\nNow there is a unique total assignment \\(A\\) that extends all the \\(A_n\\). By construction \\(A\\) satisfies all formulae in \\(S\\).',700),(318,'','Let \\(A\\) be an assignment. It is obvious that if \\(A\\models F\\cup\\{R\\}\\) then \\(A\\models F\\). We argue that the converse also holds. Suppose \\(A\\models F\\) and write \\(R=(C_1\\setminus\\{L\\})\\cup(C_2\\setminus\\{\\overline L\\})\\) for some literal \\(L\\), where \\(L\\in C_1\\) and \\(\\overline L\\in C_2\\). There are two cases:\r\n<ul>\r\n<li><b>Case 1:</b> If \\(A\\models L\\) then since \\(A\\models C_2\\) it follows that \\(A\\models C_2\\setminus\\{\\overline L\\}\\) and thus \\(A\\models R\\)</li>\r\n<li><b>Case 1:</b> If \\(A\\models \\overline L\\) then since \\(A\\models C_1\\) it follows that \\(A\\models C_1\\setminus\\{L\\}\\) and thus \\(A\\models R\\)</li>\r\n</ul>',703),(319,'','Suppose that \\(C_1,C_2,...,C_m=\\square\\) is a proof of \\(\\square\\) from \\(F\\). By repeated applications of the resolution lemma we have that \\(F\\) is equivalent to \\(F\\cup\\{C_1,C_2,...,C_m\\}\\). But the latter set of clauses contains the empty clause and thus is unsatisfiable.',705),(320,'','The proof is by induction on the number \\(n\\) of different propositional variables in \\(F\\).<br/>\r\n<br/>\r\n<ul>\r\n<li><b>Base case:</b> If \\(n=0\\), so \\(F\\) does not mention any propositional variables, then \\(F\\) either contains no clauses or it contains only the empty clause. In the former case \\(F\\) is equivalent to \\(true\\) and in the latter we have \\(\\square\\in F\\) so trivially \\(\\square\\in Res^*(F)\\).<br/><br/></li>\r\n<li><b>Inductive step:</b> Suppose that \\(F\\) is an unsatisfiable set of clauses that mentions variables \\(P_1,P_2,...,P_n\\) and let \\(F_0=F[false/P_n]\\) and \\(F_1=F[true/P_n]\\).<br/>\r\n<br/>\r\nSince \\(F\\) is unsatisfiable, \\(F_0\\) is also unsatisfiable. Moreover \\(F_0\\) mentions one fewer variable than \\(F\\) so by the induction hypothesis there is a resolution proof \\(C_0,C_1,...,C_m=\\square\\) that derives the empty clause from \\(F_0\\). For each clause \\(C_i\\) in the above proof that comes from \\(F_0\\), either \\(C_i\\) is already in \\(F\\) or \\(C_i\\cup\\{P_n\\}\\) is in \\(F\\). By replacing the deleted copies of \\(P_n\\) from the latter type of clauses and propagating \\(P_n\\) through the proof we obtain a new proof \\(C_0\',C_1\',...,C_m\'\\) from \\(F\\), where either \\(C_m\'=\\square\\) or \\(C_m\'=\\{P_n\\}\\). In the first case there\'s nothing left to prove, so consider the second case. Applying similar reasoning to \\(F_1\\) we can assume that there is a proof of \\(\\{\\lnot P_n\\}\\) from \\(F\\). Gluing the two proofs and applying one more resolution step to \\(\\{P_n\\}\\) and \\(\\{\\lnot P_n\\}\\) gives a proof of \\(\\square\\) from \\(F\\)</li>\r\n</ul>',707),(321,'','The cases for when \\(P\\) appears only positively or only negatively in \\(F\\) are straightforward. Then if \\(A\\models F[true/P]\\) then \\(A[P\\mapsto1]\\models F\\) and if \\(A\\models F[false/P]\\) then \\(A[P\\mapsto0]\\models F\\).<br/>\r\n<br/>\r\nFor the case where \\(P\\) occurs both positively and negatively, we need to show that if \\(F\\) is satisfiable then \\(G\\) is satisfiable. Indeed, this follows from the resolution lemma, since \\(G\\subset F\\cup Res(F)\\). Next we show that if \\(G\\) is satisfiable then \\(F\\) is satisfiable. To this end, suppose that \\(A\\) is an assignment satisfying \\(G\\). For every clause \\(C\\in F\\) that does not mention \\(P\\) we have \\(C\\in G\\) and hence \\(A(C)=1\\). Thus any such clause \\(C\\) is satisfied by both \\(A[P\\mapsto0]\\) and \\(A[P\\mapsto1]\\). It remains to consider clauses in (F\\) that mention \\(P\\). We consider two cases. First suppose that \\(A\\) satisfies every clause \\(C\\) such that \\(C\\cup\\{P\\}\\in F\\). Then clearly \\(A[P\\mapsto0]\\models F\\). The remaining case is that \\(A\\) fails to satisfy some clause \\(C\\) for which \\(C\\cup\\{P\\}\\in F\\). Consider any clause \\(D\\) such that \\(D\\cup\\{\\lnot P\\}\\in F\\), since \\(C\\cup D\\in G\\) we must have \\(A(D)=1\\). Thus defining \\(A[P\\mapsto1]\\models F\\).',709),(322,'','Suppose that \\(G\\) has elimination sequence \\(G_0,G_1,...,G_n\\) of width \\(k\\) under a given vertex ordering. A run of the Davis-Putnam procedure under the same vertex ordering goes through a sequence of formulae \\(F_0,F_1,...,F_n\\) with \\(F_0=F\\) and \\(F_n\\) is either \\(true\\) or \\(false\\). Now it is easy to show by induction on \\(i\\) that all cliques in \\(G_i\\) have size at most \\(k+1\\). Also, al cliques in the primal graph of \\(F_i\\) have size at most \\(k+1\\). But each clause in \\(F_i\\) induces a clique in the primal graph, thus each such clause has at most \\(k+1\\) literals.',711),(323,'','Just rename bound variables to something else.',718),(324,'','Use the quantifier identities to push all quantifiers to the front.',719),(325,'','We convert an arbitrary first order formula \\(F\\) to an equisatisfiable Skolem form formula as follows:\r\n<ol>\r\n<li>Rectify \\(F\\) be systematically renaming bound variables, yielding formula \\(F_1\\)</li>\r\n<li>Using the quantifier identities, move all the quantifiers in \\(F_1\\) to the outside, yielding an equivalent formula \\(F_2\\) in rectified prenex form.</li>\r\n<li>Repeatedly eliminate the outermost existential quantifier in \\(F_2\\) until an equisatisfiable formula \\(F_3\\) in Skolem form is obtained.</li>\r\n</ol>',721),(326,'','The proof is by structural induction over terms. The base case is that \\(t\\) is a constant symbol \\(c\\), then \\(H(c)=c\\) by definition of a Herbrand structure. The induction step is that \\(t\\) has the form \\(f(t_1,...,t_k)\\) for a \\(k\\)-ary function symbol \\(f\\) and ground terms \\(t_1,...,t_k\\). Then\r\n\\[\\begin{array}{rl}\r\nH(f(t_1,..,t_k))&&=f_H(H(t_1),...,H(t_k))\\\\\r\n&&=f_H(t_1,...,t_k)\\ \\text{inductive step}\\\\\r\n&&=f(t_1,...,t_k)\\ \\text{definition of}\\ \\ f_H\r\n\\end{array}\\]',723),(327,'','By the version of the translation lemma proved earlier we have \\(H(F[t/x])=H[x\\mapsto H(t)](F)\\). But by the previous proposition, we have \\(H(t)=t\\). The result follows.',724),(328,'','If \\(F\\) has a Herbrand model then it is clearly satisfiable.<br/>\r\n<br/>\r\nConversely, suppose that \\(F\\) is satisfied by some structure \\(A\\). Then we show that \\(F\\) has a Herbrand model \\(H\\). To define \\(H\\) it suffices to define the interpretation of the predicate symbols since the interpretation of the constants, function symbols and the universe are already determined. The idea is to define \\(H\\) to mimic \\(A\\). To this end, given a \\(k\\)-ary predicate symbol \\(P\\) we define \\((t_1,...,t_k)\\in P_H\\) if and only if \\(A\\models P(t_1,...,t_k)\\).<br/>\r\n<br/>\r\nWe claim that all closed formulae \\(G=\\forall y_1...\\forall y_kG^*\\) in Skolem form, if \\(A\\models G\\) then \\(H\\models H\\). It follows from this that \\(H\\models F\\). The proof of the claim is by induction on the number of quantifiers \\(k\\).<br/>\r\n<br/>\r\nThe base case is that \\(k=0\\). Since \\(G\\) is closed it is a boolean combination of atomic formulae \\(P(t_1,...,t_k)\\) for ground terms \\(t_1,...,t_k\\). But, by construction, \\(A\\) and \\(H\\) assign the same truth value to each such atom. Thus \\(A\\models G\\) implies \\(H\\models G\\).<br/>\r\n<br/>\r\nThe induction step is as follows. Suppose \\(A\\models\\forall yG\\). We cannot directly apply the induction hypothesis to \\(G\\) since it is not closed. However by the translation lemma we have that \\(A(G[t/y])=A[y\\mapsto A(t)](G)=1\\), thus \\(A\\models G[t/y]\\) for all closed terms \\(t\\). Now we can apply the induction hypothesis and conclude that \\(H\\models G[t/y]\\) for all closed terms \\(t\\). But now by the translation lemma for Herbrand models we have that \\(H[t/y]\\models G\\) for all closed terms \\(t\\), hence \\(H\\models\\forall yG\\).',725),(329,'','By Herbrand\'s theorem a formula in Skolem form is satisfiable if and only if it has a Herbrand model. Thus it suffices to show that \\(F\\) has a Herbrand model if and only if \\(E(F)\\) is satisfiable considered as a set of propositional formulae. Let \\(F\\) have the form \\(\\forall x_1...\\forall x_nF^*\\). Given a Herbrand structure \\(A\\) we have<br/>\r\n<br/>\r\n\\(A\\models F\\)<br/>\r\n\\(\\Longleftrightarrow\\ A[t_1/x_1]...[t_n/x_n]\\models F^*\\) for all \\(t_1,...,t_n\\in U_A\\)<br/>\r\n\\(\\Longleftrightarrow\\ A[t_1/x_1]...[t_n/x_n]\\models F^*\\) for all ground \\(\\sigma\\)-terms \\(t_1,...,t_n\\)<br/>\r\n\\(\\Longleftrightarrow\\ A\\models F^*[t_1/x_1]...[t_n/x_n]\\) by the translation lemma for Herbrand models<br/>\r\n\\(\\Longleftrightarrow\\ A\\models E(F)\\)<br/>\r\n<br/>\r\nObserve that the last sentence is true for some Herbrand structure \\(A\\) iff \\(E(F)\\) is satisfiable as a set of propositional formulae.',727),(330,'','By the compactness theorem of propositional logic \\(E(F)\\) is unsatisfiable if and only if there is some finite subset of \\(E(F)\\) that is unsatisfiable. By the soundness and completeness of propositional resolution this holds if and only if we can derive \\(\\square\\) from \\(E(F)\\) using resolution.',728),(331,'','We claim that the following algorithm determines whether a set of literals has a unifier and, if so, outputs a most general unifier.<br/>\r\n<br/>\r\n<b>Unification algorithm</b><br/>\r\n<b>Input:</b> Set of literals \\(L\\)<br/>\r\n<b>Output:</b> Either a most general unifier of \\(L\\) or FAIL<br/>\r\n\\(\\theta=\\) identity substitution<br/>\r\n<b>while</b> \\(\\theta\\) is not a unifier of \\(L\\)<br/>\r\n<b>begin</b><br/>\r\n&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;pick two distinct literals in \\(L\\theta\\) and find the left-most position at which they differ<br/>\r\n&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;<b>if</b> one of the corresponding sub-terms is a variable \\(x\\) and the other is a term \\(t\\)<br/>\r\n<b>then</b> \\(\\theta=\\theta\\cdot[t/x]\\) <b>else return</b> FAIL\r\n<b>end</b>\r\n<br/><br/><br/>\r\nWe argue termination as follows. In any iteration of the while loop that does not cause the program to halt, a variable \\(x\\) is substituted for a term \\(t\\) that does not contain \\(x\\). Thus the number of different variable occurring in \\(L\\theta\\) decreases by one in each iteration and the loop must terminate.<br/>\r\n<br/>\r\nThe loop invariant is that for any unifier \\(\\theta\'\\) of \\(L\\) we have \\(\\theta\'=\\theta\\cdot\\theta\'\'\\). Clearly the invariant is established by the initial assignment of the identity substitution to \\(\\theta\\). To see that invariant is maintained by an iteration of the loop, suppose we find an occurrence of variable \\(x\\) in a literal in \\(L\\theta\\) such that a different term \\(t\\) occurs in the same position in another literal in \\(L\\theta\\). From the invariant we deduce that any unifier \\(\\theta\'\\) of \\(L\\) must satisfy \\(\\theta\'(x)=\\theta\'(t)\\), hence \\(\\theta\'=[t/x]\\cdot\\theta\'\\). Thus the invariant is maintained by the assignment \\(\\theta=\\theta\\cdot[t/x]\\).<br/>\r\n<br/>\r\nThe termination condition of the while loop is that \\(\\theta\\) is a unifier of \\(L\\). In conjunction with the loop invariant this implies that the final value of \\(\\theta\\) is a most general unifier of \\(L\\). Finally, the invariant implies that if \\(\\theta\'\\) is a unifier of \\(L\\) then it is also a unifier of \\(L\\theta\\). But the algorithm only outputs FAIL if \\(L\\theta\\) has no unifier, in which case \\(L\\) has no unifier.',730),(332,'','Clearly any assignment that satisfies \\(\\forall(F^*\\cup Res(F^*))\\) must satisfy \\(F\\).<br/>\r\n<br/>\r\nConversely, suppose that \\(R\\) is a resolvant of clauses \\(C_1,C_2\\in F^*\\) with \\(\\theta\\) being the unifier used in the definition. Let \\(A\\) be an assignment that satisfies \\(\\forall C_1\\) and \\(\\forall C_2\\). We must show that \\(A\\) satisfies \\(\\forall R\\), that is that any variant assignment \\(A\'\\) satisfies \\(R\\). But \\(A\'\\) satisfies both \\(C_1\\theta\\) and \\(C_2\\theta\\) and satisfies as most one of the complementary literals \\(L_1\\theta\\) and \\(L_2\\theta\\). Thus \\(A\'\\) satisfies \\(R\\) as required.',732),(333,'','Repeatedly apply the resolution lemma.',733),(334,'','Let \\(C_1\'\'\\) and \\(C_2\'\'\\) be variable-disjoint renamings of \\(C_1\\) and \\(C_2\\), then \\(C_1\'\\) and \\(C_2\'\\) are ground instances of \\(C_1\'\'\\) and \\(C_2\'\'\\) and we can write \\(C_1\'\'=C_1\\theta_1\\) and \\(C_2\'\'=C_2\\theta_2\\) for ground substitutions \\(\\theta_1\\) and \\(\\theta_2\\).<br/>\r\n<br/>\r\nLet \\(L_1\\subset C_1\'\'\\) be the set of literals mapped to \\(L\\) by \\(\\theta_1\\) and let \\(L_2\\subset C_2\'\'\\) be the set of literals mapped to \\(\\overline L\\) by \\(\\theta_2\\). Then \\(\\theta_1\\theta_2\\) is a unifier of \\(L_1\\cup\\overline{L_2}\\). Writing \\(\\theta\\) for the most general unifier, we have that\r\n\\[R=(C_1\'\'\\theta\\setminus L_1\\theta)\\cup(C_2\'\'\\theta\\setminus L_2\\theta)\\]\r\nis a predicate-logic resolvant of \\(C_1\\) and \\(C_2\\)<br/>\r\n<br/>\r\nNow we know from the proof of the unification lemma that \\(\\theta_1\\theta_2=\\theta\\theta_1\\theta_2\\). Thus we have\r\n\\[C_1\'=C_1\'\'\\theta_1=C_1\'\'\\theta_1\\theta_2=C_1\'\'\\theta\\theta_1\\theta_2\\]\r\nand, using the face that \\(\\theta_1\\) and \\(\\theta_2\\) commute\r\n\\[C_2\'=C_2\'\'\\theta_2=C_2\'\'\\theta_1\\theta_2=C_2\'\'\\theta\\theta_1\\theta_2\\]\r\nIt follows that \\(R\'\\) is a ground instance of \\(R\\) under the substitution \\(\\theta_1\\theta_2\\)',734),(335,'','Suppose that \\(F\\) is unsatisfiable. By the completeness of ground resolution there is a proof \\(C_1\',C_2\',...,C_n\'\\) where \\(C_n\'=\\square\\) and each \\(C_i\'\\) is either a ground instance of a clause in \\(F^*\\) or is a resolvant of two clauses \\(C_j\',C_k\'\\) for \\(j,k\\lt i\\). We inductively define a corresponding predicate-logic resolution proof \\(C_1,C_2,...,C_n\\) such that \\(C_i\'\\) is a ground instance of \\(C_i\\). For each \\(i\\), if \\(C_i\'\\) is a ground instance of a clause \\(C\\in F^*\\) then define \\(C_i=C\\). On the other hand, suppose that \\(C_i\\) is a resolvant of two ground clauses \\(C_j\',C_k\'\\) with \\(j,k\\lt i\\). By induction we have constructed clauses \\(C_j\\) and \\(C_k\\) such that \\(C_j\'\\) is a ground instance of \\(C_j\\) and \\(C_k\'\\) is a ground instance of \\(C_k\\). By the lifting lemma we can find a clause \\(C_i\\) which is a resolvant of \\(C_j\\) and \\(C_k\\) such that \\(C_i\'\\) is a ground instance of \\(C_i\\).',735),(336,'','\\((\\Leftarrow)\\) Suppose \\(m|h\\), well \\(h|a\\) and \\(h|b\\), so \\(m|a\\) and \\(m|b\\)<br/>\r\n\\((\\Rightarrow)\\) Suppose \\(m|a\\) and \\(m|b\\), write \\(h=ax+by\\), then \\(m|ax\\) and \\(m|by\\), so \\(m|h\\)',760),(337,'','\\[\\begin{array}{lll}\r\ne|{a\\over d},\\ e|{b\\over d}&&\\Rightarrow&&ed|a,\\ ed|b\\\\\r\n&&\\Rightarrow&&ed|d\\\\\r\n&&\\Rightarrow&&e|1\\\\\r\n&&\\Rightarrow&&e=1\r\n\\end{array}\\]\r\n\r\n\\[\\begin{array}{lll}\r\ne=(a+cb,b)&&\\Rightarrow&&e|a+cb,\\ e|b\\\\\r\n&&\\Rightarrow&&e|cb\\\\\r\n&&\\Rightarrow&&e|a\\\\\r\n&&\\Rightarrow&&e|(a,b)\r\n\\end{array}\\]\r\n\r\n\\[\\begin{array}{lll}\r\nf=(a,b)&&\\Rightarrow&&f|a,\\ f|b\\\\\r\n&&\\Rightarrow&&f|a+cb\\\\\r\n&&\\Rightarrow&&f|(a+cb,b)\\\\\r\n&&\\Rightarrow&&(a,b)=(a+cb,b)\r\n\\end{array}\\]',761),(338,'','(2nd part)<br/>\r\nSuppose \\((a,e)=1\\), then \\(e|b\\Rightarrow e|ab\\) and \r\n\\(e|ab\\Rightarrow b=b(ax+ey)=abx+bey\\ where\\ ax+ey=1\\Rightarrow e|b\\)',762),(339,'Proof by strong induction','For \\(n=1\\), \\(n\\) equals the empty product.<br/>\r\n<br/>\r\nFor \\(n+1\\), if \\(n\\) is prime then we\'re done, else \\(n\\) is composite so \\(n=ab\\) for some \\(a,b\\lt n+1\\). So \\(a,b\\) have expressions as products of primes, so \\(n+1\\) has an expression.<br/>\r\nFor the uniqueness, use the lemma that \\((a,e)=1\\Rightarrow(e|ab\\Leftrightarrow e|b)\\), so if \\(n=p_1...p_r=q_1...q_s\\) then each \\(p_i|q_j\\) for some \\(j\\), so the expression is unique up to ordering.',764),(340,'','\\((a,b)=1\\Leftrightarrow1=ab+nt\\Leftrightarrow n|ab-1\\Leftrightarrow ab\\cong 1\\)',771),(341,'','<ol>\r\n<li>\\(ax\\cong b\\ (mod\\ n)\\Leftrightarrow\\exists x,y\\ s.t.\\ ax-ny=b\\Leftrightarrow(a,n)|b\\)</li>\r\n<li>Let \\((a,n)=d\\), then \\(\\exists x_0,y_0\\ s.t.\\ ax_0+by_0=b\\). If there is another solution then \\(\\exists x,y\\ s.t.\\ ax-ny=b=ax_0-ny_0\\Leftrightarrow a(x_0-x)=n(y_0-y)\\Leftrightarrow{a\\over d}(x_0-x)={n\\over d}(y_0-y)\\). But as \\(({a\\over d},{n\\over d})=1\\), \\({n\\over d}|x_0-x,\\ {a\\over d}|y_0-y\\), so \\(x=x_0+{n\\over d}t,\\ y=y_0+{a\\over d}t\\). This gives distinct solutions for \\(t=0,1,...,d-1\\).<br/>\r\n<br/>\r\nConversely, for any \\(x=x_0+{n\\over d}t,\\ y=y_0+{a\\over d}t\\), then \\(ax-ny=b\\)</li>\r\n</ol>',772),(342,'','Define a ring homomorphism \\(\\phi:\\mathbb Z\\to{\\mathbb Z\\over m}\\times{\\mathbb Z\\over n}\\) by \\(x\\mapsto([x]_m,[x]_n)\\). Then \\(x\\in ker\\phi\\Leftrightarrow(x,mn)=1\\), so \\(ker\\phi=(mn)\\mathbb Z\\). Then \\({\\mathbb Z\\over mn}\\cong im\\phi\\) by the first isomorphism theorem. But then \\(|im\\phi|=mn=|{\\mathbb Z\\over m}\\times{\\mathbb Z\\over n}|\\).',773),(343,'non-constructive','Using \\({\\mathbb Z\\over mn}\\cong{\\mathbb Z\\over m}\\times{\\mathbb Z\\over n}\\) and induction, \\({\\mathbb Z\\over N}\\cong{\\mathbb Z\\over n_1}\\times...\\times{\\mathbb Z\\over n_t}\\) where \\(N=n_1...n_t\\). So as there is a bijection, \\(\\forall i,\\ x,x\'\\cong a_i\\ (mod\\ n_i)\\Leftrightarrow x\\cong c\'\\ (mod\\ N)\\).',774),(344,'constructive','Let \\(N_i={N\\over n_i}\\), then \\((N_i,n_i)=1\\) for all \\(i\\) as \\((n_i,n_j)=1\\) for all \\(i\\neq j\\).<br/>\r\nBy lemma, \\(\\exists x_i\\ s.t.\\ N_ix_i\\cong 1\\ (mod\\ n_i)\\), define \\(x=\\sum a_iN_ix_i\\). Then for all \\(i\\), \\(x\\cong a_iN_ix_i\\cong a_i\\ (mod\\ n_i)\\).<br/>\r\n<br/>\r\nIf \\(x\'\\) is another solution, then \\(x\\cong a_k\\cong x\'\\ (mod\\ n_k)\\Rightarrow n_k|x-x\'\\Rightarrow N|x-x\'\\)',774),(345,'','Remember Lagrange\'s theorem, that for a finite group \\(G\\) and \\(x\\in G\\), \\(x^{|G|}=e\\) where \\(e\\in G\\) is the identity element.<br/>\r\n<br/>\r\nThen consider the group of units \\(({\\mathbb Z\\over n})^\\times\\). \\([x]^{|({\\mathbb Z\\over n})^\\times|}=[1]\\) so \\(x^{\\phi(n)}=1\\ (mod\\ n)\\)',777),(346,'','<ol>\r\n<li>\\(n=p^e\\Rightarrow \\phi(n)\\)\r\n\\(=\\#\\{\\overbrace{1,2,...,p-1}^{p-1},\\overbrace{p+1,p+2,...,2p-1}^{p-1},...,p^e-1\\}=\\)\r\n\\(={p^e\\over p}(p-1)=p^e-p^{e-1}\\)</li>\r\n<li>\\(n=p_1^{e_1}...p_r^{e_r}\\Rightarrow \\phi(n)=\\#({\\mathbb Z\\over n})^\\times)\\)\r\n\\(=\\#(({\\mathbb Z\\over p_1^{e_1}})^\\times\\times...\\times({\\mathbb Z\\over p_r^{e_r}})^\\times)=\\phi(p_1^{e_1})...\\phi(p_r^{e_r})\\)\r\n\\(=n\\prod_{i=1}^r(p_i^{e_i}-p_i^{e_i-1})\\)</li>\r\n</ol>',779),(347,'','Let \\(S_d=\\{a\\in\\mathbb N:a\\leq n\\ and\\ (n,a)=d\\}\\), then \\(\\bigcup_{d|n}S_d=\\{1,...,n\\}\\). Then as \\(S_d\\cap S_{d\'}=\\emptyset\\) for \\(d\\neq d\'\\), \\(n=\\sum_{d|n}\\#S_d\\).<br/>\r\nNow note that \\((n,a)=d\\Leftrightarrow({n\\over d},{a\\over d})=1\\), so \\(\\#S_d=\\phi({n\\over d})\\). Then \\(n=\\sum_{d|n}\\phi({n\\over d})=\\sum_{d|n}\\phi(d)\\)',780),(348,'','Suppose \\(p\\) is composite, then \\((p,(p-1)!)\\neq1\\Rightarrow(p-1)!\\not\\in({\\mathbb Z\\over p})^\\times\\Rightarrow(p-1)!\\not\\cong-1\\ (mod\\ p)\\)<br/>\r\n<br/>\r\nSuppose \\(p\\) is prime, then \\(({\\mathbb Z\\over p})^\\times=\\{1,2,...,p-1\\}\\). Now we know \\(x^2-1\\) has at most two roots and they are \\(1\\) and \\(-1\\). Then all elements in \\(({\\mathbb Z\\over p})\\setminus\\{1,-1\\}\\) still pair off with their inverse. So \\([2][3]...[p-2]=[1]\\Rightarrow(p-1)!\\cong-1\\ (mod\\ p)\\).',782),(349,'','<ol>\r\n<li>\\(ord_n(a^u)\\) is the least natural number \\(k\\) s.t. \\(t|uk\\), hence \\(k={t\\over(t,u)}\\)</li>\r\n<li>\\(ord_n(r^u)={\\phi(n)\\over(\\phi(n),u)}\\) and this is \\(\\phi(n)\\Leftrightarrow(\\phi(n),u)=1\\)</li>\r\n</ol>',785),(350,'','Clearly \\((iii)\\Rightarrow(ii)\\Rightarrow(i)\\)<br/>\r\n<br/>\r\nRecall that \\(\\sum_{d|p-1}\\phi(d)=p-1\\), let \\(J_d=\\{a\\in\\mathbb N:a\\leq p-1,\\ ord_n(a)=d\\}\\), then \\(\\bigcup_{d|p-1}J_d=({\\mathbb Z\\over p})^\\times\\) and as \\(J_d\\cap J_{d\'}=\\emptyset\\) for \\(d\\neq d\'\\), \\(\\sum_{d|p-1}\\#J_d=p-1\\) which means it\'s enough to show that \\(\\#J_d\\leq\\phi(d)\\).<br/>\r\n<br/>\r\nSuppose \\(J_d=\\emptyset\\), then clearly \\(\\#J_d\\leq\\phi(d)\\). Suppose then that \\(J_d\\neq\\emptyset\\), so \\(\\exists a\\leq p-1\\ s.t.\\ ord_p(a)=d\\), so \\(\\langle[a]\\rangle\\subset({\\mathbb Z\\over p})^\\times\\) is a cyclic group of order \\(d\\). By Lagrange, elements of this group are the only solutions to \\(x^d-1\\cong0\\ (mod\\ p)\\). Now, we know that \\([a]^i\\) is a generator of \\(\\langle[a]\\rangle\\) iff \\((a,i)=1\\), so \\(\\exists\\phi(d)\\) elements of order \\(d\\) in \\(\\langle[a]\\rangle\\), so \\(\\#J_d\\leq\\phi(d)\\).',786),(351,'','Let \\(g\\) be a primitive root of \\(n\\), so \\(\\langle g\\rangle=({\\mathbb Z\\over n})^\\times\\), then \\(g^i\\cong g^j\\ (mod\\ n)\\Leftrightarrow\\phi(n)|i-j\\).<br/>\r\n<br/>\r\nDefine now the discrete logarithm, \\(l(x)\\) of \\(x\\) to the base \\(g\\ (mod\\ n)\\), such that \\(g^{l(x)}\\cong x\\ (mod\\ n)\\). As \\(g\\) is primitive, \\(l(x)\\) must exist for all \\((x,n)=1\\) and is unique when we require \\(l(x)\\lt\\phi(n)\\). Note that \\(l(xy)=l(x)+l(y)\\).<br/>\r\n<br/>\r\nAlso recall that \\(\\exists x\\in\\mathbb Z\\ s.t.\\ n|ax-b\\Leftrightarrow(a,n)|b\\)<br/>\r\n<br/>\r\nThen \\(\\exists x\\in\\mathbb Z\\ s.t.\\ x^k\\cong a\\ (mod\\ n)\\)\r\n\\(\\Leftrightarrow\\exists x\\ s.t.\\ (g^{l(x)})^k\\cong g^{l(a)}\\ (mod\\ n)\\)\r\n\\(\\Leftrightarrow\\phi(n)|kl(x)-l(a)\\)\r\n\\(\\Leftrightarrow(k,\\phi(n))|l(a)\\)\r\n\\(\\Leftrightarrow\\phi(n)|l(a){\\phi(n)\\over(\\phi(n),a)}\\)\r\n\\(\\Leftrightarrow g^{l(a){\\phi(n)\\over(\\phi(n),a)}}\\cong1\\ (mod\\ n)\\)\r\n\\(\\Leftrightarrow a^{\\phi(n)\\over(\\phi(n),a)}\\cong\\ (mod\\ n)\\)',788),(352,'','If \\(p\\vert a\\), then \\(\\left({a\\over p}\\right)=0\\) and also \\(p\\vert a^{p-1\\over2}\\) so \\(a^{p-1\\over2}\\cong0\\ (mod\\ p)\\)<br/>\r\n<br/>\r\nNow for \\(p\\not\\vert a\\), \\(a^{p-1}\\cong1\\Leftrightarrow0\\cong(a^{p-1\\over2})^2-1\\Leftrightarrow0\\cong(a^{p-1\\over2}-1)(a^{p-1\\over2}+1)\\ (mod\\ p)\\) So we know one of the above is congruent to \\(0\\).<br/>\r\n<br/>\r\nBut \\(a^{p-1\\over2}-1\\cong0\\Leftrightarrow a^{p-1\\over2}\\cong1\\Leftrightarrow\\left({a\\over p}\\right)=1\\) by earlier proposition.',791),(353,'','Assume that \\(p_1,...,p_N\\) is a complete list of said primes. Consider \\(L=(2p_1...p_N)^2+1\\), then \\(\\exists p\\) odd s.t. \\(p\\vert L\\) and \\(p\\neq p_i\\) for any \\(i\\). Then \\((2p_1...p_N)^2\\cong-1\\ (mod\\ p)\\Rightarrow\\left({-1\\over p}\\right)=1\\Rightarrow\\exists K\'\\ s.t\\ p=4K\'+1\\) by corollary, which is a contradiction.',793),(354,'','Proof of (iii):<br/>\r\nNote \\(\\left({ab\\over p}\\right)=0\\Leftrightarrow\\left({a\\over p}\\right)=0\\ or\\ \\left({a\\over p}\\right)=0\\)<br/>\r\nThen assuming \\((a,p)=(b,p)=1\\), then by Euler\'s criterion \\(\\left({ab\\over p}\\right)=(ab)^{p-1\\over2}=a^{p-1\\over 2}b^{p-1\\over2}=\\left({a\\over p}\\right)\\left({b\\over p}\\right)\\)',794),(355,'','\\(({\\mathbb Z\\over p})^\\times=\\langle g\\rangle\\) for some primitive root \\(g\\), so \\(\\left({g\\over p}\\right)=g^{p-1\\over2}=\\pm1\\ (mod\\ p)\\). But \\(o(g)=p-1\\) so \\(g^{p-1\\over2}\\neq1\\), hence \\(\\left({g\\over p}\\right)=-1\\). But now \\(\\left({a\\over p}\\right)=\\left({g^{l(a)}\\over p}\\right)=\\left({g\\over p}\\right)^{l(a)}=(-1)^{l(a)}\\). As \\(l(a)\\) is 1-1 on \\(({\\mathbb Z\\over p})^\\times\\), \\((-1)^{l(a)}\\) is half the time \\(+1\\) and half the time \\(-1\\), so \\(\\sum_{i=1}^{p-1}\\left({a\\over p}\\right)=0\\)',795),(356,'','\\(r_i=p-s_j\\Leftrightarrow K_1=p-K\'a\\Leftrightarrow(K=K\')a\\cong p\\Leftrightarrow K+K\'\\cong0\\) but \\(K,K\'\\in\\{1,...,{p-1\\over2}\\}\\Rightarrow K+K\'\\in\\{1,...,p-1\\}\\Rightarrow K+K\'\\not\\cong0\\Rightarrow r_i\\neq p-s_j\\)',798),(357,'','\\(1\\times2\\times...\\times{p-1\\over2}\\cong r_1r_2...r_m(p-s_1)(p-s_2)...(p-s_n)\\)\r\n\\(\\cong r_1...r_ms_1...s_n(-1)^n\\cong a\\times2a\\times...\\times{p-1\\over2}a(-1)^n\\)\r\n\\(\\cong1\\times2\\times...\\times{p-1\\over2}(-1)^n\\)\r\n\\(\\Rightarrow a^{p-1\\over2}\\cong(-1)^n\\Rightarrow\\left({a\\over p}\\right)=(-1)^n\\) By Euler\'s criterion',799),(358,'','By Gauss\' lemma, \\(\\left({2\\over p}\\right)=(-1)^n\\) where \\(n=\\#\\{j\\in\\mathbb N:1\\leq j\\leq{p-1\\over2}\\ and\\ \\overline{2j}\\gt{p\\over2}\\}\\)\r\n\\(=\\#\\{1\\leq j\\leq{p-1\\over2}\\}-\\#\\{1\\leq j\\leq{p-1\\over2}:\\overline j\\lt{p\\over4}\\}\\)\r\n\\(={p-1\\over2}-\\left\\lfloor{p\\over4}\\right\\rfloor\\)<br/>\r\n<br/>\r\nThen we look at the cases:\r\n<ul>\r\n<li>\\(p=8k+1\\Rightarrow n=4k-2k=2k\\) which is even.</li>\r\n<li>\\(p=8k-1\\Rightarrow n=4k-1-(2k-1)=2k\\) which is even.</li>\r\n<li>\\(p=8k+3\\Rightarrow n=4k+1-2k=2k+1\\) which is odd.</li>\r\n<li>\\(p=8k-3\\Rightarrow n=4k-2-(2k-1)=2k-1\\) which is odd.</li>\r\n</ul>',800),(359,'','Write \\(\\overline x=x-pk\\) where \\(k=\\left\\lfloor{x\\over p}\\right\\rfloor\\). Then \\(\\sum_{i=1}^mr_i+\\sum_{i=1}^ns_i=\\sum_{j=1}^{p-1\\over2}\\overline{a_j}=\\sum_{j=1}^{p-1\\over2}(a_j-\\left\\lfloor{a_j\\over p}\\right\\rfloor)\\)\r\n\\(\\cong\\sum_{j=1}^{p-1\\over2}j-\\sum_{j=1}^{p-1\\over2}\\left\\lfloor{a_j\\over p}\\right\\rfloor\\ (mod\\ 2)\\) as \\(2\\not\\vert a\\)\r\n\\(\\Leftrightarrow\\sum_{j=1}^{p-1\\over2}j\\cong\\sum_{i=1}^mr_i-\\sum_{i=1}^ns_i+np\\ (mod\\ 2)\\)\r\n\\(\\Leftrightarrow n\\cong\\sum_{i=1}^mr_i-\\sum_{i=1}^ns_i+\\sum_{j=1}^{p-1\\over2}j\\cong2\\sum_{j=1}^{p-1\\over2}j-\\sum_{j=1}^{p-1\\over2}\\left\\lfloor{a_j\\over p}\\right\\rfloor\\cong\\sum_{j=1}^{p-1\\over2}\\left\\lfloor{a_j\\over p}\\right\\rfloor\\ (mod\\ 2)\\)<br/>\r\nThen by Gauss\' lemma, \\(\\left({a\\over p}\\right)=(-1)^n=(-1)^e\\) where \\(e=\\sum_{j=1}^{p-1\\over2}\\left\\lfloor{a_j\\over p}\\right\\rfloor\\)',801);
